JEFFERSON CITY — Just a year after moving into the governor’s mansion, Republican Mike Parson is poised to depart the capital city landmark.The move, however, is temporary as workers embark on a $3.3 million renovation project that will upgrade the heating and cooling system, fix longstanding plumbing problems and restore interior surfaces.That means new digs for Parson and his wife, Theresa, when they are in town.

Beginning on June 10, they will move into existing housing at the Missouri National Guard compound east of Jefferson City. While the housing unit is perched above the Missouri River like the mansion, it is not within walking distance of the Capitol building.Repairs to the mansion follow a 2016 report that noted the 147-year-old home needs upward of $4.3 million in repairs, including replacement of columns on the home’s sun porch, electrical upgrades, and replacement of the heating and cooling system.The report said all repairs could be made in one year if the governor and his family were to live somewhere else.According to the briefing paper, the interior plaster, paint and flooring of the mansion need to be repaired at an estimated cost of $500,000.“This is a necessary project as the interior plaster on the first floor is flaking and falling,” the document says. “In addition, the existing paint is lead-based and would require a hazardous remediation project. While this work would be occurring, it would be necessary for the family to not be in the residence.”The three-story brick building was first occupied by Gov. Benjamin Gratz Brown in 1872. The first floor includes a 17-foot-high Great Hall, two parlors, a library and a divided dining room. It has 13 bedrooms on the second and third floors.
Parson’s move to a temporary home is similar to what former Illinois Gov. Bruce Rauner did in 2015 when the mansion in Springfield was shuttered for $15 million in renovations and upgrades.Rauner and his wife, Diana, lived in a house on the Illinois State Fairgrounds when they were in the capital city.Unlike Illinois, the money paying for the repairs is not from private sources, but from a bond issue the state conducted in 2014. Parson was the sponsor of the legislation.
Some work has already been completed, including the replacement of boilers in the basement.The heating and cooling system will be the biggest undertaking in the project. The mansion has multiple systems installed between 1965 and 2008 that are not integrated between 1965 and 2008.That has left some parts of the building more humid than others, resulting in water damage in some areas of the house, including the first-floor parlor.Pipes that have rusted and clogged and caused damage to walls and floors also will be replaced.Other work includes upgrades to electrical service and fire alarm systems. An exterior fountain also will be repaired.


