UPDATES with filibuster hitting 20 hour markJEFFERSON CITY — The final week of the Legislature’s annual session got off to a bumpy start Monday as opponents of giving General Motors state tax dollars to expand in Wentzville used their filibuster powers to delay action in the upper chamber.Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring, used stalling tactics to chew up three hours of valuable debate time as he outlined why he is trying to block a $50 million-plus incentive package being pushed by fellow Republican Gov. Mike Parson.

In particular, Eigel said he’s upset the legislation is being sponsored by Sen. Lincoln Hough, R-Springfield, and not by himself or Sen. Bob Onder, R-Lake Saint Louis, whose district includes the factory and many of its workers.“This is a bill that has a direct impact on my district,” said Eigel, adding that some of his own family members work on the truck and van assembly line.Eigel, who drives a Dodge pickup, also said giving companies subsidies is a “path to tyranny,” because it allows government to pick winners and losers.He eventually handed over the filibuster duties to Sen. Andrew Koenig, R-Manchester, who called parts of Parson’s GM package a “disgrace.”“It is a complete waste of Missouri tax dollars,” Koenig said.Onder took over heading into the sixth hour of the filibuster, which was still going at 9:30 a.m Tuesday.The latest attack by members of the Senate’s Conservative Caucus came after Parson and Republican leaders in the House helped muscle the four-pronged economic development proposal through the House late last Thursday.It includes a $5 million per year, 10-year tax credit program for GM if the automaker invests at least $750 million in the St. Charles County facility, which currently employs about 3,500 workers and supports more than 12,000 employees at 178 suppliers in Missouri.But, with the clock ticking down toward Friday’s 6 p.m. adjournment, the delaying tactics mean less time for debate on GM and other hot button issues, including sweeping anti-abortion legislation and a plan to undo a legislative redistricting plan that voters approved in November.Mayors and other local officials from St. Charles County sat in the gallery to watch as Eigel took over the Senate floor and outlined his opposition to the package and then burned more time by reading speeches by former President Ronald Reagan.Earlier in the day the local officials gathered in the governor’s office to livestream a series of positive testimonials about the project on Facebook.“I want to thank the governor for the leadership and supporting — and making sure that we retain jobs in the Wentzville area, and keeping this plant viable,” Wentzville Mayor Nick Guccione said Monday in the governor’s office. “We do need a trained, skilled workforce because people are retiring.”
The estimated 40 local officials also serve as an unofficial lobbying arm of the governor’s office to pressure the entire Senate to approve the package.“They were in town to receive a boost of encouragement from the governor,” said Parson spokesman Steele Shippy.In addition to the tax credits for GM, the plan contains elements of Parson’s “Fast Track” job training scholarship program for adults, which is funded in the proposed budget at $10 million.It also has two other economic development programs the Republican governor wants, including a “deal closing fund” that could be tapped by his administration to seed job growth without legislative approval.But Eigel and Onder call “Fast Track” unneeded and the deal closing fund a “slush fund.”
“My philosophy has always been one that less government is better,” Eigel said.Eigel said he was greeted by the local officials before Monday’s session began and told them he could support a plan that wouldn’t require the expansion of any state subsidy programs.“There’s already a path that’s been identified,” Eigel said.While action in the Senate was frozen, the House approved a stripped-down version of a tax incentive program as a way to potentially solve the impasse.“This is another option for them,” said Rep. Nick Schroer, R-O’Fallon, who sponsored the alternative proposal.“This is so important when a company is coming to the table saying get your act together, get us something to entice us to come to your state,” Schroer added. “We’re trying to put our money where our mouth is and put something on the table.”The governor’s office, however, said officials are not negotiating any changes to the original plan. And Senate President Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, said the new version was unacceptable.The legislation does not mention the number of jobs that would be created or retained at the plant, where the Chevrolet Colorado, Chevrolet Express Cargo Van, GMC Canyon pickups and GMC Savana full-size van are built.The legislation is Senate Bill 68.Jack Suntrup and Lexi Churchill of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this report.


