JEFFERSON CITY — Moving in rapid-fire fashion Thursday, the Missouri House approved a package of incentives worth more than $50 million to help General Motors expand its plant in Wentzville.Just a week after the Post-Dispatch first reported the automaker’s expansion plan at the facility 40 miles west of St. Louis, the GOP-controlled House voted 92-51 to approve a four-piece economic development proposal that includes a $5 million per year, 10-year tax credit program for GM.The money will be paid out if the automaker invests at least $750 million in the St. Charles County facility, which  currently employs about 3,500 workers and supports more than 12,000 employees at 178 suppliers in Missouri.

The push for state assistance comes as GM has shuttered five plants in North America and laid off more than 14,000 salaried and hourly workers as part of a restructuring.“We do not want, or need, to be next,” said Rep. Nick Schroer, R-O’Fallon.Among those who voted "no" were a handful of members from St. Charles County, including Rep. Bryan Spencer, R-Wentzville, whose district includes the plant.He was skeptical of the need for subsidies, saying he believes Gov. Mike Parson is pushing too hard and moving too fast for the incentives. "Haste makes waste and there's a lot of waste here," Spencer said. "It's too much.""This is not capitalism. This is crony capitalism," added freshman Rep. Tony Lovasco, R-O'Fallon. Others were concerned about the long-term stability of a company that is closing plants and laying off thousands of workers."There's no guarantee that GM will be around in five years," said Rep. Jason Chipman, R-Steelville.With a week to go in the Legislature’s annual session, the measure now heads to the Senate, where it faces an uncertain future.The two senators who represent St. Charles County, Republicans Bob Onder of Lake Saint Louis and Bill Eigel of Weldon Spring, have suggested they may want to pare down the package sought by Parson.
In addition to the tax credits for GM, the plan also contains elements of Parson’s “Fast Track” job training scholarship program for adults, which is funded in the proposed budget at $10 million.It also has two other economic development programs the Republican governor wants, including a “deal closing fund” that could be tapped by his administration without legislative approval to lure companies to the state.Eigel, in an earlier email to colleagues, called the program a “slush fund” that he and his colleagues should block.The legislation does not mention any number of new jobs that would be created at the plant where the Chevrolet Colorado, Chevrolet Express Cargo Van, GMC Canyon pickup trucks, and GMC Savana full-size van are built. The facility has been in operation since 1983.But, a handout from the governor’s office notes that the program is aimed at job retention and job retraining.
“The package of legislation proposed by Governor Parson sharpens Missouri’s economic tools, helping us compete for the General Motors expansion in Wentzville and in future job creation projects across the state,” the four-page flyer said.A statement from Parson said, “We are now one step closer to passing one of the most comprehensive workforce and economic development proposals that proves to the country that Missouri is open for business.""This isn't only going to help GM," said Rep. Ron Hicks, R-Dardenne Prairie, who said he was initially skeptical of the Fast Track program but now believes it contains safeguards that will help move people into jobs.House Minority Leader Crystal Quade, D-Springfield, failed in a bid to add language to the legislation that would require the company to pay back state money if there are job losses at the factory."All we're asking is they maintain the jobs that are here," Quade said.In addition to keeping jobs at the factory and the suppliers, Schroer said the expansion could trigger bridge and road construction projects in the area."This is going to prompt a lot of good construction jobs," Schroer said.The legislation is Senate Bill 68.


