JEFFERSON CITY — A test that St. Louis area motorists love to hate could soon go by the wayside.Under legislation backed by the leader of the Missouri Senate, vehicle emissions testing could be dropped in the region next year.Senate President Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, inserted an amendment into legislation Wednesday that would terminate the tests, which have been taking place for decades in the city of St. Louis, and St. Louis, St. Charles, Jefferson and Franklin counties.

He told his colleagues the state can end the program because air quality has improved. And, he said, newer cars emit less pollution.“It is no longer needed,” Schatz said.Because of high ozone levels, the St. Louis region is the only area in Missouri where emissions testing is required when motorists go to renew their license plates. Automobiles are the largest source of the chemicals that form ozone, but factories, utilities, the petroleum industry and industrial solvents also contribute.Ozone is a respiratory irritant that can cause health problems, especially for children, the elderly and people with heart and lung diseases.The Missouri Department of Natural Resources monitors ozone across the state during the ozone season, which begins March 1 and ends October 31. Sunlight and warm temperatures expedite the process, so ozone usually is a greater problem during the late spring, summer and early fall.But air quality in the St. Louis region improved from an average of 30.3 days of poor air quality a year in the baseline time period of 2009-2011 to an average of 14.0 days per year in 2016-2018, according to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency.Sen. Andrew Koenig, R-Manchester, said some people cannot afford to comply with the tests or buy newer cars that meet the standards.“It’s a tax on poor people,” Koenig said. “If you’ve got a brand new car, you’re going to pass an emissions test.”Others in the Senate raised questions about ending the program, saying it could result in a spike in pollution levels.
“I think we’re moving, from my perspective, in the wrong direction here,” said Sen. Jill Schupp, D-Creve Coeur.Environmental groups also raised alarms.“This is a sneak attack on clean air. These programs are vital to reducing smog pollution in St. Louis. Getting rid of this program will hurt people with asthma, children, the elderly,” said Andy Knott, campaign representative for the Sierra Club.The Republican-led Legislature has endorsed a number of initiatives in recent years that opponents say will roll back environmental protections, including easing regulations for handling toxic coal ash waste, barring local governments from having tougher rules for large-scale animal feeding operations and altering the make-up of the commission that oversees clean water.
A separate piece of legislation awaiting action in the Senate would eliminate vehicle safety testing. However, its prospects remain unclear with just eight days left in the legislative session.Currently, 30 states and Washingtonrequire emissions tests in at least some areas, while 17 states require regular safety inspections. Thirteen states require no inspections.Sen. Doug Libla, R-Poplar Bluff, said he is concerned that removing the emissions testing could jeopardize federal funding.“I am not sure this is the time to be getting this done,” Libla said.In addition to potentially losing federal dollars, a fiscal analysis shows the state would lose $2.8 million in license fee receipts it collects to pay for the program.If approved, the change would go into effect Jan. 1. In addition to needing a final vote in the full Senate, the measure needs approval in the full House and to be signed by Gov. Mike Parson.The legislation is House Bill 499.


