JEFFERSON CITY — Four years after the Legislature directed public colleges and universities to charge undocumented immigrants’ out-of-state or international tuition rates, lawmakers reversed course Tuesday.Lawmakers agreed to allow state-funded schools to charge undocumented immigrants living in Missouri in-state tuition. But the schools will still not be allowed to award scholarships to the students.The move came as a Missouri House and Senate conference committee parsed the state’s $30 billion budget to settle differences between the two chambers before the chambers send the plan to Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican. The new fiscal year starts July 1.

The Senate had stripped the restrictive language, but the House had kept the in-state tuition and scholarship bans in its version of the budget.Sen. Jason Holsman, D-Kansas City, offered what he called “compromise” language — allowing in-state tuition but still banning scholarships for the students — as the conference committee was debating funding for higher education.The affected students “live here,” Holsman said. “And they’ve grown up here.”He said the students are leaving the state and are taking their tuition dollars with them. Holsman said colleges will be free to choose whether they charge undocumented students living here in-state tuition, similar to policies in place before 2015.















            Missouri bans college aid to undocumented students

Colleges have been instructed to strip undocumented students of scholarships and in-state tuition. 




House Budget Chairman Cody Smith, R-Carthage, said colleges are only able to charge in-state tuition currently because of the state’s financial support.Because of this, he suggested taxpayers would in effect be condoning illegal behavior if undocumented students were given in-state tuition as well.Holsman, before the hearing, lined up support from some GOP colleagues, who joined with Democrats to put the new language in place.“There isn’t a good reason” for the state’s current policy “other than something based in fear,” said said Rep. Ingrid Burnett, D-Kansas City.The move represented a victory for Democrats, who had long opposed the in-state tuition restrictions for undocumented immigrants, a group that includes so-called DACA recipients.The two chambers also agreed on an infrastructure funding plan backed by the Senate: The state would issue $301 million worth of bonds, paying the loans back over seven years.
The two chambers budgeted $50 million in general revenue for bridge repairs and another $50 million for a cost-share program so that the state can match funds localities put up for road repairs.The committee also zapped half of the money Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring, had asked for to dig a channel between Bangert Island and mainland St. Charles. Only $1 million is currently appropriated for the project.















            St. Charles wants state taxpayers to pay $2 million to re-create an island on the Missouri River

Not everyone is happy about the state support for the St. Charles project, which the city engineer says he envisions as something like the San Antonio River Walk. 




The committee moved to boost school transportation funding by $5 million, down from the $10 million boost the Senate had recommended.
Lawmakers also agreed to budget $5 million for rural broadband grants, up from $2.5 million the House had budgeted.Despite opposition from Democrats, the conference committee also kept strict anti-abortion language in the budget, prohibiting funds from being sent to any “abortion facility or any affiliate or associate thereof.”Sen. Jamilah Nasheed, D-St. Louis, was able to broker an agreement to keep new spending in the budget to care for victims of sexual assault.The Senate had budgeted $500,000 in new spending, but the House had included no new spending for the endeavor. The committee ultimately agreed to spend $250,000.“This is for housing for these people,” said Rep. Deb Lavender, D-Kirkwood.The budget also includes record spending for K-12 education and small increases to college and university core funding.Medicaid spending continues to grow and will account for about $11 billion in spending next year.The plan assumes a 2 percent increase in revenue collections over this fiscal year. This year’s budget assumes a 1.7 percent growth in revenue over last fiscal year.As of Monday, the state had collected $159 million more this year than at the same point last year, a 1.98 percent increase.The budget still must receive approval in the full House and Senate before heading to Parson’s desk.


