CHICAGO — Cardinals pitcher Carlos Martinez needed six pitches to get three groundouts in one perfect inning for Low-A Peoria on Sunday as the righthander began his rehab assignment.Martinez’s team assignment will be determined game by game as he makes his way back from shoulder trouble, but the plan for the Cardinals is to use him in relief.He won’t start games to assure he appears — readying instead for the routine he’ll have as he speeds toward joining the Cardinals as a reliever.




The target Sunday was to get him one inning of work and to have him start an inning with the bases empty.The tasks will shift based on how recovers, and the goal for the Cardinals is to see Martinez throw at full intensity, appearance to appearance.“Got to come out of that bullpen, man,” Cardinals manager Mike Shildt said. “Warm up. Get going.”TAKING A BETTER LEADWith four stolen bases by four different players Saturday at Wrigley Field, the Cardinals ran into the National League lead with 23 steals this season. They are a month ahead of last year’s pace, and last year’s leader, Harrison Bader, doesn’t have his first steal of 2019 yet.Kolten Wong has already matched his 2018 total of six, and six Cardinals have at least two steals though the team had none Sunday in its 13-5 loss to the Cubs.
For years, the Cards have started spring talking about being more aggressive on the bases only to slow or stumble as summer arrived. This spring, they worked on a new description: assertive.“Baserunning is probably the least sexiest part of the game in general,” Shildt said. “But it’s also where you win a lot of games. Outside of hitting a home run, you have to run the bases to score, every single time. And you’re either creating opportunities or you’re eliminating opportunities. Eliminating opportunities if you don’t go first to third when you should, don’t tag up when you should, read the ball in the dirt like you should. There is a lot to it. This is a group that is sincere about putting the time and effort into it.”EXTRA BASES
• As the Blues completed their victory Sunday in Dallas, the organist at Wrigley Field began, on cue, playing “When the Saints Go Marching In” as a nod during the Cardinals’ batting practice. . . .• The Cardinals are 57-56 all-time on ESPN broadcasts of "Sunday Night Baseball." The Cubs or Cardinals will appear in all four ESPN Sunday telecasts this month. …• Undrafted free agent Tommy Parsons was promoted to High-A Palm Beach after an unerring start to his season for Peoria. Parsons, 23, was 4-0 with a 0.26 ERA in 35 innings for the Cardinals’ lowest full-season affiliate. He had 26 strikeouts and only five walks.



St. Louis Cardinals






            Ragged Cardinals swept away by red-hot Cubs

By Derrick Goold
St. Louis Post-Dispatch









