JEFFERSON CITY • General Motors officials outlined a plan to state and local leaders Thursday to spend $1 billion on its truck and van plant in Wentzville, adding hundreds of thousands of square feet and an unspecified number of new jobs.In a closed-door meeting in Gov. Mike Parson’s office, the leaders learned Missouri is competing against other states for the expansion project, which was first reported by the Post-Dispatch Wednesday.“I’m excited that Missouri has a seat at the table to compete for a tremendous opportunity that will provide a boost to our state and to our regional economy,” Parson told reporters afterward.

GM offered no additional details about the talks after saying Wednesday the company appreciates the willingness of the state to work with the company on unspecified “opportunities.”Sen. Bob Onder, R-Lake Saint Louis, whose district includes the plant, said the project would not only retain the existing 3,500 jobs, but add positions, potentially through direct GM jobs and secondary suppliers.“I think it’s going to be both,” Onder said.Although officials are revealing scant details, the package is expected to be a combination of infrastructure spending, tax incentives and subsidies and will need approval from the Legislature, Parson said.It remains unclear exactly what the company is seeking and how much it could cost taxpayers.“We’ve just got to figure out what those numbers are,” Parson said. “We have not completed any negotiations. Many of the details we are not able to disclose. And, we are competing against other states.”The proposal was unveiled as the Legislature heads into the final two weeks of its annual session, adding heightened urgency for lawmakers to focus on approving a number of incentive programs and job training initiatives before heading home for the summer.“There are a lot of details they need to iron out and they’ve only got two weeks,” said St. Peters Mayor Len Pagano, who attended the briefing.Parson and others said they believe a package could come together in the short time span, without requiring a special session.“I think there is plenty of time to get that done,” Parson said.House Speaker Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield, said lawmakers and the governor's office would work over the weekend to fine-tune an incentive package for the company."I think we will have a very clear idea of what the cost will be by next week," he said.
Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring, said state and company officials discussed Parson's Fast Track scholarship program as one item that could help draw in the investment.The $22 million proposal has become a flash point this legislative session, with Eigel, Onder and other members of a conservative bloc blocking the program's passage.Eigel said after the meeting it was too early to say whether he and allies would continue blocking the scholarships, which would be available for students 25 and older with no college degree."The opportunity to have a $1 billion investment in St. Charles is really a — it's an almost unprecedented opportunity," Eigel said. "And so I am very much interested in seeing what can be done to make that happen for the St. Louis region."Eigel, Onder, Sen. Andrew Koenig and others had held up the program's passage Tuesday night because Senate leadership would not allow the group to add an amendment that would create what are known as Education Savings Accounts. That proposal would more easily allow families to send their children to private schools, which critics fear would harm the public school system.
Eigel said he didn't know whether he and others would give up the push for ESAs and allow Fast Track or other incentives to pass."I don't know that this has to be a zero-sum game where I have to make those commitments in order to do something and take advantage of something that's this unique," he said. "When you have something like this on the table, you have to try to make it happen. So I don't know what that means in terms of giving up stuff."Onder also sounded a potentially positive note.“Overall, the impact is going to be huge and very favorable to our state and to our region,” Onder said. “We’re all committed to doing what we can to really build on the very productive partnership that we’ve had with General Motors.”The Wentzville plant, which opened in 1983, covers more than 3.4 million square feet. Workers build the mid-size Chevrolet Colorado and GMC Canyon pickups and GM’s full-size vans.The automaker added a third shift on the van production line in October to meet strong demand for the vehicles.The scramble to piece together an incentive package to bring jobs to the state is not new.In 2017, former Gov. Eric Greitens called lawmakers into a special session to approve legislation designed to bring a steel mill to the state’s Bootheel region. The proposed factory did not materialize.In 2014, lawmakers and then-Gov. Jay Nixon struck a deal with Boeing Co. obligating the state to hand Boeing $229 million over 18 years if the aerospace giant grows its current St. Louis-area workforce by 2,000 jobs.The deal also allows Boeing to pocket millions in state tax money if it just maintains the jobs it already has here.


