JEFFERSON CITY — A plan by Republicans to sell a state park purchased under former Democratic Gov. Jay Nixon could cost the state thousands of dollars in appraisal, auction and legal fees, according to a nonpartisan analysis of the plan by state budget officials.The Committee on Legislative Research Oversight Division also said money the state fetches at auction would need to be returned to an account administered by the Department of Natural Resources, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the U.S. Forest Service, meaning the potentially millions of dollars in sales proceeds would not enter the state’s general coffers.Almost $11 million in settlement money with lead mining companies funded the purchase of 4,200 acres of Oregon County land in 2016, creating Eleven Point State Park, despite outcry from local officials.

The Post-Dispatch reported then that money also covered the purchase of about 1,100 acres near Johnson’s Shut-Ins State Park and several smaller parcels totaling 200 acres, as well as funding for native plant and stream restoration.Nixon and proponents say mined land will never be returned to its original state, so the settlement allowed the government to protect a comparable amount of unaffected land in perpetuity.But opponents have long said Nixon’s land acquisitions were “shrouded in secrecy” and that the DNR does not have the resources to take care of the 88 parks and historic sites it already operates. Opponents of the Oregon County purchase continue to challenge the legality of its purchase in court.The Missouri House has advanced two bills to the Senate that would require the state to auction off the property. The legislative session ends on May 17.The nonpartisan analysis of the plan says the bills require the state to give the previous owner of the land the right of first refusal to purchase the property, for no less than 80 percent of fair market value.If the previous owner doesn’t want the land, the state would be required to auction off the property.And, the Department of Natural Resources told state budget officials that they expected to return any proceeds to the joint account controlled by the state and the feds.“[P]ursuant to financial agreements with the U.S. Department of Interior (“DOI”), any proceeds from the sale of the properties must be returned to the DOI Restoration Account,” the analysis said.
An updated appraisal could cost the state approximately $7,000, the analysis said, which would come from the state parks earnings fund.The analysis says that since the property’s deed requires “the property to remain dedicated to public use as a state park,” that legal challenges could await any planned sale.The analysis also says that the state could also be on the hook for auction fees — approximately 10 percent of the sale price — but that the cost “would likely be passed on to the buyer.”
Parks boosters have assailed the attempt to sell the park, and the Department of Natural Resources itself declined to discuss selling the park following public backlash against the idea.Rep. Robert Ross, R-Yukon, said where the sales proceeds go would likely be determined by litigation. The question of whether the state could legally sell the land would also likely end up in the courts, he said.“This will be litigated,” said Ross, a critic of the purchase. When the state bought the land, “that became an asset of the state of Missouri and now if the state of Missouri decides to sell that, that does not guarantee that that money has to go back to the ASARCO (lead mining) settlement.”Missouri State Parks has not opened the park, saying it doesn’t have the resources to do so. But boosters say plans call for minimal development that would keep construction costs low.DNR is worried about the costs of maintaining the parks, leading parks officials to float joint operating agreements between the Department of Conservation or private groups.Three other planned parks — the land near Johnson’s Shut-Ins, Bryant Creek State Park in Douglas County and Ozark Mountain State Park in Taney County — also await development as Republican Gov. Mike Parson’s administration assesses Nixon’s acquisitions.The legislation is House Bill 1237.


