JEFFERSON CITY • State revenue collections have ticked up in recent days — welcome news for legislators tasked with writing the state’s $30 billion budget.The Missouri Senate took up on Wednesday the spending plan for next fiscal year, voting to spend $62 million more on K-12 education, which would fully fund the state’s funding formula. Public colleges and universities also would see small increases to core funding.The increases come after months of worry over the state’s financial outlook. This year’s budget assumes a 1.7 percent growth in revenue over last year, but collections had fallen far short of that benchmark until recently.

As of March 25, for example, collections were down $353 million from the same point in 2018, or 5.3 percent.But, as of Tuesday, the state had collected $34.7 million more than at the same point last year, a 0.47 percent increase — better, but still not at the 1.7 percent anticipated growth.“We are optimistic that we are going to be in the net positive,” said Steele Shippy, spokesman for Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican. But, he said, as collections fluctuate, “we’re prepared to balance the budget as needed.”Next year’s budget, for the fiscal year starting July 1, assumes 2 percent growth in revenue. That could mean cuts to spending if there were an economic downturn, said Sen. Scott Sifton, D-south St. Louis County.“This budget might potentially be out of balance” under that scenario, he said Wednesday.Still, the Senate spent the morning debating increased funding for education. In addition to the funding formula increase, the Senate also allocated $10 million more than this year for school transportation costs.The House recommended a $5 million increase, meaning the two sides will have to come to an agreement in a conference committee. School districts have long complained that the state has not adequately funded transportation costs.As the state has reduced the percentage of transportation costs it has covered over the last three decades, school districts have had to pay for more of the costs.“I’m glad to see the Senate has proposed and adopted a higher position on transportation funding, but it’s still underfunded,” said Sen. Lauren Arthur, D-Kansas City.The Senate also reduced the appropriation for Parson’s proposed Fast-Track scholarship program from $18.5 million to $10 million. The legislation authorizing the new scholarship for students 25 and older has yet to clear the Legislature.
“This is a bill that hasn’t passed,” said Senate Budget Chairman Dan Hegeman, R-Cosby, who said he funded the program despite reservations about funding yet-to-be-approved programs. “It is a new program — a startup program that may or may not pass.”The Senate appropriated $50 million in general revenue for bridge repairs, down from the House’s $100 million appropriation.Senate budget writers also appropriated $35 million for a program that would allow localities and the state to share the cost of infrastructure improvements.
House Speaker Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield, said last week that the revenue situation would continue to improve as the state began to cash checks that taxpayers sent in around Tax Day, April 15.Haahr was among those who waited until April 15 to pay his taxes.“I don’t think my check has cleared yet, so I think that will continue to move in the right direction,” he said on Thursday.Haahr also said the positive trend could lessen the push for revenue generating alternatives like enforcing sales taxes on online purchases or expanding gambling by legalizing video gambling in bars, gas stations and truck stops and allowing casinos to offer sports wagering.“Obviously, that probably changes the complexion,” Haahr said.Haahr said talks on those issues would continue nonetheless.Senate leaders said the push to expand gambling should not be linked to shortfalls in revenue.“I would never advocate for that to be a way to fill our budget with gambling revenue,” Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, said Thursday.Differences between the House and Senate budget plans will have to be worked out in a conference committee before Parson considers the final products.


