JEFFERSON CITY • The leader of a bloc of conservative Missouri senators is threatening to sink at least four major initiatives sought by Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, as the Legislature heads into its final weeks.According to an email obtained by the Post-Dispatch, Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring, wants the six-member Conservative Caucus to use its ability to stall action in the GOP-controlled upper chamber to leverage votes on an internet sales tax collection bill, a charter school expansion proposal and legislation that would allow slot machines in bars, gas stations and fraternal organizations.In the email, Eigel expresses frustration that his group’s priorities aren’t being debated after the members allowed a transportation funding plan backed by the governor to move forward.

“We pushed chamber anxiety to a high level and then left the battlefield at the height of the stress allowing a couple … priorities to pass,” Eigel said. “Now comes time for the Republican Caucus to reciprocate — and yet, stunningly, they may have other ideas in mind!”“Despite our assurance we’d be getting to our stuff and warnings that failure to do so this week would cause trouble, here we are,” the April 14 email notes.Eigel told the Post-Dispatch Wednesday that he remained hopeful the situation would turn in his favor.“Things do seem to be shaking loose a little, so I’m cautiously optimistic,” Eigel said.The email is the latest example of heightened tension in the Senate, which is controlled by Eigel’s fellow Republicans.With a May 17 adjournment looming and major proposals stuck, the chamber has already boiled over once because of the caucus’ tactics.Last week, Sen. Mike Cierpiot, R-Lee’s Summit, lashed out at the group, which includes Republican Sens. Eric Burlison of Springfield, Denny Hoskins of Warrensburg, Cindy O’Laughlin of Shelbina, Andrew Koenig of Manchester and Bob Onder of Lake Saint Louis.“I have made efforts to reach compromise with this group, thought we had an agreement and watched that agreement evaporate,” Cierpiot said. “I’m finished with that approach, with that group, unless things change.”Cierpiot questioned how the caucus could claim conservative “purity” while backing issues such as expanding gambling.“They might rename themselves the Inconsistent Caucus because they certainly are,” Cierpiot said. “Or maybe the Chaos Caucus, because that seems to be what their efforts are mostly after.”
The caucus was formed in January as a subset of the 24-member Republican supermajority in the Senate. At the time, they said their priorities included abortion, gun rights and smaller government.Eigel said the caucus’ support of expanded gambling was meant to address a rise in illegal slot machines in the state.“If a compromise could be reached that addresses this as part of a small expansion that stays within constitutional bounds, I’m interested,” he said.Among other items Eigel said the caucus might block is a long-sought prescription drug monitoring program backed by Sen. Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan.On Tuesday, in a sign that Senate leaders were aware of the caucus’ threat to filibuster, the PDMP legislation — considered a key part of fighting the opioid epidemic — was skipped on the agenda.
Eigel also suggested the caucus would block Parson’s job-creation programs, including an adult college scholarship proposal, a revamp of the Department of Economic Development and two bills that he said would streamline the agency’s ability to lure businesses to Missouri.Eigel called the latter “slush funds.”He also warned that a gasoline tax increase sponsored by Sen. Doug Libla, R-Poplar Bluff, could be targeted.The governor’s office had not seen the email. A spokesman said Parson continued to work with the Legislature.In a list of recommendations, Eigel said, “If our priorities don’t see the finish line this week, the chamber should be stalled until that occurs.”“It has always been my No. 1 fear that when the time came that we would be willing to negotiate and we would want to cash in on ‘goodwill,’ nothing would happen,” he noted.Senate Majority Leader Caleb Rowden, R-Columbia, played down the tension in comments to reporters.“It always gets interesting in the last month or so,” Rowden said. “We’re going to keep trying to make sure as many folks have the chance to get the stuff done that they want to get done, and that requires us working through some contentious moments off the floor, and sometimes it requires it on the floor.”


