JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri’s fledgling medical marijuana program could be facing its second lawsuit after a company bidding to help run the initiative cried foul over the awarding of a contract to a competitor.In a protest filed with the state Thursday, an attorney for BioTrackTHC said the awarding of a contract to register patients, license facilities and track marijuana from seed to sale to Metrc LLC was flawed because the winner did not disclose fees that would be charged to growers and other vendors.Those fees could have helped Metrc outflank competitors by lowering what it charges the state, the protest noted.

The protest seeks to void the contract with Metrc and award the potentially lucrative job to BioTrack based on a point system used by the state when it evaluates bids.“Competitive bidding procedures must ensure that all who wish to bid have a fair opportunity to compete in a field where no favoritism is shown to other contestants,” the protest notes.Although the protest could be resolved before it reaches a courtroom, it comes as the Department of Health and Senior Services is being sued by the Post-Dispatch over the decision to withhold the names of nearly 500 companies and individuals that are seeking to grow, process and sell marijuana products.Voters approved Amendment 2 in November, making Missouri the 33rd state to legalize marijuana for medicinal use. Sales are to start early next year. Tax proceeds and licensing fees are supposed to go into a newly created veterans health care fund, which is expected to generate about $20 million per year.But the amendment allows the state to dip into the fund to administer the program. The Missouri House has also approved legislation that would force the state to use the veterans fund when handling medical marijuana-related lawsuits, meaning the net amount going to veterans could be far less than $20 million per year as the state implements its program.BioTrack and Metrc are among the top operators vying to help states administer their marijuana programs. Metrc has contracts with at least 10 states, while BioTrack has seven.BioTrack hired former Missouri House Speaker Steve Tilley to lobby on its behalf and retained Jefferson City lawyer Charles Hatfield, who is a former aide to former Gov. Jay Nixon, to submit the protest.In some states, different companies handle the various aspects of operating a medical marijuana program. But Missouri wants one company to do most of the information technology set-up for its licensing and tracking system. The contract with Metrc, if it survives the protest, will run for five years.Gov. Mike Parson’s administration would not say whether the protest would delay the program.“The protest is currently under review. We do not comment on pending protests,” said Brittany Ruess, spokeswoman for the Office of Administration.The contract is worth about $5 million, but Metrc could make millions more by charging vendors the fees.Missouri is required by law to approve at least 60 commercial growers, 86 facilities that manufacture marijuana-infused products and 192 dispensary licenses — 24 dispensaries for each of Missouri’s eight congressional districts.The St. Louis area will probably have more than 48 dispensaries. Two congressional districts cover St. Louis and St. Louis County and parts of St. Charles, Jefferson and Franklin counties.












News






            What will it take to win a license to grow or sell marijuana in Missouri?





Post-Dispatch suit
In the Sunshine Law case, meanwhile, attorneys for the Post-Dispatch and the Department of Health and Senior Services are scheduled to meet at 1:30 p.m. Monday in Cole County Circuit Court.The newspaper sued the state in January after officials refused to turn over the identities of the hundreds of entities seeking to grow, distribute or manufacture medicinal marijuana products in the state.The state has said the text of Amendment 2 precludes it from releasing any of the identifying information.The amendment says, in part, that the department “shall maintain the confidentiality of reports or other information obtained from an applicant or licensee containing any individualized data, information, or records related to the licensee or its operation … .”In the lawsuit, Post-Dispatch attorney Joseph Martineau argued the state was relying on an “overly restrictive interpretation” of that provision to justify concealing names of businesses and identifying information.“(T)he provision does not say that the Department ‘shall maintain the confidentiality of the applicant or licensee’ as well as the reports or other information obtained from the applicant or licensee,” Martineau argues.
Martineau wrote that the interpretation “is flawed, unsupported by the language of the provision, contrary to the provision’s intent, and disregards the important public policy that the process of applying for and awarding licenses to manufacture, distribute and dispense marijuana should be open and transparent.”Martineau said other records exemptions written into the state’s Sunshine Law were explicitly intended to conceal the identities from the public.Amendment 2 “says nothing about maintaining the confidentiality of the identity or identification of individuals or companies applying for licenses,” he said.On March 4, the attorney general’s office, on behalf of the health department, said Circuit Judge Daniel Green should apply a “traditional constitutional interpretation” to the constitutional clause that says the state should “maintain the confidentiality of … any information.”“The Post-Dispatch’s argument is laid bare repeatedly throughout its Petition where it is forced to argue that ‘any information related to the licensee of its operation’ doesn’t really mean any information,” the state argues. “By the Post-Dispatch’s reasoning, identifying information of applicants and their operations — obtained from the applicant— must be disclosed by the Department.”“The Post-Dispatch’s position is untenable and cannot be allowed to prevail over the will of Missouri voters and the plain language of the Constitutional provision they adopted overwhelmingly,” the state says.The newspaper responded on April 16 in a motion for summary judgment. Citing a section of the Sunshine Law that states “public records must be presumed open to public inspection unless they contain information which clearly fits within one of the [statutory] exemptions,” the newspaper said there was no clear exemption for the names of the applicants.The newspaper also cited a separate section stating that the Sunshine Law should be “liberally construed” in order to promote transparency.















