JEFFERSON CITY • The director of one of Missouri’s largest state agencies is stepping down after nearly two years on the job.Steve Corsi, who ran the Department of Social Services, will leave in June to pursue a position with a faith-based nonprofit, Gov. Mike Parson said in a statement Thursday.













Steve Corsi, Gov. Eric Greitens' choice to head the Missouri Department of Social Services.




“Dr. Corsi has served our country nobly as a veteran and has been a great asset to the State of Missouri during his time as a Department Director,” Parson said.Corsi, who was earning $148,000 annually, was brought to Missouri by Gov. Eric Greitens after serving as director of a similar agency in Wyoming.Corsi came under scrutiny for being overpaid based on state statutes.While the budget called for him to receive $128,000 per year, he also was receiving a separate check from the Department of Health and Senior Services that raised his total take home pay to $142,000 annually.
Officials later altered the pay scale to allow him to be legally paid at his current level.Corsi is the latest holdover from the Greitens administration to depart. Parson ousted Department of Public Safety Director Drew Juden soon after taking office.And, embattled Department of Revenue Director Joel Walters announced his resignation last month after acknowledging he'd made mistakes in adjusting income tax withholding tables.
A psychologist by training, Corsi oversaw a sprawling agency that manages health care and other benefits for low-income and elderly Missourians, as well as provides services for juvenile offenders and the developmentally disabled.Parson credited Corsi with boosting programs designed to move more people into work and for helping foster children and youth.A replacement has not been named.“My administration will work over the coming weeks to identify new leadership that can continue to build on the positive reforms made within the department,” Parson said.


