JEFFERSON CITY • A plan to transmit wind energy into and through the state could be in jeopardy after the Missouri House gave initial approval on Tuesday to a measure that would forbid the project’s developer from using eminent domain to construct the line.The move comes a month after the Missouri Public Service Commission, which regulates utilities, deemed the Grain Belt Express transmission line in the public interest and granted the project “a certificate of convenience and necessity,” allowing the developer to use eminent domain in order to acquire easements for the project.The long-stalled line seeks to transmit Kansas wind energy through eight northern Missouri counties, through Illinois and Indiana, and to eastern states for consumption. The line would also deliver power to at least 350,000 Missourians and unlock energy savings of $12.8 million per year, based on contracts already reached with municipal utilities around the state.

After the PSC’s five commissioners appointed by multiple governors granted unanimous approval to the line, House Speaker Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield, said last month he would make the passage of a bill forbidding eminent domain for the project a priority.“The General Assembly will act to protect Missourians from private companies trying to seize their land through eminent domain,” Haahr said in a statement. “The legislation the House is moving forward is vital for many Missourians who otherwise would be forced to allow unreasonable restrictions on their family farms, damaging the value of their land and taking away their private property rights.”The legislation, sponsored by Rep. Jim Hansen, R-Frankford, bans eminent domain "for the purposes of constructing above-ground merchant lines.""This is just another attempt by a private companies and a government commission to eliminate our personal liberties," Hansen said of the project. “I am not opposed to green energy,” Hansen said. “I’m so opposed to a private company saying, ‘I’m gonna do this and you’re gonna like it — or else.’”Clean Line Energy Partners announced in November that it would sell rights to the transmission line to Chicago-based Invenergy. The PSC has yet to approve that sale.“We’re certainly opposed to anything that would slow, or work to slow, the benefits that the Grain Belt Express can bring to Missouri,” said Beth Conley, a spokesperson for Invenergy, who added that building the project would bring $500 million of direct investment and 1,500 jobs to the state, in addition to customer savings.“This project has been thoroughly vetted for more than five years by the Missouri PSC,” she said. “We feel good about that decision and their ability to adjudicate the case.”Rep. Peter Merideth, D-St. Louis, said he doesn’t like eminent domain, but he said he would oppose Hansen’s bill because it targets only one industry."It seems like it is a bill that is designed with a very narrow focus because of one decision from the PSC about one project that some folks in the state don’t like," Merideth said.
The proposal still must win final approval in the House before moving to the Senate for consideration. Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, has not taken a position on the measure.











With the legislation emerging to oppose the project’s use of eminent domain, a conference call was held last week by representatives of the Missouri communities that have signed up to receive power from the project.One by one, officials — often from rural parts of the state — described how the line stands to benefit local residents.
The communities of Lebanon, Rolla, Columbia and Kirkwood, for instance, each stand to see savings of more than $1 million a year from accessing the cheap energy provided by the project. Customer bases in Farmington, Hannibal, Jackson and Marshall, meanwhile, would each save around $500,000 annually."Anytime lower pricing is injected into the market, we all benefit," said Mark Petty, director of the city-owned power utility, Kirkwood Electric. He noted that considerations about eminent domain were already taken into account during the PSC’s "extensive process for the approval of the project," which it ruled was in the public interest.If the project is shot down by the legislation, supporters worry about what it would mean for future economic development efforts in the state."My fear for that is the precedent it would set for any future project in the state of Missouri," said John Grotzinger, chief operating officer for the Missouri Joint Municipal Electric Utility Commission. "Whether it’s electric, water, sewer, telecom ... (eminent domain) is a necessary evil and a last resort to make a project happen."Complications could be especially tough on Missouri’s electric grid, which is awash in coal power despite sitting next to an abundance of increasingly cost-effective wind energy from Plains states. But transmission issues are widely seen as a key stumbling block when it comes to linking that power supply with growing demand from far-flung population centers."For us, the transmission issue is huge," said Dennis Klusmeyer, the superintendent for the City of Shelbina. If the project comes on line, customers in the northern Missouri town of 1,600 people would trim electric costs by nearly 4 percent compared to the alternatives available to them."This project is very worth the effort and is well-needed in Missouri. We are in need of infrastructure improvement in the state and across the country," he said.The legislation is House Bill 1062.


