JEFFERSON CITY • More than a half million dollars poured into Gov. Mike Parson’s campaign fund during the first three months of 2019, signaling that the Republican is gearing up to run for a full term in 2020.Reports filed with the Missouri Ethics Commission show Parson raised $198,931 in his personal campaign account.Uniting Missouri, a separate political action committee not controlled by Parson, raised $354,156.

That left the governor and his allies with $3.4 million in cash, with nearly one-third of that coming from retired St. Louis financier Rex Sinquefield.Although Secretary of State Jay Ashcroft has been mentioned as a potential primary rival, fundraising numbers submitted by the Republican show he had $206,000 in his campaign account on April 1 after raising $95,700.Among Democrats potentially seeking the state’s top job, Sen. Scott Sifton of Affton reported having $313,000 on hand as of April 1. Auditor Nicole Galloway has $65,798 in her account after raising $114,194 in the first quarter. Neither has formally announced future political plans.
Parson, a former legislator, was elected lieutenant governor in 2016 and was elevated to governor June 1 following the resignation of scandal-plagued Eric Greitens.Parson has not made a formal announcement about his plans to run, but his fundraising activity suggests he’s preparing for a campaign.
At an event in Cape Girardeau in late March, for example, Parson collected $47,236 for his personal campaign account. Among the donors was former Lt. Gov. Peter Kinder, who wrote a check for $250.At a February event in Poplar Bluff, Republican Senate candidate Eddy Justice gave Parson $2,600. Former House Speaker Todd Richardson, who was named by Parson to a job overseeing the state’s Medicaid program, contributed $500. State Rep. Jeff Shawan, R-Poplar Bluff, gave Parson $2,600.Along with Sinquefield, Uniting Missouri received a number of contributions from businesses that have interests in legislation moving through the process in the Capitol, including transportation engineering firms and video gambling companies.Records show Parson paid $14,900 for airplane flights. He also spent $195 on Kansas City Chiefs apparel.


