JEFFERSON CITY • The group campaigning to merge St. Louis and St. Louis County received its second big money contribution Friday.













John McDonnell, BioSTL founding chairman, at an appearance in Clayton on Sept. 27, 2011. Photo by Christian Gooden, cgooden@post-dispatch.com


Christian Gooden


John McDonnell, the former chairman of McDonnell Douglas Corp., wrote a $300,000 check to Unite STL, which is the committee formed to help finance the Better Together merger campaign.

That follows a March contribution of $125,000 from a coalition of Carpenters Union locals in Missouri, Kansas and southern Illinois.The latest contribution is significant after retired financier Rex Sinquefield, who financed much of Better Together’s early work, had said he would not support the campaign if he were its only donor.It also is the first six-figure contribution following the announcement of a federal investigation into the administration of St. Louis County Executive Steve Stenger, who would have become the automatic mayor of the combined city under an earlier version of Better Together’s plan.Following news of the probe, Better Together inserted new language calling for an election to fill the post.
McDonnell, who retired as chairman of the aerospace company in 1997, has donated to both Republican and Democratic causes. In the 2016 election, he backed Democrat Chris Koster for governor and Republican Mike Parson for lieutenant governor. He also gave $1,500 to Sen. Bill Eigel, who is a member of a conservative bloc of senators in the Missouri Legislature’s upper chamber.
McDonnell also is listed as an early donor to the Better Together cause in 2018. Others at that time include Sinquefield, Civic Progress and the Regional Business Council."We are very proud to have Mr. McDonnell's support," said Unite STL spokesman Ed Rhode.The money to Unite STL will help finance the plan to gather more than 160,000 signatures and place the merger question on the November 2020 statewide ballot.If approved, the merger would combine under one metro city the police departments, court systems, roadways, regional planning and zoning, and economic development arms of the city, county and the 88 county municipalities. County municipalities would become new political subdivisions, called “municipal districts,” with power over some services, such as parks and trash collection, but with otherwise severely restricted authority.















            Read more about Reshaping St. Louis

Read the Post-Dispatch coverage of the Better Together plan to reunite St. Louis City and County. 







