JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri lawmakers attempted to take a new transportation funding scheme for a test drive Tuesday, but the plan quickly ran into gridlock in the hallways of the Capitol.In the Senate, opponents of a plan to borrow $351 million for roads and bridges worked to put the brakes on the measure. And, down the corridor, the chairman of the House Budget Committee expressed skepticism about the borrowing plan, but pledged to try to work out a compromise.“I do know this is a collaborate process. We will have a series of negotiations,” Rep. Cody Smith said.

Three months after Gov. Mike Parson announced a proposal to borrow $351 million to repair bridges across the state, Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, proposed a new version designed to tamp down opposition to borrowing.Rather than spreading the cost over 15 years, the new version would repay the loan over seven years, potentially saving tens of millions of dollars in interest costs.Parson floated the outlines of the plan in January in response to the failure of a ballot initiative in November that sought to raise the state’s 17-cent-per-gallon gas tax by 10 cents.But, members of the House balked at the notion of borrowing and instead approved a budget that would earmark $100 million in general revenue for road building.Schatz’s new proposal, which is designed to strike a middle ground in terms of borrowing and general tax dollars, was formally introduced on the floor of the Senate after the $100 million House allocation was cut from the budget during an earlier budget hearing.The maneuvering signals that Senate leaders and Parson are on the same page when it comes to transportation funding heading into the final month of the legislative session.“I think this was a reasonable position to move back to. From a business perspective, I think it makes sense,” Schatz said.But, some members of the Senate and leaders in the House are signaling that more negotiations are necessary.“I still remain concerned about taking on additional debt. I’m going to be very hesitant to embrace a package that would incur unnecessary debt,” said Smith, R-Carthage.
Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring, said he likes the House approach.“My preference is for the $100 million,” Eigel said.“I think the House is taking the fiscally responsible approach,” added Sen. Bob Onder, R-Lake Saint Louis.Sen. Cindy O’Laughlin, R-Shelbina, said the borrowing plan is an “end around the taxpayer.”
Democratic lawmakers said the fissures among Republicans at the state and federal level don’t bode well for fixing the state’s roads and bridges.“We have an infrastructure problem and we cannot continue to kick the bucket down the road,” said Sen. Jamilah Nasheed, D-St. Louis. “We have to fend for ourselves.”Schatz has argued that if the state doesn’t issue bonds, it could jeopardize the state’s ability to qualify for a federal grant that will pay for the replacement of the Rocheport bridge on Interstate 70, which moves freight and travelers over the Missouri River in central Missouri.The Senate version of the budget also contains $15.8 million for repairs to flood damaged roads and bridges.“I know of at least one bridge that will need to be replaced,” said Sen. Dan Hegeman, R-Cosby and chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee.A debate on the borrowing plan was underway in the Senate Tuesday night. It was not clear whether a final vote would be taken.The legislation is Senate Concurrent Resolution 14.


