JEFFERSON CITY • A Cole County judge said Tuesday that U.S. Sen. Josh Hawley will not have to sit for a deposition amid an open records dispute between the state and a Democrat running for attorney general.Circuit Judge Patricia Joyce issued an order Tuesday quashing a subpoena by Elad Gross, a Democrat running for Missouri attorney general.Agents for Gross had served Hawley, a Republican, a subpoena last month following Hawley's speech at the Conservative Political Action Conference in Washington. 

The subpoena stemmed from an open records dispute Gross has with Gov. Mike Parson's administration. Gross is seeking a cache of documents from Parson’s office related to former Gov. Eric Greitens, but the governor’s office won’t turn the documents over unless Gross signs a $3,600 check.Gross filed a complaint with the Missouri attorney general’s office last fall, but the  office took no action against the governor. Hawley, who at the time was attorney general, won election to the U.S. Senate in November.
Gross said he subpoenaed Hawley instead of the attorney general's office because Hawley had personal knowledge of the information he sought. In a court brief, Hawley's attorneys moved to quash the subpoena. 
Kelli Ford, who works in Hawley's U.S. Senate office, issued a statement after Joyce's ruling:“Of course this is how the court ruled," she said. "As we have said all along, this was just the latest political stunt by a Democrat candidate trying to get a headline by attacking Josh Hawley. Another swing and a miss.” Gross said after the ruling that he hopes Hawley will sit down voluntarily to tell him what he knows about "dark money in the state."


