JEFFERSON CITY • A new plan to boost spending on roads and bridges in Missouri is expected to surface as early as Tuesday as Gov. Mike Parson and legislative leaders work to find a transportation solution after voters turned down a gas tax hike in November.Without the added revenue from a 10-cent per gallon, phased-in gasoline tax increase, Parson asked lawmakers to allow him to borrow $350 million to repair 200-plus bridges, including three in the St. Louis region.The Republican-controlled House balked at the borrowing plan and instead approved a budget that earmarks $100 million out of the state’s general checkbook for additional road construction.

Now, Senate leaders are expected to outline a middle ground with a combination of new spending and a shorter borrowing window.With a Senate committee scheduled to take up the House budget for the first time on Tuesday, the Post-Dispatch has learned that Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, is expected to introduce changes designed to give both sides some of what they are seeking.Instead of a $100 million outlay, the new money would amount to an estimated $56 million. That would be combined with $350 million in borrowing, but with a shorter payback period.“We’re looking at somewhere between what the House has presented and potentially something less than that,” Schatz said earlier.The new plan could assuage fears by Democrats that the $100 million plan advanced in the House budget would take money away from education, social service programs and public defenders.But, Schatz’s proposal will need the support of leaders in the Republican-controlled House.Rep. Cody Smith, R-Carthage, who is chairman of the House Budget Committee, earlier said he was “absolutely” ready to seek a compromise with the Senate.
“We have an open dialogue,” Smith told reporters after the House budget was approved.His primary concern with the governor’s plan was the cost of borrowing the money and spreading that cost over 15 years.“I’m very concerned about taking on additional debt and managing the size of that debt going forward,” Smith said. “I think there is opportunity to land somewhere in the middle.”Among Schatz’s concern is that the House plan could result in the state not having enough money to qualify for a federal grant that will pay for the repair of the Rocheport bridge on Interstate 70, which moves freight and travelers over the Missouri River.
Smith signaled that it’s a concern for him too.“I don’t think anybody in the Missouri General Assembly is interested in leaving tens of millions of dollars in federal funds for bridge repair on the table,” Smith said.The scramble to find a way to pay for road and bridge construction follows voters’ rejection of a proposed gasoline tax increase last November. Schatz had sponsored the ballot initiative and Parson traversed the state calling on voters to back the plan.Missouri’s 17-cent-per-gallon gas tax is among the lowest in the nation.The latest proposal comes as state budget revenues remain under estimates. The latest report shows revenue down $177 million, or 2.6 percent, from last year. The current year’s budget was built on a projection of 1.7 percent growth, meaning Parson may have to withhold spending if more money doesn’t flow into the state bank account.Lawmakers are scheduled to be in session until May 17.


