JEFFERSON CITY • Republicans are pushing back on Auditor Nicole Galloway’s claim that Gov. Mike Parson’s administration acted unlawfully when it quietly adjusted income tax withholding tables in January.Galloway said in an audit Tuesday that the Republican administration didn’t follow rule-making procedures, as prescribed by law, when officials changed the state’s tax withholding formula in January.But Republicans said later that previous changes to the withholding formula — under earlier administrations — also were not enacted under the procedures Galloway cited. Galloway made no mention of that fact, Treasurer Scott Fitzpatrick, a Republican, said this week.

State law says withholding changes must be made through the rule-making process. The regulation on the books is 26 years old, however, meaning withholding changes made since also did not follow state law, Fitzpatrick said.“The regulation has been outdated for 26 years. You would have thought that an auditor or the Department of Revenue would have identified that,” he told the Post-Dispatch Friday.The audit came after months of bipartisan criticism of the Department of Revenue for a lack of communication with taxpayers following previous changes to the tax tables that were made in response to federal tax cuts approved in 2017.As a result, people who did not adjust their 2018 withholding are getting smaller refunds or owe money.The dust-up led to the resignation of Revenue Director Joel Walters, who had been brought on board by former Gov. Eric Greitens.
Parson has tried to rebuff the criticism by calling it political grandstanding. In response to the audit, he asked Fitzpatrick to conduct his own review of the changes made by Revenue officials.In a three-page response obtained by the Post-Dispatch, Fitzpatrick agreed with Galloway about the actions taken and not taken by the Department of Revenue, but said that he doesn’t believe the department broke any law because it was trying to fix something that had been broken for more than a quarter century.
“Had the department implemented the withholding instructions pursuant to this antiquated regulations, the result would have been incompatible with current tax law and would have resulted in substantial under withholding,” Fitzpatrick wrote.The treasurer’s response was distributed to members of the Legislature on Thursday.House Minority Leader Crystal Quade, D-Springfield, sided with Galloway Friday, saying state law requires the state agencies to follow certain processes when altering rules and regulations.“That process was not followed and no amount of rationalization by the Treasurer or the rest of the administration will change that,” Quade said. “If it hopes to restore its credibility, the administration must own up to its failures and take its duty to taxpayers seriously.”In a statement Friday, Galloway said, “The State Treasurer agrees: the Department of Revenue is over withholding taxes from Missourians’ paychecks and ignored the legal process. It’s further bipartisan acknowledgement that there are ongoing issues affecting taxpayers. The administration needs to follow the law, get it right and stop misleading taxpayers.”


