JEFFERSON CITY • The man who financed much of the early work behind a campaign to merge St. Louis and St. Louis County lunched with Gov. Mike Parson at the governor’s mansion Thursday.But, whether the two talked about the controversial effort to transform the region into a mega city was unclear in the aftermath of the meeting, which included a seat at the table for economist Art Laffer, who is considered the architect of a tax cut scheme in Kansas that left that state’s revenues in tatters.“The governor and I had a productive lunch conversation about the future economic growth needs of a state we both dearly love,” Rex Sinquefield said in a statement provided to the Post-Dispatch by a spokesman.

The lunch, first reported by the Kansas City Star, comes as the Republican governor has not taken a firm position on the Sinquefield-financed Better Together proposal, a campaign to get voter approval of a plan to fuse the city and the county.Municipal mayors in the county have expressed strong opposition to the idea, which Sinquefield has said would accelerate growth in the state.Lawmakers this week presented a number of bills that would leave the decision to voters in the county and city, as opposed to the entire state.
Sinquefield, a wealthy retired financier, backed Parson’s opponent in the 2016 primary election for lieutenant governor, but has since contributed $1 million to a political action committee formed to support Parson in a run for governor in 2020.Parson took over as chief executive in June after the resignation of former Gov. Eric Greitens.
Laffer is considered the architect of a 2012 tax cut package in Kansas that was supposed to trigger economic growth that would make up for the loss in revenue.The plan was dumped five years later after significant drops in revenues affected state aid to schools and universities and health care spending.Parson has not called for tax cuts in his budget proposal and is facing the prospect having to withhold funding for programs due to the impact of budget cuts enacted in 2014. Despite the lagging revenue, some GOP lawmakers continue to press for reductions as the legislative session enters its final weeks.


