JEFFERSON CITY • Republicans may control the levers of government in Missouri, but they are not in lockstep when it comes to collecting taxes from online sales.While some see the potential revenue as a way to keep pace with the rising costs of running government, or as a means to pump more cash into education or road and bridge construction, others in the party in power see it as an opportunity to lower income tax and corporate tax rates for Missourians.The disagreement over what to do with an estimated $165 million in future annual proceeds is becoming a focal point under the dome as the Legislature heads into the final seven weeks of the spring session.

Last year, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that states could start collecting revenue from online sales from out-of-state businesses that don’t have a physical presence in a state.Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, said in December that he wanted to see a tax enacted in order to level the playing field for in-state companies and their out-of-state competitors.The prospect of a new source of money for the state comes as revenue is arriving below projections, potentially forcing Parson to withhold money from various programs in order to keep the state’s budget balanced.Although more money could start flowing as Missourians pay their state income tax bills, revenue collections as of Wednesday were down $286.7 million from the same point last year, or 4.3 percent.However, instead of using the money to fill in budget holes or pay for road and bridge construction or education, some Republican lawmakers say the state should reduce taxes for Missouri residents and businesses.In the House, Rep. J. Eggleston, R-Maysville, is sponsoring a bill that would reduce the top individual income tax rate over two years if sales taxes increase at a certain rate once they are being collected from online sales.Sen. Andrew Koenig, R-Manchester, is sponsoring a similar proposal in the Senate.During an earlier floor debate, Sen. Tony Luetkemeyer, R-Parkville, said the money from online sales could be used to eliminate the corporate income tax.
“I look at the tax relief that could be provided to all the small, family-owned businesses,” Luetkemeyer said.Sen. Eric Burlison, R-Springfield, also suggested that he’d like to see the revenue used to lower taxes.“I think it’s important to keep our tax rates low,” Burlison said.
Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring, among the most vocal supporters of lowering income and corporate tax rates, said he agrees with Parson that more money needs to be spent on repairing the state’s roads and bridges.But, Eigel said, “There’s disagreement on how we get from here to there. I believe we need to reduce the tax burden and this is a way to move forward with that.”Rep. Chrissy Sommer, R-St. Charles, said a decision on how to proceed had not been made. As chairwoman of the House Ways and Means Committee, she’s held hearings on bills calling for online sales tax collections that wouldn’t require revenue to be returned to taxpayers through cuts to income or corporate taxes.“I understand there are those who wish that money could be returned. But it’s more complicated than that. Some of us are already paying taxes on online purchases,” Sommer said.Parson, meantime, is staying out of the debate over what should be done with the money.“We’re going to continue working with the Legislature. It is an issue that deserves serious debate,” the governor’s spokesman Steele Shippy said.












Political Fix






            Missouri governor wants law for online sales tax collections


















