A government office that grants money and technical assistance to energy efficiency and renewable energy projects around Missouri will be shuffled between state agencies this summer.The state Division of Energy, which has more than 30 employees, will be transferred from the Missouri Department of Economic Development to the Missouri Department of Natural Resources on Aug. 28. The move was first announced in an executive order from Gov. Mike Parson in January, but has now cleared a 60-day window in which lawmakers could have raised concerns .Some tout the change as a welcome part of efforts to streamline and realign state government organizations to emphasize core aspects of their mission. Others, though hopeful that the move can benefit state energy and environmental policy, will keep a cautious eye to ensure that it is not accompanied by political interference from the DNR to control the division’s focus or give more favorable treatment to fossil fuels.

“The impetus for a lot of this is our ‘Best in Midwest’ campaign,” said Maggie Kost, the director of communications and marketing for the Department of Economic Development, referencing an ongoing effort to evaluate how Missouri compares to neighboring states. She said Missouri is not doing as well as its regional peers whose government agencies are more “laser-focused” on economic development functions.“When everything is a priority, nothing is a priority,” Kost said. “We had more functions than any peer agency.”Kost and many others say it’s a logical fit to pair the Division of Energy with the DNR. In fact, the division had formerly been part of the DNR, before being moved into the economic development sphere in 2013, under Gov. Jay Nixon.Although the DNR said many details about the transition — from logistical questions to policy aims — have yet to click into place, agency officials expressed enthusiasm about the move.
“Transferring @MO_DivofEnergy back to MoDNR will benefit @MoGov by expanding our department’s ability to balance a healthy environment w/ a healthy economy," said @CarolSComer1. We're working together w/ @MoEcoDevo & @GovParsonMO to ensure a smooth transition. #MissouriForward pic.twitter.com/KifrSakczS— Missouri DNR (@MoDNR) March 19, 2019

“For us, moving the DOE back to DNR expands our ability to do that healthy environment, healthy economy balance that we’re always talking about,” said Connie Patterson, a department spokeswoman. “We’re looking at it as an opportunity to work very closely with them on energy policy for the state of Missouri.”Though it’s unclear what, exactly, that may entail, pursuit of an “affordable” and “reliable” energy strategy has been emphasized in initial statements from the DNR. Around the country, those exact terms have, in some cases, become weaponized buzzwords in political fights that oppose renewable energy. But the DNR says it has no such motive to favor fossil fuels over lower-carbon sources of energy.“We support all methods of generation and renewable energy under that umbrella along with everything else. And a lot of that is market-driven,” Patterson said. “Everything’s on the table for discussion, and we’re all looking for opportunities to support that affordable and reliable energy strategy.”Others are cautious, such as Steve Mahfood, a former director of the DNR.Given the “inexorable” link between energy production and environmental issues, he agrees that operating within the DNR is a good fit for the division, but the track record of the current administration concerns him.
The agency, for example, has recently proposed controversial rules about how to regulate coal power byproducts such as coal ash, in response to new legislation that electric utilities helped shape.Current DNR leadership has also overseen a steep drop in enforcement actions — a trend met with alarm by some, despite assurances from the DNR that environmental quality in the state is not being compromised amid a broad push to slash regulatory “red tape.”“A lot of what DNR now does seems to support traditional energy industries — coal-fired power plants and things like that, instead of renewables,” Mahfood said.“My cynical side says maybe this is a way to focus on what we’ve been doing and maybe suppress any kind of new generation and green energy approach.”Mahfood said the Division of Energy has historically had a “very strong role” within the DNR and “has been very successful in making things happen at a local level.”
But he wonders if soon having the two as part of the same “tightly wound package” could expose state energy policies to political meddling, with energy regulators and promoters again under one roof.“If you’ve got (the Division of) Energy over in (the Department of) Natural Resources, you’ve got all the components of supporting the industry as it currently is,” he said. “Being in one department, you’ve got one voice, it can all be directed upwards and the message can be controlled.”Moving forward, Mahfood said, environmental watchdogs will need to keep an eye on ensuing energy policies that emerge from the DNR, or other signs, such as who the department might allow to testify in support of bills or Missouri’s Comprehensive State Energy plan, developed by the division.Potential changes in policy could ultimately rest with DNR leadership, and specifically with director Carol Comer, appointed by former Gov. Eric Greitens. Before coming to Missouri, Comer had been commissioner of the Indiana Department of Environmental Management under Vice President Mike Pence, while he was the state’s governor.“Does she have a vision for this addition?” asks Josh Campbell, the executive director of the nonprofit Missouri Energy Initiative.“It’s very possible she may have an agenda she wants to push. We don’t know what it is — it could be great.”He doesn’t think the DNR’s early statements stressing “affordability” and “reliability” signal a looming fight against renewables, noting that those are key aspects of any energy policy and the prevailing trends in energy generation. Power generators are turning away from coal “on their own free will,” he said, with Missouri electric companies and municipal utilities increasingly shifting plans toward wind and solar — economic momentum that can’t be reversed by politics.“When you look at what’s been going on the last few years,” Campbell said, “that horse has left the gate.”


