JEFFERSON CITY • Although he’s been governor for less than a year, Gov. Mike Parson has appointed or hired at least 13 former state lawmakers to serve in key posts in his administration.On Wednesday, his latest appointee, former Sen. Brian Munzlinger, appeared briefly before a Senate panel en route to his likely confirmation to the Missouri Probation and Parole Board by the Legislature’s upper chamber on Thursday.Parson appointed the Republican from Williamstown to the $86,000 per year post two weeks ago. The board reviews whether prison inmates should be granted parole or conditional release.

Munzlinger, a farmer, left his $35,900 per year job as a lawmaker in January after 16 years in the House and Senate. He served alongside Parson in both chambers for much of his tenure.He faced few questions from members of the Senate Gubernatorial Appointments Committee, several of whom he previously served with.“It’s different sitting on this side,” Munzlinger told the panel.It is not uncommon for governors to appoint members of the Legislature to various boards and commissions.For example, former Gov. Eric Greitens named former Sen. Jason Crowell to the Missouri Housing Development Commission and former Rep. Paul Fitzwater, R-Potosi, to the probation and parole board.Greitens also appointed former Sen. Ryan Silvey to the Public Service Commission, which regulates utilities.Silvey’s appointment raised eyebrows because he had repeatedly clashed with Greitens, leaving observers to speculate the governor was attempting to remove a critic from the Legislature.
In 2011, former Gov. Jay Nixon denied accusations that he appointed former Rep. Dennis Fowler of Advance to the Board of Probation and Parole as a political reward for his vote against an income tax cut.Fowler was among 15 Republicans who had to uphold the Democratic governor's veto of the bill.Since taking office in June, Parson has used his appointment power to name at least 12 former lawmakers to posts within his administration.Former Senate Majority Leader Mike Kehoe of Jefferson City took over Parson’s old job as lieutenant governor. Former Sen. Eric Scmitt of Glendale was named attorney general in January after Josh Hawley vacated the position for a seat in the U.S. Senate.
Former House Budget Chairman Scott Fitzpatrick is now the state treasurer, filling Schmitt's vacancy.Parson also picked former House Speaker Todd Richardson to be the director of the state’s Medicaid program.Former Rep. Marsha Haefner, R-Oakville, was hired as a liaison in Parson’s St. Louis satellite office. Former Rep. Justin Alferman, R-Hermann, is serving as Parson’s chief legislative director.Lyndall Fraker, a former state representative from Marshfield, was tabbed to oversee the implementation of the state’s new medical marijuana law and former Sen. Jay Wasson, R-Nixa, took a position on the state tourism board.Former Rep. Don Phillips was named to the Probation and Parole Board after he left the Legislature due to term limits and former Rep. Robert Cornejo, R-St. Peters, became a member of the Missouri Labor and Industrial Relations Commission.Other former lawmakers appointed to positions by Parson include Bob Nance of Excelsior Springs, who was named to the Clay County Board of Election Commissioners in November and Gary Nodler of Joplin, who joined the Coordinating Board for Higher Education in August.


