JEFFERSON CITY • The Missouri House on Tuesday gave initial approval to a $30 billion spending plan for next fiscal year, a blueprint that includes a new scholarship program, new money for roads and more money for education.Next year’s spending plan assumes modest growth in revenue of 2 percent. This year’s budget also assumed a modest increase. But, so far this year, the state has seen no growth in revenue. The opposite is true.As of Monday, revenue collections were down $353 million from the same point last year, or 5.3 percent. The figures mean Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, could be forced to freeze some spending before the fiscal year ends June 30.

It is unclear whether or how the Senate will address the shortfalls; analysts hope collections will ultimately grow by the end of tax filing season.Medicaid funding would again increase next year under the House’s budget. According to the plan, the state would spend $11 billion on the health care program for the poor, up from $10.5 billion in this year’s budget.The increasing costs have drawn scrutiny from officials, who want to spend $34 million next year on a Medicaid “transformation” effort outlined in a report released last month.















            New report recommends $1 billion in annual savings with overhaul of Medicaid in Missouri

The state could alter reimbursement rates for hospitals, doctors and nursing homes, shift more people to home-care services and better manage prescription drug costs as a way to rein in rising costs.




In one of Tuesday’s most high-profile moves, the GOP-controlled House broke with Parson in regard to the governor’s plan to borrow $350 million for bridge projects.The House instead voted to spend $100 million from general revenue on road projects.Rep. Jon Carpenter, D-Kansas City, said the state had not historically used general revenue for such projects, instead relying on the road fund for improvements. Carpenter said the general revenue should be used elsewhere.He proposed using $69 million of the $100 million for road funds to increase funding for home health services. House Budget Chairman Cody Smith, R-Carthage, said the state had already devoted more money to the issue elsewhere in the budget.Carpenter also proposed using $31 million of the $100 million on the public defender’s office, which is chronically underfunded.His amendments failed.“Right now, Missouri’s roads and bridges are in need of repair,” said Smith, who argued the state should use general revenue for road repairs to avoid raising gasoline taxes or borrowing money.Parson’s proposed borrowing of $350 million to fund the repairs would cost about $100 million in interest over 15 years.Smith wants the Legislature to keep the $100 million figure constant for four years, but that means lawmakers could raid the line item in future budgets.The House budget increases funding for the public defender’s office by about $1.6 million, which includes $1.1 million for juvenile offices in St. Louis and Kansas City, and $500,000 to address a case backlog.















            Missouri children are waiving their right to legal counsel. That's a problem, some lawmakers say.

"Children, and particularly children who get into trouble, don't exercise good judgment," said Rep. Ingrid Burnett. "And so, expecting them to exercise good judgment when it comes to waiving their rights I think is a stretch."




The office would still be underfunded by about $30 million under the House legislation, according to the office and an outside audit.Education fundingThe House also designated $3.55 billion to the state’s K-12 education funding formula, a $62 million increase over this year.
Smith said the amount would fully fund the state’s school aid formula.The House also designated $108 million to school transportation costs, a $5 million increase over this year.Rep. Judy Morgan, D-Kansas City, said the proposed transportation funding levels still “aren’t even in the ballpark” of what is needed.















            Missouri takes districts for a bumpy ride when it comes to bus funds

School bus inspections show rural schools may suffer more than suburban ones. 




School districts are paying for transportation costs by taking money out of other pots, she said. Other Democrats said overall education funding still was inadequate.The House designated $195 million for early childhood special education programs, a $3 million increase over the current year’s appropriation.The program is designed to improve a child’s skills before the child enters kindergarten. According to the department’s budget request, 97 percent of students “substantially improved” their skills upon exiting the program, higher than the national average.
Rep. Peter Merideth, D-St. Louis, sponsored an amendment that would have given high-need families priority when applying for Parents As Teachers services. He said 1,500 high-need families are on a wait list because the state has underfunded the program. Merideth’s amendment failed amid concerns from Republicans about local officials maintaining control over the program.The House also voted to keep core funding at universities constant, and devoted $18 million to Parson’s new “Fast Track” scholarship program.The House authorized devoting $10 million in unused lottery funds to pay for part of the Fast Track program, freeing up general revenue that would have gone to the scholarships. General revenue was then shifted to cover other priorities, including $2.5 million for rural broadband efforts.The House rejected, on a 42-99 vote, a Democratic attempt to allow public universities to charge undocumented immigrants living in Missouri in-state tuition. The state currently requires schools to charge international tuition to such students, costing those students thousands of dollars more than other residents.“I certainly think that we should prioritize those that have legal status in our state first,” said Smith, who opposed the amendment.Democrats argued the amendment would not negatively affect other residents, and would improve the state’s economy by helping students better themselves.“Yes, you can work here, yes, you can pay taxes here, but what you cannot do is pay in-state tuition,” said Rep. Bruce Franks, D-St. Louis.Failed amendmentsDemocrats, who control less than a third of House seats, attempted to influence state policy in other ways, including offering an amendment to forbid state spending on capital punishment.“This is about whether or not we should spend money as a state to kill people,” Merideth said.Rep. Don Rone, R-Portageville, suggested it was hypocritical of Democrats, who had voted to “kill babies” by supporting abortion, to advocate for ending the death penalty. “The babies have not done anything,” Rone said. On death row inmates, “they made their own bed, so to speak.”A handful of Republicans joined Democrats to support the amendment, but it failed on a vote of 43-102.Democrats also wanted to block state aid to police departments that allow “shackling of pregnant women who are in labor.” Republicans voted down the amendment on a voice vote.


