JEFFERSON CITY • A section of Lindbergh Boulevard in south St. Louis County has been named after a former state lawmaker.Gov. Mike Parson signed legislation Monday designating the heavily commercial stretch between Interstate 55 and Lin Ferry Drive as the “Cloria Brown Memorial Highway.”Brown, a Republican, represented the Mehlville area three times. Her first two-year term was in 2010. After losing in 2012, she returned to win the district in 2014 and 2016.

Brown died last year after battling cancer.
In a ceremony in Parson's office, lawmakers hailed Brown's service."As a state representative, she served with grace and commitment," said Rep. Patricia Pike, R-Adrian.
“We are grateful for Cloria Brown’s service to the State of Missouri. She worked hard to make a difference for constituents and to the state,”  said Sen. Scott Sifton, D-Affton.The legislation, which was approved unanimously in January by the House and Senate, calls for private donations to pay for the signs, which would then be erected by state highway crews.


