JEFFERSON CITY • A Republican the Missouri Senate once attempted to ban from serving on the Missouri Board of Education again is now seeking a seat in the chamber that rejected him.Eddy Justice, 46, a GOP organizer from Poplar Bluff, announced Monday he was running in 2020 to replace term-limited state Sen. Doug Libla, R-Poplar Bluff, in the Missouri Senate.













Eddy Justice, owner and an agent of Eddy Justice State Farm Insurance. Courtesy of State Farm


Courtesy of State Farm




The State Farm insurance agent says he supports President Donald Trump’s “Make America Great Again” agenda and is running as a “conservative outsider” to “stand up for (constituents’) rights as Americans and to keep government off our backs.”Former Gov. Eric Greitens appointed Justice to the education board in 2017 as part of the former governor’s plan to oust then-Education Commissioner Margie Vandeven.Justice and four other Greitens loyalists on the board did fire Vandeven, but the strong-arm tactics infuriated a bipartisan coalition of senators.The move against Vandeven took place before senators had a chance to approve or reject Greitens’ nominees.The Senate ultimately declined to approve Justice and four other nominees. That meant, according to the state constitution, they could never again serve on the education board. The nominees withdrew their names from consideration and argued that, because of the maneuver, they would not be subject the lifetime ban.Questions over the validity of the lifetime ban would likely be settled by the courts if a future governor chose to reappoint any of the nominees.Libla, a close ally of Sen. Gary Romine, a Farmington Republican who advocated for the bans, said he would not comment on whether he would support Justice’s campaign.“There will probably be a primary for my seat,” he said. “It would be inappropriate for me to be making any comments one way or the other at this time.”The board under Gov. Mike Parson, the former lieutenant governor who replaced Greitens in June, has since re-hired Vandeven as education commissioner.
Justice said he would advocate for charter school expansion if elected.“I believe we have to give these kids an option if their schools are failing,” he said in an interview. “If it comes in the form of charter schools, so be it.”















            Vouchers, charter school expansion are getting push from Republicans in Missouri



Libla opposes expansion, saying charter schools have a “very dismal record of success in urban school districts.” The schools are currently allowed only in St. Louis and Kansas City.
Justice also said “all options are on the table” in regard to increasing the state’s gasoline tax to fund road and bridge repairs, something Libla has supported.Justice said past differences with the Senate would not impair his relationship with other senators.“They’re professionals, as I believe I am, and I think that if elected we’ll be able to work together in a productive manner for the people of our districts and the people of Missouri,” he said.The 25th Senate District takes in most Bootheel counties — Butler, Dunklin, Mississippi, New Madrid, Pemiscot, Stoddard — as well as Carter and Shannon counties.No other Republicans have announced bids for the seat.As far as the general election, some Bootheel counties and Shannon County historically have had Democratic tendencies, but voters have shunned the party on the state and federal level for several cycles.Libla in 2012 won 56 percent of the vote, besting Democrat Terry Swinger, who won 44 percent. Libla cruised to re-election in 2016, winning nearly 70 percent of the vote.


