ST. LOUIS • As flooding pounds areas of the Missouri River basin in Nebraska, Iowa and South Dakota, downstream river levels in St. Louis are poised to crest over the coming week.By next Thursday, the Mississippi River at St. Louis is expected to creep into a “moderate” flood stage, according to National Weather Service data. With the river expected to rise more than 7 feet in the next week, some impacts could be felt in low-lying areas and various floodgates will be closed along the St. Louis riverfront.Reaches of the Mississippi River upstream from its confluence with the Missouri River can also expect to see some floodwater, particularly in places like Clarksville, in Pike County, where there are no levees in place. The town requested sandbags from the St. Louis District of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, according to Scott Ross, the district’s chief of public affairs.

Besides sending sandbags to the area, Ross said the corps is also keeping an eye on Lock and Dam 24 in a nearby stretch of the Mississippi River.“We are anticipating that we may have to close it,” Ross said. “We think the forecast will bring us to that at some point next week.”Despite the extended forecast of “flood stage” conditions, other localized flood impacts around the St. Louis area may be limited, according to Mark Fuchs, a hydrologist with the National Weather Service office in St. Charles.He explained that “minor impacts start kicking in” when rivers reach a “flood stage” designation — which the area is expected to experience from the weekend through Wednesday, as water rises. At those levels, he said impacts are typically confined to lesser-traveled roads, athletic fields and other things that commonly occupy floodplains along rivers.But then, once rivers reach a “moderate flood stage” — the next level of severity, and the one projected to hit the region late next week — larger roadways and some buildings can be affected, Fuchs said.Things are much worse farther upstream on the Missouri River, where flooding has already prompted a range of emergency responses, including the release of water Thursday held behind the Gavins Point Dam near Yankton, S.D.Additionally, high water and dangerous currents led the U.S. Coast Guard to announce Friday that all boat traffic would be halted on a 100-mile stretch of the river, from about 50 miles south of Omaha, Neb., to St. Joseph, Mo.Meanwhile, any vessels between the Kansas City area and St. Joseph were requested to maintain a minimal wake “to minimize levee damage.”
“Restrictions to operations will be lifted as soon as conditions improve,” the Coast Guard announcement said.Missouri Gov. Mike Parson surveyed flooded areas in northwestern Missouri on Friday afternoon. His office indicated that 140,000 acres of the region’s floodplain were expected to see an impact from flooding, and said that work was underway in communities such as St. Joseph to sandbag and bolster levees.
.@GovParsonMO survey’s NWMO flood impact this afternoon, several levees are broken and water running over the top, nearly 140,000 farm acres are expected to be impacted in the flood plain. pic.twitter.com/ylX7V718Co— Steele Shippy (@SteeleShippy) March 15, 2019



pic.twitter.com/klkklucYDb— Steele Shippy (@SteeleShippy) March 15, 2019

South of Omaha, multiple locations in Nebraska were bracing for record crests along the Missouri River, Fuchs said.Those unprecedented flood levels, though, won’t surge all the way downstream to St. Louis, he added. Instead, the high water will be dispersed as swollen river channels widen and gain the capacity to hold more flow.“By the time it gets into our neck of the woods, it’s not as big a deal,” said Fuchs.The flooding upstream is a result of snowmelt and recent heavy rain. Fuchs warned that plenty of snow and ice remain in parts of the Upper Mississippi watershed, such as Minnesota and Wisconsin, setting the stage for other possible flood risks to come — particularly if that snowmelt is accompanied by more rain.“If that happens too fast, we could see a return to these conditions or possibly higher,” he said. “If we have a big rain event, it could get interesting.”















            Flooding forecast: How high will area rivers get?

A look at current stages on area rivers, plus forecast maximums and historical records. 







