JEFFERSON CITY • Despite biting criticism from lawmakers on both sides of the aisle, Gov. Mike Parson credited his outgoing tax chief Friday for implementing reforms at the Missouri Department of Revenue.In an announcement less than 24 hours after the Post-Dispatch reported the pending resignation of embattled Revenue Director Joel Walters, Parson named Ken Zellers as acting director of the agency that oversees the collection of billions of dollars in income taxes, license plate fees and other revenue in the state.Zellers, a former Anheuser-Busch InBev executive, currently serves as chief operating officer at the department.

Parson said Walters’ two years at the agency were a success.“His leadership and transformative vision helped to turn around the Department of Revenue, leading to increased customer service, identifying efficiencies that led to significant budget savings, and implementing a number of conservative reforms that helped improve and streamline services for Missouri taxpayers,” Parson said.That’s a far cry from the reaction of lawmakers, who have kept Walters on the hot seat for weeks over his admitted mishandling of the implementation of the federal tax cuts.“Missouri taxpayers deserve competency and honesty in their state agencies. The Department of Revenue’s failures and subsequent cover-up will impact the pocketbooks and trust of many Missourians. As legislators, we have a duty to hold bureaucrats accountable when they’re not forthright with the taxpayers, and I’ve never shied away from that,” said Rep. Robert Ross, R-Yukon, who chaired a special committee that probed problems at the agency.“The resignation of the director is an important step forward, but the department has much more work to do to regain the trust of the public. I’ve asked the committee to continue its work in investigating this issue and working with the new director to ensure Missouri taxpayers are protected,” added House Speaker Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield.Walters, who was brought to Missouri to run the taxing agency in 2017 by former Gov. Eric Greitens, weathered months of tough questioning from lawmakers over his role in altering the state’s withholding tables after the federal tax cut went into effect last year.Walters testified several times to the Legislature that the state’s withholding tables didn’t correctly account for the standard deduction — the amount of income taxpayers can subtract before income tax — in calculating the federal income tax deduction. Walters said the withholding error had been discovered in September after existing for at least 15 years.Walters ordered changes to the tables that he believed would reduce the impact of taxpayers withholding too much. The change went into effect in October 2018.In February, he acknowledged that it wasn’t an old error, but a mistake on his part.
The pressure on Walters was amplified Thursday when the Columbia Daily Tribune reported that the Department of Revenue had initially prepared a news release last year cautioning taxpayers to increase their income tax withholdings for the remainder of the year or face the potential of having to pay taxes instead of receiving a refund.Estimates in December show that refunds are expected to drop by $231 million, while payments are expected to increase by $134 million.As lawmakers turned up the heat on Walters, Parson reacted by saying the hearings were “political grandstanding.”Parson’s Republican counterparts in the Legislature said the resignation is proof their actions were not politically motivated.
“I’m proud of the oversight committee for standing up for the hard-working families who may end up with a surprise tax bill this April because the department failed to do its job. Clearly, the committee was not grandstanding, but instead was standing up for the people of our state,” said House Floor Leader Rob Vescovo, R-Arnold.House Minority Leader Crystal Quade, D-Springfield, said Walters’ departure does not absolve Parson for his role in the department’s meltdown.“The resignation of Director Walters is just a first step that must include Governor Parson taking full responsibility for his administration’s failures and committing to providing relief to those Missourians who are in a financial bind as a result,” Quade said.Parson spokesman Steele Shippy defended the governor.“Typical democrat socialist response, advocating that the government take more money from hardworking Missourians paychecks, while Governor Parson works to ensure all Missourians benefit from historical federal and state tax cuts,” he said in response to Quade.Walters, who earned $128,200 annually, plans to leave the agency on March 22.“I appreciate the opportunity of working alongside Governor Parson and his administration. They are doing fantastic things for the citizens of Missouri, and I am extremely proud that I have played a part in that success,” he said in a statement.


