JEFFERSON CITY • A two-term member of the Missouri House will kick off his campaign on Saturday for a seat in the state Senate.Rep. Doug Beck, D-Affton, has scheduled a fundraiser at the Affton Elks Club on Saturday as he begins his bid to replace term-limited Sen. Scott Sifton in the Legislature’s upper chamber.





















            State Rep. Doug Beck

State Rep. Doug Beck, D-Affton 






Sifton, who has represented the 1st Senate District since 2012, announced earlier that he will run for governor in 2020.A possible Beck opponent could be former Rep. Marsha Haefner, a Republican who served eight years representing the Oakville area and could not run again because of term limits.“I’m still considering it. But I will make a decision very soon,” said Haefner, who is now working in Gov. Mike Parson’s St. Louis office as a liaison for the chief executive.Beck has represented the 92nd District in the House since 2017, after he beat Republican Daniel Bogle.
He cruised to re-election last year with 60 percent of the vote over Republican Bill Heisse.
Beck, a union pipefitter for more than 30 years, is a St. Louis area native who graduated from Lindbergh High School and attended St. Louis Community College.In an earlier announcement, Beck said he’s looking forward to serving in a chamber with fewer members.“An individual can make more of a difference as a state senator where, with just 34 members, more time can be devoted to serious debate and finding areas of bipartisan agreement where progress can be made,” Beck said.The House has 163 members.The district boundaries stretch from the Oakville area north to Brentwood. The seat had been in Republican hands until Sifton won the post.


