JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri officials are forming a high-level task force to determine whether it’s feasible to build a high-speed, people-moving link between St. Louis and Kansas City.Although the technology for a so-called “hyperloop” remains unproven, House Speaker Elijah Haahr,  R-Springfield, launched the panel Tuesday, saying Missouri could establish itself as the “global epicenter” for research and development of the experimental project.“We are early in the process, but ahead of the game when it comes to this issue,” Haahr said.

In October, Kansas City-based engineering company Black & Veatch said the pneumatic tube transportation line that would transport passengers along the 250-mile expanse between the two anchor cities in less than 30 minutes would be feasible to build.The company estimated the cost of running the line somewhat parallel to Interstate 70 at between $7 billion and $10 billion.Lt. Gov. Mike Kehoe, a former senator and chairman of the Missouri Highways and Transportation Commission, will chair the task force.“We are a state that has the ingenuity, technology, the resources to look at what’s next in the future,” Kehoe said.But, Kehoe added he would not support spending state money on the project until the state has figured out how to fund its current backlog of road and bridge projects.Other members of the panel include Senate Majority Leader Caleb Rowden, R-Columbia, Sen. Brian Williams, D-University City, and University of Missouri President Mun Choi.
Talks about bringing the technology to Missouri has been in the public eye since the state unveiled its now-failed bid to lure Amazon's second headquarters to the state in 2017.As part of the package, state officials said Amazon could build in both St. Louis and Kansas City and be linked by the hyperloop.The seed for the committee was apparently planted in December by the St. Louis Regional Chamber, which is spearheading the effort. In emails obtained by the Post-Dispatch, Austin Walker, director of governmental affairs for the chamber, sought to enlist Gov. Mike Parson to attend a January meeting at the hyperloop testing grounds in Nevada.
“Obviously, the governor’s participation would be incredibly helpful,” Walker wrote.Later, after the meeting in the desert was postponed, Walker told Parson chief of staff Aaron Willard that he’d approached Haahr about creating the task force.“I have asked the speaker if he would be willing to consider a special committee to look into and strengthen the Missouri proposal, and he was very supportive of the idea,” Walker wrote.Also working behind the scenes is Steve Tilley, a former speaker of the Missouri House who serves as a lobbyist for Heartland Hyperloop Inc.Over the next several months, the committee will hold public meetings in St. Louis, Jefferson City, and Kansas City. The group will present its findings in September.“This is a chance for Missouri to position itself as a global tech leader,” said task force member Andrew Smith of the St. Louis Regional Chamber. “Bringing this technology to Missouri would serve as a powerful talent magnet and a significant boost for our technology, logistics, and manufacturing sectors.”


