JEFFERSON CITY • A dark-money group advocating for changes to how colleges and universities handle sexual misconduct claims has hired more than a dozen lobbyists to patrol the halls of the Missouri Capitol.According to the Missouri Ethics Commission, Kingdom Principles Inc. on Tuesday hired three lobbyists: Doug Nelson and Heath Clarkston of Lathrop Gage Consulting; and Kurt Schaefer, former Republican state senator from Columbia.On Thursday, the group added 10 more lobbyists to its rolls, including James Harris, who is an ally to Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican.

The group had previously hired Richard McIntosh and Matthew Alsager to push for changes to Missouri law.Records show that one of the lobbyists hired, Kyna Iman, ended her association with the group Friday, bringing down to 14 the number of lobbyists working for Kingdom Principles.According to the MEC, five of the lobbyists work for Flotron & McIntosh LLC, whose co-founder Richard McIntosh has represented St. Louis County-based World Wide Technology in the Legislature since 2000.World Wide Technology was founded by St. Louis billionaire David Steward in 1990. Steward is at least partially funding Kingdom Principles.Kingdom Principles is funding the Missouri Campus Due Process Coalition.Because of Kingdom Principles' status as a 501(c)(4) nonprofit, it does not have to reveal its donors, but a spokesman for the group confirmed Steward's involvement this week.
Such lobbyist hiring sprees are not uncommon for entities who have interests before the state. Better Together, the group seeking a merger between St. Louis County and the city of St. Louis, has also hired a squadron of lobbyists, for example.The show of force comes as public and private colleges around the state — and some associated student groups — continue to blast the pending legislation that would afford those facing discipline by college officials more hearing room privileges. 















            Two advocates for Title IX changes want cases routed to their wives’ courtroom

"It unquestionably creates a perceived conflict," said Rep. Gina Mitten of Richmond Heights, who is the ranking Democrat on the House committee considering the measure. 





The measure would allow either party to a complaint to transfer their case out of their school and to the state Administrative Hearing Commission, a formal process that would open complaints up to public scrutiny. Most Title IX complaints are handled informally, officials say.The legislation also would potentially allow the accused to sue the accuser if the accuser's claims are not proven. The accused could also sue their school for damages if that person's due process rights are not upheld, among other changes.Proponents say the changes are necessary to ensure a fair process for both parties, but opponents say the changes would discourage victims from coming forward. Opponents are also worried a new state law would conflict with federal rules that are in the works.The Senate version of the legislation is scheduled to be debated before the full chamber next week, while the House version is still pending in committee.The legislation is House Bill 573 and Senate Bill 259.


