JEFFERSON CITY • A new blueprint to fix roads and bridges faces a potentially bumpy ride in the Missouri Senate.A day after House leaders abandoned Gov. Mike Parson’s plan to borrow $350 million to fix 250 bridges, Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, suggested the alternative financing proposal floated in the House could put millions of dollars in federal funds at risk.“I don’t want to lose the opportunity to draw down federal money,” Schatz said Thursday.

Among the projects that could be scuttled if the state loses federal dollars are long awaited upgrades to the Interstate 70 bridge over the Missouri River in Rocheport, west of Columbia, Schatz said.His comments show that the road to funding upgrades and maintenance for Missouri’s transportation infrastructure remains filled with political potholes as the Legislature rumbles to the midpoint in its annual session.On Wednesday, House Budget Chairman Cody Smith, R-Carthage, said instead of borrowing money to fund bridge repairs, he is recommending the state use $100 million in general revenue to pay for the fixes.The concept won support from some members of the Senate, who already were poised to suggest alternatives to Parson’s borrowing proposal.“It’s definitely a plan I think I could get behind,” said Sen. Denny Hoskins, R-Warrensburg.“We already have a record amount of revenue coming into the state. With all that money coming in the door, why not take a portion of that and direct it into the highway fund,” said Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring.The state’s general fund revenues for the fiscal year ending in June were up over the previous year, but receipts for this fiscal year are running about $300 million behind expectations. Officials say they believe that amount could be made up as people pay their 2018 tax bills.
Parson’s plan would allow for the sale of bonds to pay for four years of projects at a cost of about $29.9 million annually for 15 years. The bonds would have an interest rate of 3.25 percent, meaning taxpayers would be on the hook for $100 million in interest payments.The governor’s proposal came after he had campaigned hard to persuade voters in November to approve a phased-in 10-cent increase in the gasoline tax.
After voters rejected the tax hike, Parson said his bonding plan could serve as a stopgap until support could be found for a long-range transportation funding program.In a statement Wednesday, Parson’s office expressed confidence that a final agreement could be reached before lawmakers adjourn in May.Eigel also acknowledged the House plan would not address the state’s long-term infrastructure needs.“This is a short-term solution to how we’re going to address some of the most pressing needs in our infrastructure,” Eigel said.Schatz, who also supported the gasoline tax increase, said he could not commit to the House plan. But, like Parson, he said he is pleased there are talks underway.“There’s opportunities for discussion,” Schatz said. “I think all options are on the table.”Other road funding proposals being discussed under the Capitol dome include raising vehicle fees and an alternative registration system based on mileage instead of horsepower.


