JEFFERSON CITY • A heated debate is brewing in the Missouri House and Senate over a series of proposals that would alter the landscape of public education in Missouri.In the House, legislators had been poised to consider a plan Wednesday that would allow charter schools beyond the boundaries of St. Louis and Kansas City — a controversial initiative that was destined to cause fissures within both the GOP caucus and the Legislative Black Caucus.With a showdown looming, legislative leaders instead delayed debate on the matter, giving them at least another week to try and secure the needed number of votes.

"There's been some fierce a-- conversations," said freshman state Rep. Wiley Price, D-St. Louis, who said Wednesday morning that he had not decided which way to vote.GOP leadership, from the governor's office to the House speaker's office, was actively engaged in trying to push the measure through the lower chamber."If I knew, I couldn't tell you," said Rep. Shamed Dogan, R-Ballwin, when asked what kind of pressure was being exerted by leadership on rank-and-file legislators. "There's a lot of negotiations going on."Rep. Elaine Gannon, a De Soto Republican and former educator, was tight-lipped about her opposition to the measure."I'm against it, but no comment," she said shortly before the House came to order at 10 a.m. Wednesday.Rep. Rebecca Roeber, R-Lee's Summit, is sponsoring the plan leadership was pushing. The package would allow charter schools to open in St. Louis County and in cities across the state with populations greater than 30,000.Charter schools are currently allowed only in St. Louis and Kansas City. Under the proposal, St. Louis County, St. Charles County, Jefferson County and cities like Columbia, Jefferson City, Springfield and Joplin could see charter schools if the legislation were signed into law.Charter schools are designed to be innovative alternatives to the school districts in which they operate, but opponents say they reduce funds that would otherwise go to public schools.The push for votes in the House also came as the Senate was poised to debate education-related legislation that school advocacy groups are scrambling to stop.The proposal sponsored by Sen. Andrew Koenig, R-Manchester, would create  a new 100 percent state tax credit capped at $25 million per year for taxpayer contributions to third-party organizations.A debate on the plan was expected to begin Wednesday, but it, too, was postponed while leaders determine if the measure can win enough support to advance.Koenig’s proposal would establish the Missouri Empowerment Scholarship Accounts Program. In addition to allowing parents to use the money to finance their child’s elementary and secondary education at a school of their choice, it would change the way students can transfer from low-performing districts and schools.The measure would affect school districts throughout the St. Louis region, including the 23,000-student city district, the Ferguson-Florissant district, as well as Normandy, Parkway, Wentzville and the Francis Howell district in St. Charles County.
The renewed debate on charter schools is partly the result of Gov. Mike Parson’s bid to create a $22 million scholarship program for adults seeking to learn new skills for high demand jobs.Debate on the governor’s so-called “Fast Track” program ground to halt last month as Republican members sought to attach amendments to it that could allow for the expansion of charter schools and educational savings accounts that could help parents pay for private schools.Senate Majority Leader Caleb Rowden, R-Columbia, told reporters last week the two issues have become tied together as the Legislature moves forward.“I don’t think it’s any secret that there are some folks who would like to see us have a conversation on education reform kind of as a part of that discussion,” Rowden said. “I would say there is a good possibility that we’ll see the charter bill or the ESA bill on the floor next week.”
Advocacy groups on both sides of the issue have dug in and are lobbying lawmakers.The American Federation for Children, for example, is among the out-of-state special interest groups pushing for the change.The California-based organization, which supports charter school expansion efforts, formerly was headed by U.S. Department of Education Secretary Betsy DeVos, a longtime advocate for charter schools.The group has contributed more than $175,000 to Republican interests in the past two years.On March 1, the American Federation for Children hired Scott Jensen, the former speaker of the Wisconsin House of Representatives, to lobby in Missouri.Jensen, a charter school advocate, was convicted of three misconduct in office felonies in 2006 and sentenced to 15 months in prison. In 2010, he reached an agreement to have the charges dismissed.School groups opposed to the changes also reported a heightened level of engagement.Brent Ghan, deputy executive director for the Missouri School Boards’ Association, said local school district officials have been flooding lawmaker offices with their concerns.“Our members are extremely engaged in this issue and have been contacting their local legislators about it in significant numbers. They are concerned about both of these issues,” Ghan said. “We’ve seen a higher level of engagement from our members on both of these issues than we’ve seen in a long time.”Doug Hayter, executive director of the Missouri Association of School Administrators, said scheduling both bills to be debated in separate chambers on the same day may indicate that Republican leaders wanted to dilute the power of the opponents.“It certainly makes you wonder,” Hayter said. “For us, it’s pretty much all hands on deck. We’re definitely putting out alerts to all of our education advocates.”


