JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson’s administration is moving to shut down a north St. Louis County day care after a worker there was filmed last month tossing a 3-year-old girl across a room.The Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services on Friday sent a letter to Sharon Phillips Williams, the registered agent of Brighter Day Care and Preschool in Pine Lawn, telling her the state was revoking the facility’s license.Emergency crews on Feb. 1 took a 3-year-old girl, with a deep gash in her head, to a hospital, where she received stitches. As police were investigating, they also discovered a second victim, whom another worker allegedly threw on a cot. Two day care workers now face abuse charges stemming from the incidents.

“These actions do not demonstrate that Brighter Day Care & Preschool, Inc. is able to provide a safe environment for children,” Sue Porting, administrator of the Department of Health and Senior Services’ child care section, said in the 17-page letter mailed on Friday.











Google Earth



The day care has a month to appeal the decision to the state Administrative Hearing Commission and will be allowed to remain open during the appeals process. The state and the day care could enter into a settlement agreement as the two sides await a hearing.A woman who answered the phone at the day care on Monday hung up when asked whether anyone was available to comment.The letter says state inspectors substantiated two other complaints at the same day care last year.The DHSS wrote to the day care on July 20 that it substantiated a complaint that a 3-year-old boy was “slammed” on a cot by a worker on May 29. The child complained of neck pain and side pain, and had scratches on his neck.In August, the state substantiated a complaint that in July, a day care van driver dropped a 6-year-old child off at the wrong house and that the driver left without ensuring the child was with the proper caretaker, according to the letter.Dr. Randall Williams, director of DHSS, said at a news conference Monday that the department had received complaints about Brighter Day Care prior to 2018.“In this particular facility’s case, those were investigated and not felt to be a systemic process problem, but more of an individual problem,” Williams said of complaints made prior to this year. “However, more recently, it was determined that this was a facility problem.”
Parson, a Republican, announced the move at the same news conference that he was launching a child care working group that would examine industry issues. Various stakeholders will report back to the governor by June 1, he said.“Missouri parents who place their child into the hands of a child care provider expect their child will get quality, safe care while they work hard to support their family,” Parson said in a statement. “I am committed to doing everything I can to protect our children. As a father, grandfather, and Governor, this must be a priority for us all.”The incident at the Brighter Day Care and Preschool in Pine Lawn was the latest of a string of incidents at St. Louis-area day cares.In November, KTVI (Channel 2) published video footage from 2016 of 3- and 4-year-olds engaging in fist fights at the Adventure Learning Center in St. Louis. Attorney General Eric Schmitt is investigating what his office called a “day care fight club.”
In December, police found a dead infant at an unlicensed day care in Maplewood. Legislation by state Sen. Jill Schupp, D-Creve Coeur, seeks to further crack down on unlicensed child care facilities, which have caused problems in Missouri for years. The measure would add accountability measures and closes a loophole in state regulations that allows a caretaker to oversee an unlimited number of related children.“When you open your home for business, the business of caring for children, there is no room for over-extension,” Schupp said during a Senate committee hearing on Monday. “Not being able to adequately serve your customers is not like selling an under-cooked burger or measuring the length of plywood incorrectly. Not serving your customers when you open your home to childcare can and does result in neglect, injury and horribly, even death.”The Post-Dispatch reported in June that St. Louis-area providers are grappling with a shortage of preschool teachers, who in private and nonprofit settings make an average of $12 an hour. A national survey found preschool teachers can make closer to $20 an hour working for public school districts.St. Louis-area families also were struggling to find quality care for children. Wait lists at centers with good reputations can reach six to 18 months before a spot opens, the Post-Dispatch report said.


