JEFFERSON CITY • For months, the director of Missouri’s tax collection agency claimed he discovered and corrected a 15-year-old error in the state’s tax tables that has resulted in people getting smaller refunds on their 2018 income tax returns.On Wednesday, he painted a different picture of the events that have led to vexing reductions in 2018 income tax returns for millions of Missourians.In front of a House committee investigating the Missouri Department of Revenue, Director Joel Walters said he himself ordered the change to reduce the amount of money withheld from a worker’s check in response to changes that were put in place after federal tax cuts went into effect last year.

“It felt like in my judgment making that formulaic change made this more accurate,” Walters said. “I was trying to do the right thing, and I was trying to make the calculation more accurate.”The revelation came a week after Gov. Mike Parson scolded members of the House for probing the tax changes, calling their grilling of Walters on two previous occasions “political grandstanding.”Members of the House Special Committee on Government Oversight, still rankled by Parson’s defense of Walters, said their suspicions had been correct.“It certainly appears to me that the story has been changing,” said Rep. Dirk Deaton, R-Noel. “That is problematic.”For many taxpayers, the tinkering by Walters, combined with the federal tax changes, will mean a lower tax refund or a higher tax bill on their 2018 taxes. The tables, he said, failed to account for the standard deduction, which is the amount of income taxpayers can subtract in calculating their federal taxes.For a married couple making a total of $100,000 and each claiming one dependent, the department says their 2018 refund would be $67, down from $516 for 2017.
A single filer with no dependents making $36,000 annually would face a tax bill of $58 for 2018, rather than a refund of $53 as in 2017.With about four weeks of tax filings on the books, the average refund is down $78 and the average tax due is up $65, said Walters, who was hired by then- Gov. Eric Greitens in 2017 after 35 years in the private sector.The state also is lagging behind in tax revenues as taxpayers delay paying their bills.
The department has since issued new withholding tables that went into effect on Jan. 1, so the issue should not play a role in 2019.Walters also told the committee that his department had asked tax preparation software companies such as TurboTax to not charge penalties to affected Missourians.“We’re not going to be enforcing penalties,” Walters said.In addition to trying to spread the message on the agency’s social media accounts, Walters also said the department had mailed 25,000 notices about the changes to businesses and planned to send 200,000 more.Despite the prodding of lawmakers, Walters did not say he regretted the department’s actions.“If it was misleading to use the word ‘error,’ then I shouldn’t have,” Walters said. “I don’t know if I regret it. I still think I did the right thing.”


