JEFFERSON CITY • The Missouri House handed Gov. Mike Parson a victory Thursday, approving a mostly intact version of his proposed scholarship program for adults seeking jobs in high-demand trades.Although funding issues remain a potential roadblock to the so-called “Fast Track” program, the measure was approved on a bipartisan 101-49 vote.Parson, who took over in June, has made workforce development a key plank in his first legislative session. The program is included in the $30 billion budget proposal he unveiled Jan. 16.

The Republican chief executive says the top priority for most businesses in picking a location is the quality of the workforce. Parson believes companies may be bypassing Missouri because of a shortage of trained workers.The program would offer tuition assistance to people age 25 and older who want to return to school for training in hard-to-fill jobs.Students must earn an adjusted annual gross income of less than $40,000 if they are single, or $80,000 per year if filing jointly. Anyone who has already earned a bachelor’s degree would be ineligible.The Department of Higher Education would create an annual list of positions where there is a need for workers.“It captures the folks that are falling through the cracks,” said Rep. Doug Beck, D-Affton.The Missouri Chamber of Commerce hailed the House action.“With today’s tight labor markets, we can’t afford to squander a single worker. We need every worker to maximize their potential,” said Daniel P. Mehan, president and CEO of the Missouri Chamber.
Not everyone supports the plan.Rep. Justin Hill, R-Lake Saint Louis, said the state should not be providing free tuition.
“This is a significant step to free education for all,” Hill said.Other Republicans voting “no” included Reps. John Wiemann of O’Fallon, Ron Hicks of Dardenne Prairie, Bruce DeGroot of Chesterfield and Shamed Dogan of Ballwin.Parson had sought $22 million for the program, saying it would serve 16,000 individuals.A House appropriations subcommittee recommended diverting more than $4 million from the program to fund other education priorities.The measure also has faced opposition in the Senate. Some senators want to cap the tuition level. Others want to require students to stay in Missouri for a set period of time if they take the money.Before voting to send the measure to the Senate Thursday, the House added a provision requiring the Legislature to revisit the law in three years to determine if it is working as intended.The legislation is House Bill 225.


