JEFFERSON CITY • Missourians would have the chance to weigh in on the state’s redistricting process under two lawmakers’ proposals.Voters approved Amendment 1, known as Clean Missouri, in November, which altered the state’s redistricting process.A nonpartisan state demographer will lead the redistricting effort for state legislative seats prior to the November 2022 elections. The end result could be more Democrats serving in the Republican-dominated Legislature.

Legislation by Sen. Dan Hegeman, R-Cosby, and Rep. Curtis Trent, R-Springfield, would require the demographer to create an online portal for public commentary. The provisions do not alter Clean Missouri itself. “I think this will give a little bit of clarity and transparency to the process,” Trent told the House General Laws Committee on Monday. “I think there’s a good chance there will be some confusion surrounding this process as there generally is with any redistricting cycle, but especially in the face of some fairly significant changes that went through in the last election cycle.”People submitting comments would be required to disclose whether anyone funded their submission, and who cut the check. No one testified for or against Trent's measure and no committee members asked him questions.A Senate committee approved Hegeman's proposal last week. It will need approval from the full Senate before moving to the House.Auditor Nicole Galloway, the only Democrat holding statewide office, is in charge of the demographer application process. She will submit the names of three candidates to the Senate majority and minority leaders.Galloway's spokeswoman, Steph Deidrick, said the auditor's office will have more information about the process in coming weeks.
Republican leaders, including Gov. Mike Parson and Senate Majority Floor Leader Caleb Rowden, R-Columbia, have previously spoken out against Clean Missouri, saying changes need to be made.When asked about altering the redistricting portion of the amendment in a Senate news conference, Rowden said he doesn’t think “anything is off the table.”
He said the change may have been "well-intentioned," but that the auditor's office should operate in an apolitical fashion. He said the new nonpartisan demographer — and the political back-and-forth that could manifest in the hiring process — will transform the auditor's office into a more political position.The state's current system of once-every-decade redistricting involves bipartisan commissions of political appointees who carve up the state's legislative districts.While Trent's legislation doesn't seek to hamstring the new demographer, House Democrats criticisms Republicans attempts to alter voter-approved laws.Republicans have sought to weaken a separate part of Clean Missouri that subjects lawmakers to the Sunshine Law.“It’s offensive to logic and it's offensive to us as a body," Rep. Mark Ellebracht, D-Liberty, said of the Republican proposals. "We hold these seats because of the will of the people that put us here.” The bills are House Bill 973 and Senate Bill 213.  Kurt Erickson of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this report.


