JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson’s plan to launch a $22 million scholarship program for 16,000 Missouri adults seeking jobs in high-demand trades was praised by lawmakers when he outlined the initiative in January.But now that the measure is beginning to move through the House and Senate, the cornerstone of Parson’s first legislative session is being picked apart.Last week, the plan hit a speed bump in the Senate after more than three hours of debate. In the House, lawmakers siphoned more than $4 million away from the program for other purposes.

Part of the reason for the turbulence is penny-pinching by legislative budget writers. Revenue collections as of Thursday were down more than 5 percent, or $310 million, from the same point last year.Budget officials expect collections to pick up, but lawmakers are nervous about revenue flow as thousands of Missourians begin to see surprise tax bills because of a Department of Revenue withholding error. And, the effects of a 2014 tax cut Parson voted for as a state senator are coming into focus.Analysts say the tax cut could cost $320 million in revenue next fiscal year, which begins July 1.















            Messenger: The accidental governor inherits a broken budget. What is he to do?



Another factor is that Parson’s administration must guide the proposal through the Legislature, which is filled with 190 lawmakers with individual priorities.So far, officials are playing down the speed bumps, saying that’s just the normal process that bills go through when they are being vetted.“We’ve got a lot of time left and I fully expect that to pass before the middle of May,” said Senate Majority Floor Leader Caleb Rowden, R-Columbia.Parson, who took over in June, has made workforce development a key plank in his first legislative session. The money is included in the $30 billion budget proposal he unveiled Jan. 16.He says the top priority for most businesses in picking a location is the quality of the workforce. Parson believes companies may be bypassing Missouri because of a shortage of trained workers.The end-product of the so-called “Fast Track” program, if approved, will likely differ from what Parson proposed.During floor debate on Tuesday, Sen. Jason Holsman, D-Kansas City, attempted to insert a provision to cap tuition costs at $10,000 per semester so all the money wouldn’t go to more expensive private schools. Later, his proposal was further tweaked to mirror tuition costs at the state’s flagship institution of higher education, the University of Missouri.Senators also wanted to require out-of-state students to repay the money if they don’t stay in the state for a set period of time.“It improves the chances that this is going to work the way we want it to work,” Holsman said.“If we provide the training, we want you to stay in Missouri,” said the bill’s sponsor, Sen. Gary Romine, R-Farmington.Sen. Bob Onder, R-Lake Saint Louis, said the added provisions would help make the program more accountable to taxpayers.“I think this should not be a flat-out giveaway,” Onder said.The legislation also says students must seek aid through the federal FAFSA process before receiving the state aid, meaning the Fast Track program would theoretically cover costs left over at the end of the application process.“Once they’ve exhausted those, then they would qualify for the grant,” Romine said.
Students must earn an adjusted annual gross income of less than $40,000 if they are single, or $80,000 per year if filing jointly. Anyone who has already earned a bachelor’s degree would be ineligible.On Tuesday night, as senators were debating the parameters, the measure got bogged down and was pulled from consideration after Rowden and Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz used a parliamentary maneuver to stop debate.The move drew the ire of Romine, who had wanted discussions to continue. “It was a very frustrating evening,” he said.A Romine ally agreed.“I’ve never really seen that tactic before,” said Sen. Doug Libla, R-Poplar Bluff.Schatz said the bill was put on hold because of an impending snow and ice storm.“We were at a point right there where we were not making any progress. I think it was important that we got people home safely,” Schatz said.
“We recognized that we’d kind of hit a stalemate and that’s when we tried to step back, reassess and figure out a path forward,” Rowden said.In the House, an appropriations subcommittee recommended diverting more than $4 million from the Fast Track program to fund other education priorities.Separate from that diversion, Rep. Kip Kendrick, D-Columbia, proposed carving as much as $12 million out of the Fast Track line item for core university funding, but abandoned the effort before it came to a vote.University of Missouri System President Mun Choi told reporters at the Capitol on Thursday that he wished the state would increase core funding as well as offer new scholarship programs.Though public colleges and universities likely won’t see a cut to core funding this year, core funding has flat-lined.“We need more money for scholarships,” Choi said. “We also need more money for core budget.”Rep. Greg Razer, D-Kansas City, said a new, bipartisan MU Caucus would seek to keep funding levels for public universities constant this year, as per Parson’s budget recommendation.“My hope is that we can sustain what the governor has recommended,” he said.“They’ve trimmed all the fat that they can trim,” Razer said. In the future, “my hope is that we can start finding a way to get more resources to our institutions.”“The level of support for higher education in this state, by all measures, (is) on the low side,” Choi said. “And we made that fact known, but we also realize that we are in a state where we’ve had some budgetary, financial challenges.”Speaking to reporters Thursday, Schatz wouldn’t say when he will call the Fast Track measure back before the full Senate. But when he does, he said there likely would be more changes.“When we bring that up, we have some work to do on that issue,” Schatz said. “Obviously the bill is kind of in limbo.”The legislation is Senate Bill 16.


