The accidental governor was having a hard time sleeping.It was early in the 2019 session of the Missouri Legislature. The budget was keeping Gov. Mike Parson up at night. Revenues were down, or at least not rising quickly. Expenses were going up. Budget writers had called the outlook “horrible.” Thrust into the role of having to craft a budget after Gov. Eric Greitens resigned less than two years into his term, Parson resorted to counting the state’s dilapidated bridges to put himself to sleep. One bad bridge … two bad bridges …An apparition appeared to him in a dream.

It was the Ghost of Governors Past.“Who are you?” Parson asked, rubbing his eyes.We’re the ones who got you into this mess. We’re here to give you some advice. Missouri governor's 'Fast Track' scholarship program slowed by budget concerns, skeptics“I could use some,” Parson said. “I really don’t understand. Every single year since Republicans have been in charge of the House and the Senate, for more than a decade now, we end the legislative year talking about how we created jobs and improved the economy. That’s what we did when I was in the Senate and when I was in the House. All of a sudden, I’ve got to craft a budget, and I find out there’s no money.”Sorry about that. We did the same thing. It’s what the people want to hear. Nobody wants to hear that we’ve put off for the next generation investing in the state’s future. It’s easier just to take credit for a booming economy, and hope that the cycle comes around.“But how did we get here? Even if the revenue hits our meager projections, we’re facing cuts to nearly everything. The bridges are falling apart and about the best I can do is float a $1 billion loan.”Well, what did you expect when you were voting for all those tax cuts? Corporate cuts. Income tax cuts. Meanwhile, we kept handing out tax credits to developers and other bigwigs like candy.“It sure would have helped if one of you would have prepared the state for this. I didn’t even run for governor, and now I’m here and I’ve got to close a prison, search the legislative couch cushions for pennies, threaten to take rent money from senior citizens, and maybe even cut $1 billion from Medicaid.”
The truth is, one of the Democrats in our club tried to issue a few warnings. But even he couldn’t resist the tax credit handouts and the lure of a corporate tax cut. You see, the donors want those things. And you don’t get to stay in the Governor’s Mansion long without the donors. It’s simply the reality of politics these days. Oh, and FYI: When talking about cutting the circuit breaker tax credit that keeps senior citizens in their homes, use the words ‘welfare creep.’“But at some point, when do we tell the Missouri people the truth, that we’ve bankrupted the state?”Oh, we aren’t fans of the truth. We’d advise against that. You’re on the right path. Talk about your bridge projects. And remember, you’re not ‘cutting’ Medicaid, you’re looking for waste, fraud and abuse. And efficiencies. Just keep waving around that report from McKinsey & Co. that says you can find a billion or so in saving. By the time voters get in on the scam, you’ll be long gone.“Sounds to me like I’ve got some more sleepless nights ahead. I read that Midwestern farm bankruptcies are up. More people are three months behind in car payments than have been in decades. People are ticked off that the president’s tax code rewrites are cutting their refunds.”
We’d advise against talking about those things. See, the people who will be funding your next campaign are actually doing pretty well. You need to keep them on your side. The good thing about tough times is that every time you cut something, all you have to say is that just like Missourians, you believe the state should live within its means. People love that stuff.“Yeah, but what if the math doesn’t work? What if the revenue doesn’t increase and I can’t replace the worn out bridges you all ignored? What if I end up having to withhold money for schools?”Look, don’t blame us for everything. The dirty little secret in Missouri budgeting is that the state could have $4 billion more in revenue and still be under 1981 taxing levels, thanks to the Hancock Amendment and other changes to the constitution that limit the Legislature’s ability to raise revenue. Worst part of the Hancock Amendment is the provision that requires the state auditor to report on it every year to make sure taxpayers aren’t due a refund. And so every year the auditor publishes a report that says the state would need to raise $4 billion more in revenue to actually hit 1981 tax-per-capita levels.“I could build one helluva budget with an extra $4 billion.”Well, that’s not going to happen. So just stay the course. Do your news conferences in front of broken down bridges. Pay McKinsey whatever it takes to make it harder for poor people, children, seniors and the disabled to access the health care services they need.“What if none of it works?”You’re missing the point. It’s not designed to work. Your job is to please the donors and get re-elected. By the time Missouri becomes Kansas, with an economy so bad that people will vote for Democrats again, you’ll be a Ghost of Governors Past. Speaking of which, don’t forget to sock some of your campaign money away. Our dues aren’t cheap. And unlike Missouri, we raise them every year. Gotta pay the bills.”Parson flicked the lights off and went back to bed. He still couldn’t sleep.


