For decades, Tony Foulds of Sheffield, England, has honored the memory of a St. Louis pilot who steered his damaged bomber away from him and other children and crashed into a wooded British hillside in 1944, killing all aboard.On Thursday evening, Missouri Gov. Mike Parson honored Foulds.During an event in the British Embassy in Washington, Parson handed a proclamation to the British ambassador to the United States, Kim Darroch, recognizing Foulds for helping maintain a small memorial at the crash site and for keeping the memory of the pilot and nine crew members alive.

“The people of Missouri say ‘Thank you’ for so many decades of honoring noble service and fostering a spirit of cooperation among peoples and nations,” the proclamation reads.















            Remembering the little-known actions of a World War II hero from St. Louis

The WWII pilot, John Kriegshauser, saved the lives of children when he put his badly damaged aircraft down in the woods instead of a park clea…




Foulds, now 82, was standing in a field in Endcliffe Park in Sheffield on Feb. 22, 1944, when he and other children saw a B-17G piloted by 1st Lt. John Kriegshauser drop from the clouds and plunge into a hillside. His story was featured by the BBC television network after a chance encounter between Foulds and a network news host. The host, Dan Walker, conducted a successful campaign to persuade the military to conduct a fly-by to recognize the 75th anniversary of the crash.














Tony Foulds was 8 years old on Feb. 22, 1944, when he saw a B-17 bomber piloted by 1st Lt. John Kriegshauser of St. Louis crash into a wooded area near a field where Fouls stood. Foulds credits the crew for saving his life.


Dan Walker


On Friday, Foulds, Darroch and a host of dignitaries are expected to attend a ceremony that was to include fly-bys by U.S. Air Force F-15Es among other aircraft. Two of Kriegshauser’s nephews who live in the St. Louis area were also planning on attending.
“St. Louisan John Kriegshauser’s actions that fateful day in 1944 are yet another example of why his is known as the Greatest Generation,” Parson said in remarks prepared for the embassy event, which was closed to media. “He and his crew acted selflessly to save innocent lives; Tony Foulds has acted nobly to preserve their tremendous legacy. Actions like Tony’s help strengthen the special relationship between the United States and United Kingdom.”Darroch said: “The courage of those 10 men on that day will be remembered — and not just by the children in the park whose lives were spared, but by the whole of the United Kingdom, who will always be grateful for their sacrifice.”Parson was in Washington to attend a meeting of the Republican Governors Association.


