JEFFERSON CITY • After spending months casting himself as the opposite of his pugnacious predecessor when it comes to relations with state lawmakers, Gov. Mike Parson took the gloves off this week.Responding to another special Missouri House committee hearing Wednesday about a vexing tax refund problem at the Missouri Department of Revenue, the governor, a Republican, accused lawmakers of using the meetings to showboat.And he defended Revenue Director Joel Walters’ handling of the situation, which could lead to many Missourians’ either receiving a lower tax refund or a higher tax bill because of the effects of the 2017 federal tax cut championed by President Donald Trump.

“Since this year’s session began, Director Walters has testified at 10 hearings where the withholding issue was discussed. Our office is aware of the decade-old mistake that was found in the withholding tables and have worked with the department to correct the problem and focus on solutions, not political grandstanding,” Parson said in a statement to the Post-Dispatch.Trump’s changes doubled federal-level deductions. That, in turn, amplified the effects of a 15-year-old miscalculation in the state tax tables.While the miscalculation, which has been corrected, won’t affect the overall amount of taxes Missourians ultimately owe, lawmakers said people often counted on getting a refund during the tax season. Now, some won’t.Parson admonished lawmakers and taxpayers for relying on refunds, saying they should adjust their W-4 forms so they pay as little to the government up front, a move that would reduce refunds and put that money in their paychecks.“Missouri legislators’ argument that individuals should want to give a zero percent interest loan to the government throughout the year is ridiculous,” Parson said.On Wednesday, Walters again faced members of the House Special Committee on Government Accountability and acknowledged the department hadn’t done enough to prepare people for the changes.“We didn’t know how big the issue” would be, Walters said.Committee chairman Robert Ross, R-Yukon, who has led the often pointed inquiry into Walters’ leadership on the problem, said the agency’s attempt to spread the word by social media failed miserably.In a state where 3.6 million tax returns are filed, the department has 982 Facebook followers and about 2,000 Twitter followers, he said.“The memo’s not getting out there, director,” Ross said.Rep. Peter Merideth, D-St. Louis, also complained that the department could have done a better job making sure Missourians understood the effects of the changes.“It seems like we did a disservice to our constituents,” Merideth said.But Parson said he believed Walters had successfully notified top state officials and the public about the problem.“In numerous one-on-one meetings and in public testimony, Director Walters has clearly identified the issue and shared the department’s planned process to help individuals that may be affected,” Parson said.
The comments are a departure for a governor who has worked to show he would not be as combative as former Gov. Eric Greitens, a self-described outsider who routinely feuded with members of the Legislature before he resigned last June.Since taking office, Parson has made it a practice to visit with members of the Legislature, where he served before being elected lieutenant governor in 2016.In the statement to the newspaper, Parson said he had a lengthy record of fighting for lower taxes, including signing into law the nation’s 14th-lowest tax rate.The governor “fundamentally believes that individuals should keep more of their hard-earned money,” the statement said. “Both the Tax Cuts and Job Act signed by President Trump and latest state income tax cut will benefit millions of Missourians.”In the committee, Walters outlined a number of different examples of how the federal changes, combined with the updated tax tables, might affect taxpayers when they file their returns.
Under one scenario, a married couple making a total of $100,000 and each claiming one dependent would see their refund go to $67 for 2018 from $516 for 2017.A single filer with no dependents making $36,000 annually would face a tax bill of $58 for 2018, rather than a refund of $53 as in 2017.House Speaker Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield, said Thursday that Parson’s criticism would not stop the chamber from continuing to press Walters.“We are the people’s body and give all Missourians a voice in state government. A core constitutional function of the elected Legislature is to have oversight over the unelected bureaucracy. The committee will continue to fully examine the actions by the Department of Revenue that are impacting taxpayers and state revenue, and to protect Missourians from experiencing this type of pain again,” Haahr said.Ross, who has scheduled a third committee meeting on the issue for next Wednesday, also expressed disappointment with Parson.“It is unfortunate that the executive branch is confusing grandstanding with standing up for the taxpayers, but we will never back down from doing our job,” Ross said.House Minority Leader Crystal Quade, D-Springfield, called Parson’s rebuke “deeply disappointing.”“Most Missourians are not certified public accountants or tax policy experts, and since they never needed to change their withholding information in previous years, it is unreasonable to expect they should have known to do so without Governor Parson’s Department of Revenue making robust efforts to inform them, which it completely failed to do,” Quade said. “Right now, we must do everything possible to help the countless Missourians who are wondering how to pay tax bills they didn’t know they were going to owe.”“I don’t have a problem with what the House is doing,” said Senate Minority Leader Gina Walsh, D-Bellefontaine Neighbors. “I don’t think it’s grandstanding. We are asking questions that should be asked.”Missouri’s governors


