CLAYTON • A local government watchdog is accusing the St. Louis County Council of violating the Missouri Sunshine Law by refusing to release resumes and applications for four people appointed to county boards.Tom Sullivan, of University City, said he wrote to the council’s records custodian, Genevieve Frank, on Jan. 14 to request resumes and applications for Kathrina M. Donegan, Julie Griffith and Vijay R. Bhasin, who were appointed by County Executive Steve Stenger to the St. Louis-Jefferson Solid Waste Management District board, and Mary McMurtrey, who was appointed by council member Lisa Clancy to the port authority.Frank responded that the records were closed because they were confidential personnel records.

Sullivan wrote that the appointees “are not employees and nor would they be employees of the respective organizations for which they would be board members.” And he pointed to a previous Missouri attorney general’s decision that says appointed and unpaid members of committees and citizen boards are not employees.Sullivan wrote that the council should be fined for “flagrantly violating the law.”Frank declined to comment.Sullivan also alleges that the council voted to override a Stenger veto in January without providing notice to the public that the issue would come to a vote.
The attorney general’s office last year dismissed another complaint Sullivan made against the council, ruling that the council did not violate the Sunshine Law in December 2017 when it filed last-minute legislation that cut $31 million from the county budget.
Sullivan had filed the complaint because the Missouri Sunshine Law requires a public body to post a meeting agenda 24 hours before a meeting. The council’s agenda posted for the Dec. 12 meeting did not point to any effort to slash county spending, and Sullivan said he felt the last minute changes shut out the public from providing input. But the attorney general’s office ruled that the law did not prohibit governmental bodies from adding items to an already-posted agenda as long as the public was informed about the new items with appropriate advance notice and the additions were not made with the intent to circumvent the Sunshine Law.The attorney general’s office is still suing Stenger for alleged Sunshine violations.In January 2018, then-Attorney General Josh Hawley filed a lawsuit in St. Louis County Circuit Court against Stenger’s office, alleging that members of Stenger’s staff routinely violated the Sunshine Law. A lawyer in the St. Louis County counselor’s office asserted weeks later that the lawsuit should be dismissed because Stenger’s office was not a legal entity that could be sued on its own. Hawley’s office amended the lawsuit to name the monolithic St. Louis County as defendant.Attorney General Eric Schmitt, who was appointed as Hawley’s replacement by Gov. Mike Parson after Hawley won a seat in the U.S. Senate, is still pursuing the suit. A hearing is scheduled for May 13.Meanwhile, Hawley is still facing questions over his enforcement of the Sunshine Law.


