JEFFERSON CITY • Republican lawmakers have advanced a proposal requiring two-parent notification prior to a minor's abortion.Similar measures have failed five times in the past. Minors currently must receive consent from one parent or guardian before an abortion.The proposal, sponsored by Rep. Rocky Miller, R-Lake Ozark, would still require one parent to consent to the abortion, but a second parent or guardian would have to be notified.

The legislation, which the House Children and Families Committee approved Tuesday on an 8-5 vote, includes exceptions in cases where a parent or guardian has been found guilty of child abuse or sex offenses.The Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services said that in 2017, 125 abortions out of a total of almost 4,000 statewide were performed on minors. Supporters hope a change in state law will reduce that figure.The full House must still approve the legislation before it moves to the Senate for consideration.A second initiative, sponsored by Rep. Nick Schroer, R-O’Fallon, would ban all abortions when a heartbeat is detected. Heartbeats can be detected as early as six weeks, Schroer said.“If it was on planet Mars, it would be life, but the fact that it's here on a mother’s belly and not classified as life is astonishing to me,” he said.  One supporter said death is measured by the end of a person’s heartbeat, so life should be measured by the beat’s beginning.Dr. Erin King, executive director of the Hope Clinic for Women in Illinois, called the proposal “an extreme and dangerous measure” that comes close to banning all abortion in Missouri. The obstetrician gynecologist explained the change would ban abortion before most women even realize they’re pregnant.“If House Bill 126 were enacted, it would no longer matter what this patient wanted, her life circumstances or what could be best for her medically,” King said.Rep. Sarah Unsicker, D-Shrewsbury, noted the legislation's cost estimate, which indicates that Missouri could lose more than $7 billion in Medicaid funding because of a potential conflict with federally mandated abortion requirements in cases of rape, incest and when the procedure is needed to save mothers' lives.Schroer said both Republicans and Democrats have criticized fiscal analyses conducted by taxpayer-paid, nonpartisan legislative staff.
“If you trust fiscal notes, lady, with all do respect, I got a house that I can sell you on Mars,” he said, later adding: “What dollar amount do you put on life?”Courts have ruled against similar heartbeat bills in Iowa, Arkansas and North Dakota over the past few years.The two proposals are among several anti-abortion measures the Missouri Legislature is considering this year. No measures have reached the desk of Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican who has shown support for increased abortion regulations.
Missouri's only abortion provider is the St. Louis Planned Parenthood clinic.The legislation is House Bill 127, House Bill 680, House Bill 339 and House Bill 126.












