JEFFERSON CITY • Republican politicians are leading a push to make the initiative petition process more difficult in Missouri, especially when it comes to changing the state constitution.The effort follows the November 2018 election in which Missouri voters faced four state constitutional amendments and three propositions. And, a controversial effort to force a statewide vote on a St. Louis city-county merger proposal is on the horizon for 2020.A pair of proposed bills would add fees throughout the petition process for campaigns that pay signature collectors. Six joint resolutions, up from just one last session, would go a step further by increasing the mandated amount of signatures needed and the number of congressional districts in which they should be collected. The resolutions would have to be approved by voters before becoming law.

Rep. Peter Merideth, D-St. Louis, who has proposed a bill to allow signature collection online, sees the influx of legislation as a reaction to the handful of measures Missouri voters approved in November. Three of those — medical marijuana, minimum wage and ethics reform — each received more than 60 percent approval.Top Republican lawmakers, including Gov. Mike Parson and Senate Majority Floor Leader Caleb Rowden, R-Columbia, have expressed a desire to alter some of what voters passed on the ballot. During a news conference on the session’s opening day, Rowden zeroed in on Clean Missouri, which he said was “very poorly written.”“I think we’re going to have to go back and we’re going to have to make some changes to it that aren’t necessarily designed to change the intent, but are designed to make it to where it actually functionally does what the folks want it to do,” he stated.Democrats are pushing back, including Auditor Nicole Galloway, the only Democrat holding statewide office in Missouri. “Why were voters so smart when they put you into office but not so smart when they vote on issues that directly affect their government and how they live their lives?” Galloway said in an interview with the Post-Dispatch.Sen. David Sater’s bill was the first of the measures to receive a hearing in the Local Government and Elections Committee, where he serves as vice chairman.Sater, R-Cassville, presented his bill Wednesday, assuring the committee that he strongly believes there should be an initiative petition process, but adding that Missouri’s system has been distorted and now works against the people instead of for them.“The current initiative process is no longer a citizens-driven grassroots process, but a corporate one that circumvents the will of the people expressed in our republic form of government,” Sater said. “Our constitution is a very sacred document and it should not be for sale to the highest bidder.”His proposal would enact a $500 filing fee, a 40-cent-per-signature fee and an additional $25 charge per page if submissions exceed 10 pages.The legislation also would shorten the time period to submit petitions and collect signatures in years the secretary of state is on the ballot. Currently, Missourians are able to file the day after an election, but the bill would push that back 12 weeks.As of Jan. 31, 40 petitions have already been submitted for 2020.Some of the 10 people who testified against Sater’s bill took issue with the concept of a signature fee, comparing it to an illegal poll tax.“I believe there is a high possibility that such a thing is unconstitutional,” lobbyist Woody Cozad said. “It is a tax on the exercise of a constitutionally guaranteed right.”Such a fee could add more than $80,000 to the process, depending on how many signatures are collected, a measurement based on the previous election’s voter turnout.Missouri AFL-CIO President Mike Louis, who led the campaign against the anti-union Right to Work initiative in August, noted that campaigns need to collect at least 25 percent “extra” signatures because many end up being disqualified.
Several opponents pointed out that by adding expenses to the process, only the big-money groups that Sater spoke out against would be able to afford to launch initiative petition drives.Secretary of State Jay Ashcroft, who oversees the initiative petition process, testified in favor of the bill, citing a need to cut down on “frivolous petitions” in a “content-neutral way.”Last election cycle, Missourians filed 371 petitions, with 148 being approved for circulation. In a similar cycle a decade earlier, just 51 petitions were approved for circulation.Representatives from the Missouri Chamber of Commerce and Industry and Missouri Cattlemen’s Association advocated for the bill, saying “controversial issues” should be vetted in the legislative chambers, not on the ballot.Committee member Sen. John Rizzo, D-Kansas City, later countered during the hearing that some issues approved on the ballot would “never pass” in the Legislature given the high Republican to Democrat ratio. He cautioned that if those in favor of the bill start to make the process harder, Missourians will take other routes to assert their demands.
“What they’re going to start doing instead of going around because it’s become so difficult, is start to change who’s down here,” Rizzo said. “… They’re going to have [their voices] heard at some point, it just depends on when and where.”Sater’s bill was voted out of committee Wednesday.Sen. Eric Burlison, R-Battlefield, is among those who say the process to change the “sacred document” that is Missouri’s constitution has become too easy. He says issues like medical marijuana do not have a place in the document.“The constitution is about rights,” Burlison said. “It’s about very fundamental issues. To me getting into that issue is, not to use a pun, but getting in the weeds of something. To me that’s what statutes are for.”“To get into such detail about a particular product or good I think is an error. We made that error with alcohol in the U.S. Constitution and reversed it.”Petitions proposing changes to the state constitution are required to field signatures from 8 percent of voters in two-thirds of the state’s eight congressional districts. Statutory changes need signatures from just 5 percent of voters from these regions to get on the ballot.Senators and representatives have filed a combined six joint resolutions to alter these requirements constitutionally. While some proposals hike the percentage of voters’ signatures needed, others expand the number of congressional districts required from two thirds to all of them. Several change both.SJR 11, Burlison’s proposition, would require signatures to be collected from all congressional districts. Although he leaves the percentage of voters the same, the overall number of signatures to gather would ultimately rise from the additional districts needed.In SJR7, Sen. Mike Cierpiot, R-Lee’s Summit, filed a similar measure. While his would also expand the number of mandated congressional districts, his resolution instead lowers the percentage to keep the overall number of signatures required the same.He says he doesn’t want to make the process harder, just more representative.“Right now you can stay in Kansas City and St. Louis and hit six congressional districts,” Cierpiot said. “This makes you actually go out to the southwest and southeast. I think it gives a better reflection of the state.”The proposals are SB5, HB290, SJR11, SJR7, SJR1 HJR25, HJR10, HJR11.


