JEFFERSON CITY • Faced with the possible rejection of his nominee by the Senate, Gov. Mike Parson has withdrawn the appointment of a member of the state’s Conservation Commission.Nicole Wood, a St. Francois County cattlewoman and land manager, had served on the commission since July, and was awaiting confirmation by the Senate.She told the Post-Dispatch she was “heartbroken” by the development, which came to a head Thursday when Parson notified the Senate her nomination was being withdrawn.

“I really enjoyed the time that I spent serving,” Wood said.  “I was excited to be a part of it.”The commission, which is funded through a sales tax separate from overall state revenues, was formed in 1935 with the purpose of taking politics out of land conservation issues.But, it appears politics did play a role in Wood's ouster.The commission has been embroiled in a dispute with the owners of captive deer and elk hunting operations over how to combat the spread of chronic wasting disease, or CWD — a fatal neurodegenerative disease.In July, the Supreme Court ruled that the commission had authority over both wild deer and elk, as well as those in captivity.The court’s ruling likely will mean the regulations on captive deer and elk operators that had been set to go into effect on Jan. 1, 2015, will be enforced.In addition to barring white-tailed deer, mule deer and other hybrids from being imported into Missouri, breeders face new record-keeping and permitting requirements under the new rules.The regulations call for stiffer fencing requirements and testing for chronic wasting disease when a deer older than 6 months dies in a facility.Wood’s nomination sparked a behind-the-scenes battle to convince senators to either confirm her or reject her.
The Conservation Federation of Missouri delivered a letter to senators in late January expressing the organization’s support for Wood.Wood also made the rounds in the Senate, visiting with lawmakers to convince them to back her nomination.“I thought my meetings went pretty well with the senators,” she said.But, groups that represent the captive deer hunting operators urged members of the Senate to oppose her.
“Nicole Wood has demonstrated that she does not appreciate or understand the diversity of Missouri's hunting, fishing, and trapping traditions,” noted a letter from the Grover, Mo.-based Cavalry Group, which defends animal-related business owners in disputes.Wood, who runs cattle on 4,000 acres in Iron County and manages 10,000 acres in Texas County near the Current River watershed, said she’s an avid hunter.She also said the commission’s battle with the outfitting companies started before her tenure.“I feel like I’m a good conservationist and would bring a good business mind to the commission,” Wood said.In a statement, Parson’s office said her nomination was withdrawn because the Senate did not give Wood a confirmation hearing, signaling that she lacked the support for a vote in the full Senate.“Our office has begun the process of looking at potential candidates and hope to fill the vacancy on the conservation commission in the next few weeks,” the statement noted.Wood’s ouster comes at a pivotal time for the four-member commission. In addition to her vacancy, two other members — David William Murphy of Columbia and Marilyn Jeannette Bradford of Jefferson City — expire in June, giving Parson the ability to put a majority of members on the panel.


