JEFFERSON CITY • Top officials at the Missouri Lottery say a plan to cut the agency’s advertising budget could mean less money for schools next year.In his proposed state budget, Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, called for an $11 million reduction in the lottery’s $16 million budget for advertising.His budget chief, Dan Haug, said the lottery is well known in Missouri and can weather the reduction.

“The lottery is very mature,” Haug told the Post-Dispatch Wednesday. “People see the lottery every time they walk into a convenience store. How effective are those additional advertising dollars?”May Scheve Reardon, the executive director of the lottery, told a Senate budget panel Wednesday that the reduction in ads could result in an estimated $35 million less going toward schools in the fiscal year beginning July 1.“Advertising is best practice for any kind of business,” Reardon said.The lottery, which began operating in 1986, provides about 4 percent of state aid for elementary, secondary and higher education in Missouri.After selling about $1.4 billion in tickets last year, the lottery was able to transfer $306 million to education in the prior fiscal year.Reardon said the goal for next year is to transfer $323 million to schools. But she said the lack of advertising could trigger a drop in sales.
“We really feel our advertising has been a great benefit to our beneficiary of elementary, secondary and higher education,” Reardon said.Members of the Senate Appropriations Committee asked for proof that the cut would hurt ticket sales, but Missouri Lottery Commission Chairman Paul Kincaid could not provide any hard data.“I don’t have a clear, crystal ball,” Kincaid said. “It’s more of an art than a science.”
According to figures provided by the lottery, the agency’s advertising budget was 1.2 percent of sales compared to an average of 1.5 percent of sales in surrounding states.It’s not the first time the lottery has had to fight attempts to cut its ad budget.In 2014, the House Budget Committee proposing cutting $8.3 million from the lottery's advertising budget, directing the money instead to the schools fund sustained by lottery money.The lottery sells its products in 4,600 retail locations across the state. Of the $1.4 billion in tickets sold, $939.5 million was paid out in prizes.In its goals for the coming year, the lottery wants to increase the percentage of Missourians who play by 1.5 percent.


