JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson’s plan to borrow $350 million to fix 250 bridges appears to be on a fast track in the Missouri Senate.In action Tuesday, 17 special interest groups representing truckers, engineering companies, road builders, farmers and others with a stake in the construction industry, signaled support for a plan that would allow for the sale of bonds to pay for four years of projects at a cost of about $29.9 million annually for 15 years.No senators asked questions about the proposal. No one testified in opposition to the legislation that would finance the work using money from the state’s general check book, not out of road and bridge funds which are typically used to fix the state’s highways.

Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz, who is sponsoring the legislation, said the lack of opposition may be because lawmakers understand that they must address the issue of maintenance after voters turned down a 10-cent per gallon increase in the gasoline tax in November.“I think we have a consensus in the Senate and in the House as well that knows we need to take care of our roads and bridges. That we can agree on. It’s just how do we get there and how do we fund it,” said Schatz, R-Sullivan.Schatz said the measure is expected emerge from the committee process next week, setting the stage for what could be a lively debate on the floor.Parson outlined the plan during his State of the State address, arguing that, without the added revenue from a gas tax increase, he had to look at other alternatives to keeping the state’s system of roads and bridges safe.The plan has its critics. The bonds will have an interest rate of 3.25 percent, meaning taxpayers will be on the hook for $100 million in interest payments.“Not everybody is a fan of going down this path,” Schatz said, pledging to work behind the scenes to secure the votes for passage.“Maybe we can avoid those fights on the floor and try to address those issues in the backroom,” Schatz said.The proposal also appears to limit the possibility of political tinkering by lawmakers by leaving the selection process for the targeted bridges in the hands of regional transportation commissions.
A list of projects released by Parson shows 8 percent of the total being spent  in the St. Louis region, even though the area is the most populated in the state.In the first year of the program, MoDOT would oversee three bridge replacement projects in the St. Louis area worth a total of $8.3 million.They include the $1.2 million replacement of a bridge on Ladue Road over Hibler Creek in Creve Coeur; a $2.7 million replacement of a bridge over Happy Sac Creek in Franklin County; and a $4.4 million replacement project at the intersection of Valley Dell Drive and Gravois Road in Jefferson County.
Projects in later years include replacing the North Broadway bridge over Interstate 44 in St. Louis and the replacement of the Missouri Highway 47 bridge over Interstate 44 in St. Clair in Franklin County.Parson opposes attempts by lawmakers to insert their own pet projects into the list.The list of 250 bridges comes from a broader statewide construction plan of priority projects already slated for repair that was chosen by regional and metropolitan planning commissions, Transportation Department Director Patrick McKenna said. From that list, Parson worked with the department to identify bridges that could be completed quickly and for less than $8 million.McKenna said keeping the per-project price tag low means more bridges can be repaired. But he said that also means it tends to go toward projects in rural areas, where bridges often are smaller and less expensive to fix.The Missouri Farm Bureau testified in support of the process, saying it wouldn’t be fair to let pork barrel politics seep into the selection of which bridges are fixed.“We think that’s an important part of this,” said BJ Tanksley.The legislation is Senate Concurrent Resolution 14.


