JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri lawmakers are again debating a proposal requiring the parent of a daughter younger than 18 seeking an abortion to notify the other “custodial parent or guardian” of the procedure.The legislation, which has failed to advance five previous times, is among at least one dozen abortion-related measures pending in the Republican-led Legislature this year.The proposal, sponsored by Rep. Rocky Miller, R-Lake Ozark, would alter current law, in which a physician must get informed written consent from one parent or guardian.

There would be some exceptions to adding a second parent to the notification process, such as a parent or guardian who is a sex offender or has been found guilty of child abuse.Supporters said the change could reduce the number of abortions. In 2017, the Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services reported that 125 abortions were performed on girls under 18 out of a total of nearly 4,000 statewide.“These types of laws do save lives,” said Samuel Lee, director of Campaign Life Missouri. “Moms and dads need to be involved in the lives of their children — no matter how messy life can be sometimes.”“We hope this is the year that it passes,” said Susan Klein, executive director of Missouri Right to Life.But, abortion rights proponents argued the change could put a young woman’s life in danger, by forcing her to confront an abusive or angry parent.“In the real world, we cannot legislate perfect families,” said Sean Whiting, legislative director for Planned Parenthood Advocates in Missouri.He said the proposal also would erect a barrier to patients seeking “timely care.”In previous years, similar measures were approved by the House, but were not taken up by the Senate.Other abortion-related proposals awaiting hearings in the House and Senate this session include legislation requiring physicians to perform a fetal heartbeat detection test before performing an abortion in most cases. Except in cases of medical emergency, the physician would then be prevented from performing the abortion if a heartbeat were detected.Similar heartbeat bills have been introduced in more than a dozen states over the past six years. But, the courts have ruled against the bans in Arkansas, North Dakota and Iowa.
Gov. Mike Parson would not say last week if he supports the proposal, but said he is “pro-life.”Rep. Tom Hurst, R-Meta, introduced legislation prohibiting a person from knowingly taking a minor out of state to obtain an abortion without consent from the minor's parent or guardian. The bill is identical to legislation proposed each of the past two years.Another bill, House Bill 540, requires certain health care professionals who make referrals for abortions to first conduct a "risk evaluation" for the patient.
The risk evaluation would include any physical, psychological or situational factors which would increase the risks of the patient experiencing physical or emotional reactions to the abortion.Rep. Mike Moon, R-Ash Grove, introduced a resolution to outlaw abortion, saying states should stop attempting to limit abortion, but rather just stop it altogether.“It’s time to draw the proverbial line in the sand and take a principled stand to protect life,” Moon said.The parental consent legislation is House Bill 127.



