JEFFERSON CITY • An estimated 1 million Americans will place a legal bet on Sunday’s Super Bowl matchup between the Los Angeles Rams and the New England Patriots.But none of those legal bets will be placed in Missouri.While eight other states have already legalized sports wagering, lawmakers in the Show-Me State are still haggling over details that affect not only gamblers, but the casinos that would offer the bets, the professional leagues and college conferences that offer the contests and the regulators who would monitor the system.

On Thursday, it was apparent that negotiators are still far from reaching a compromise after two years of behind-the-scenes negotiations.On Thursday, in a committee hearing room packed with gambling and sports industry lobbyists, Sen. Denny Hoskins, R-Warrensburg, outlined a plan calling for a 12 percent tax on wagers that would generate at least $6 million for education. A separate 2 percent tax would raise at least $1 million for veterans programs.Afterward, no one rose to speak in support of the measure.“This is a work in progress,” Hoskins acknowledged.The Super Bowl has typically been the biggest sports betting event of the year. But this year it will be legal following a 2018 U.S. Supreme Court decision that allowed it to be offered in states beyond the gambling stronghold of Nevada.In Rhode Island, where sports betting got underway in November, scores of people from Massachusetts are crossing the state line to place a bet on the game, presumably for their Patriots.Back in Missouri, the zeal for betting has waned after Kansas City’s NFL team lost in the playoffs.“At this point I’m still trying to overcome the fact that the Chiefs are not playing,” said Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan. “The fact that the Rams left Missouri makes me want to root for the Patriots, but I’m not sure I’d bet on either one of them because they are both very good football teams.”Gov. Mike Parson said he expects Missouri to eventually offer sports betting, but he is waiting for lawmakers to strike a deal before weighing in on the specifics.
“I think that’s going to be an issue that the State of Missouri has got to deal with,” Parson said.Along with reaching an agreement on tax rates, the state must also set an application fee for casinos wanting to offer sports betting.In his bill, Hoskins set the licensing fee at $10,000, with a $5,000 annual renewal cost. By contrast, Pennsylvania has a $10 million licensing fee.Similarly, Pennsylvania is charging a 36 percent tax, compared to Hoskins’ 12 percent. A separate bill sponsored by Sen. Lincoln Hough, R-Springfield, would charge a 6.75 percent tax.
Parson said he had no comment on what kinds of taxes and fees are appropriate.“I don’t know what the legislators are going to do about that,” Parson told members of the Missouri Press Association during an event at the governor’s mansion.Mike Winter, executive director of the Missouri Gaming Association, which represents the state’s casinos, said the tax rates proposed by Hoskins would leave casinos little room for profits.“We look forward to continuing the discussion,” Winter said.Senate Majority Floor Leader Caleb Rowden, R-Columbia, previously sponsored sports betting bills. This year he is not closely involved in the talks.But, he said, “It’s coming and we might as well be part of it. I’m hoping we can get something done. It’s a complicated path, for sure.”The legislation is Senate Bill 44 and Senate Bill 222.


