JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson on Thursday did not commit to supporting an effort to merge St. Louis city and county — but the state's chief executive indicated that he thought the region's fractured system of governance was not working."When the mayor of St. Louis comes forward and says, you know, we've got serious problems in St. Louis — one of the major urban areas of the state, which has a huge impact on the entire state of Missouri," Parson told reporters, "I think, one, that should be noted, that someone reached out to say we've got problems."He said "everything should be on the table" for "how to fix that."

"It seems like the way it has been," Parson added, "has definitely got some problems."Parson's comments came days after the nonprofit group Better Together unveiled its long-awaited plan to merge the city and county, two separate entities since the Great Divorce of 1876.The proposal would leave school and fire districts intact. But, the county’s 88 municipalities would become “municipal districts” whose authority would be limited to overseeing an array of services, including parks and recreation and trash collection.When pressed, Parson, a Republican, would not say whether he supported the initiative, adding the effort had "a lot of moving pieces" and that it would be too early to take a position.He likewise did not take a position on whether a statewide vote should be held on the merger.Parson would have no direct role in placing a proposed constitutional amendment on the ballot, but his backing could prove consequential as support and opposition to the plan begins to harden.Supporters of the effort — including St. Louis Mayor Lyda Krewson and St. Louis County Executive Steve Stenger — argue that the consolidation will save taxpayer money, lead to safer communities and spark greater business investment.But mayors of various municipalities and others have criticized Better Together — and the proposed statewide vote, which could impose the "metro city" vision even if the majority of city and county voters reject it."I certainly agree that working together adds value to our region," said state Rep. Dean Plocher, R-Des Peres, "but when it requires a statewide vote to force it down the throats of the county, my constituents and the city, I don't think that's good politics, I don't think it's good policy, and I think it runs contrary to the idea of good governance.Plocher said his phone "lit up" when the Better Together proposal was unveiled."Quite honestly I'm not aware of anyone supporting it," Plocher said of his constituents.Democratic Rep. Bob Burns represents parts of south St. Louis and parts of the Lemay area in St. Louis County.
Burns said that he was initially "totally opposed" to a merger, but he said he was "a little bit more comfortable" with the idea after this week's presentation."I'm receptive but I'm not going to say I'm for it," Burns said. He said detailing how a metro city would address crime in St. Louis — and the perception of crime in the city — needed to be discussed as part of any effort to gain public support for the initiative.Burns said his constituents who lived in the county were more likely to voice opposition than his constituents who lived in the city.Rep. Gina Mitten, D-Richmond Heights, said many of her constituents are most worried about out-state voters imposing their will on the city and county.Conversely, some of her constituents who support Better Together worry the only way a merger will happen is if out-state voters weigh in.
"I would say that that's a minority," she said of the latter group.Some lawmakers have floated ways to counter the statewide vote proposal.Mitten, whose district also includes parts of the city and county, said an alternative to a statewide vote forcing a merger could be a statewide vote that authorizes the city and county to consolidate, upon city and county voter approval.Rep. Bruce Franks, D-St. Louis, proposed legislation this week that would require a majority of voters in the city and the county to authorize any merger.Sen. Jamilah Nasheed, D-St. Louis, filed legislation that would require 60 percent voter support in the city and county in order for a merger to take place.















            'Metro City': Better Together launches a two-year effort to meld St. Louis city and county

