JEFFERSON CITY • A plan to launch a scholarship program for 16,000 Missouri adults seeking jobs in high-demand trades, health care and technology received positive reviews in its first test before the Legislature on Monday.Less than two weeks after Gov. Mike Parson unveiled the proposal as part of his State of the State speech, members of a House committee heard an outline of the $22 million plan.Rep. Kathy Swan, R-Cape Girardeau, who is sponsoring the measure, said it is the first scholarship program for adults age 25 or over.

“This is intended to serve those who have fallen through the cracks,” Swan said. “We do not have anything in this state that reaches this specific group.”Parson, who took over in June, has made workforce development a key plank in his first legislative session. The money is included in the $30 billion budget proposal he unveiled Jan. 16.He says the top priority for most businesses in picking a location is the quality of the workforce. Parson believes companies may be bypassing Missouri because of a shortage of trained workers.In a sign of his interest in the issue, the governor made a rare, brief appearance at the hearing to listen in on the debate.“We all agree that change is needed,” Swan told members of the committee.Parson already has taken steps to reorganize state government by moving hundreds of staffers out of the Department of Economic Development in order to sharpen the focus of the agency on job creation.Parson also wants an additional $16.3 million for training programs designed to help workers gain skills needed at particular employers.Department of Economic Development Director Rob Dixon said despite low unemployment, economic growth in Missouri has lagged compared to neighboring states.“We need to have that supply of labor,” Dixon said. “It’s been a decade since we stepped back and assessed our economic development strategy.”
“We are really far behind and we need to catch up,” said Rep. Travis Fitzwater, R-Holts Summit.Department of Higher Education Director Zora Mulligan told members of the House Workforce Development Committee that many of the people who are migrating to Missouri do not have bachelor’s degrees.“We are bringing in people who are lower-skilled,” Mulligan said.Parson wants to set aside $22 million to provide scholarships to workers older than 25 who want to go into high-demand health care, trade and technology positions.
Rep. Craig Fishel, R-Springfield, said he has trouble hiring people to work at his construction business.“This is music to my ears. I’ve lost four key employees to retirement. I have not been able to replace them,” said Fishel.The panel is expected to vote on the measure in the coming weeks, but some lawmakers say they need additional information.Rep. Jim Hansen, R-Frankford, said the Legislature will need to know whether the programs are effective.“What kind of follow-up will the General Assembly get about this program?” Hansen asked.Dixon said the agency plans to post performance results on its website.“We have to be careful and cautious,” added Rep. Doug Beck, D-Affton.The legislation is House Bill 225.


