JEFFERSON CITY • State Sen. Scott Sifton said Friday that he was preparing to run for Missouri governor in 2020 — a move that could set up a contest next year between the St. Louis County Democrat and Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican.“I’m focused on the legislative session that just began, but it’s my present intention to run,” Sifton told the Post-Dispatch, adding that he was planning to officially enter the race at a later date.





















            Scott Sifton

Scott Sifton (D) 






Sifton’s announcement comes as Auditor Nicole Galloway, the only Democrat elected to statewide office in Missouri, signaled Thursday that she did not intend to run for the post next year. When asked if she had no desire to run, Galloway said in an interview: “Yeah, I’m here focused (on) being auditor.”Sifton, 44, is term-limited in the Senate and flirted with a run for attorney general in 2016. He is thought by party insiders to be the only major Democrat eyeing the party’s nomination.Sifton is a practicing attorney, formerly of the Husch Blackwell law firm. He lives in the Affton area with his son Stephen, 10, and daughter Madelyn, 6. He won a seat in the Missouri House in 2010. His Senate district stretches from the Oakville area north to Brentwood. The seat had been held by a Republican until Sifton flipped the district in 2012.“Right now let’s just call him a potential gubernatorial candidate,” Senate Minority Leader Gina Walsh, D-Bellefontaine Neighbors, said on Friday. “Scott’s a thoughtful person, and he doesn’t rush into anything when he makes decisions. He analyzes, and that’s what I like about him.”In the past, Missouri Democratic Party leaders have coalesced around a preferred nominee for governor early on in each election cycle. The party has not had a competitive gubernatorial primary in 15 years.Galloway has championed legislation Sifton has sponsored. In March 2018, and again this year, Galloway voiced support for legislation that would force major state contractors to disclose contributions of $500 or more to dark-money 501(c)(4) groups.Sifton also advertised the endorsement of the Missouri Fraternal Order of Police during his 2016 re-election.















            State Senate seat rooted in South County a key for both major parties

Democratic incumbent Scott Sifton of Affton faces Republican Randy Jotte of Webster Groves in the St. Louis area's most competitive Missouri Senate race.




Then- Gov. Jay Nixon, the state’s last Democratic governor, from 2009 to 2017, often struggled to satisfy various factions of the state Democratic Party.He sought to appeal to broad cross-sections of the state by honing an “independent” brand, seen as too conservative by many Democrats.During protests in Ferguson, some black politicians and others grew angry at the governor’s handling of the situation. Then- Attorney General Chris Koster, a Democrat who ran for governor in 2016, also faced criticism that he was too conservative.
Walsh said Sifton had not shied away from favoring things such as access to abortion and gay rights.“I think it’s fair to say I’m socially progressive,” Sifton said Friday.Sifton suggested he favored a more fiscally conservative approach to government spending.“We’ve got to be careful with how we spend our public dollars in Missouri,” he said. “The more efficient we are, the more we can do to help folks, whether that’s Medicaid, education or anything else.”
Sifton has been able to pull off close victories in the St. Louis County suburbs, suggesting he has the ability to appeal to independent voters. He said his campaign would focus on “wages for working families and access to affordable health care and quality education.”As of New Year’s Eve, Sifton had just under $318,000 cash on hand after raising more than $70,000 in the last fundraising quarter and spending $57,000, according to recent campaign filings. He was not on the ballot last year.By comparison, Parson, his likely Republican opponent, had $936,000 on hand at the end of the year. The Uniting Missouri PAC, which does not have to adhere to campaign contribution limits and is supporting Parson, had $2 million in its coffers.No similar group has raised significant money for Sifton.His most recent campaign filings show expenditures on campaign consulting, website support and office rent. He has also paid four staffers in recent months.Many outstate Missouri counties appear to be tilting increasingly further to the right, and the state’s suburbs may prove crucial to Democrats seeking to regain power in 2020.Encouraged by a better-than-expected Democratic showing in the 2nd Congressional District, the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee is already sending out emails blasting U.S. Rep. Ann Wagner, R-Ballwin, whose district covers much of the St. Louis suburbs.Wagner narrowly hung onto her seat last November, but also outspent her opponent, first-time candidate Cort VanOstran, a Democrat.Several other Republicans in the state House faced challenges in the Kansas City and St. Louis suburbs last election, though Democrats ultimately flipped just three Republican seats. Republicans were able to neutralize the Democrats’ gains by winning three Democratic seats in conservative areas.Lexi Churchill of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this report.


