JEFFERSON CITY • St. Charles County’s two state senators want to see spending in their area before supporting Gov. Mike Parson’s proposed $350 million bond to repair and replace hundreds of bridges in Missouri.“In my own district, there are no projects whatsoever,” Sen. Bob Onder, R-Lake Saint Louis, told reporters on Thursday.Sen. Bill Eigel, R-Weldon Spring, said he met with Parson, also a Republican, on Wednesday. Eigel said he didn’t push for any specific projects in his district to be included in the list of more than 200 bridges to be repaired over a four-year span.

“I don’t want to get too far in the weeds for a discussion that really has just gotten underway,” Eigel said, “but the governor has recognized the need for projects to be done around the state — not just in urban areas, not just in rural areas — but around the state. Identifying what that list is — we’re just now getting on to that part of the discussion.”When asked whether the list of projects was open for negotiation, Parson’s spokesman, Steele Shippy, said in a statement: “The Governor is working every day with members of the legislature to discuss his plan that clearly prioritizes the entire state of Missouri, not any one district or project.“The Governor’s infrastructure plan is built on bold ideas and a willingness to tackle tough issues — like fixing 250 bridges in need of critical repair or replacement,” Shippy said.Projects in the St. Louis region represent 8 percent of the total being spent throughout the state during the multiyear initiative.In making his pitch for the bridge plan, Parson said the list of projects was not politically driven because they were chosen by regional planning boards and then approved by the state Highways and Transportation Commission.That sentiment was shared by Senate President Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan.“We try to take politics out of it. They are on the five-year plan because it’s time to address those,” Schatz said. “I’m not sure there is a lot of negotiations.“If someone is concerned they are not getting enough attention, they just may be blessed that they have good bridges,” Schatz said.In the first year of the program, MoDOT would oversee three bridge replacement projects in the St. Louis area worth a total of $8.3 million.They include the $1.2 million replacement of a bridge on Ladue Road over Hibler Creek in Creve Coeur; a $2.7 million replacement of a bridge over Happy Sac Creek in Franklin County; and a $4.4 million replacement project at the intersection of Valley Dell Drive and Gravois Road in Jefferson County.
By comparison, the list calls for 18 projects worth $31.2 million in the more rural northwest part of the state.The Kansas City region will receive $25.5 million in funding for 14 projects in the initiative’s first year.The state will direct $14.5 million to 13 projects in northeast Missouri next fiscal year.“I understand that in St. Louis, maybe you have a couple of areas where there’s a bottleneck, so that is a concern,” said Sen. Cindy O’Laughlin, R-Shelbina, in northeast Missouri. “But in our area, we have roads that are falling apart, and you’re in danger of driving off the road and overturning.“We all realize that there’s various competing interests, and that we have to find a way to address that,” O’Laughlin said.
In Year 2, the list calls for $13.3 million in St. Louis area projects, including replacing the North Broadway bridge over Interstate 44 in St. Louis. That compares to six projects that year in the Kansas City region worth $21.5 million.There are no projects in the St. Louis region in the third year of the plan and just three worth $5.9 million in the fourth and final year, including the replacement of the Missouri Highway 47 bridge over Interstate 44 in St. Clair in Franklin County.MoDOT officials said the infusion of cash would free up funds for other road projects around the state. Voters in November rejected a 10-cent increase to the state’s fuel tax that would have jump started construction projects.Some Democrats agree that the projects should be the subject of political horsetrading.“That’s the business we signed up for. That is literally what we do,” said Sen. Jason Holsman, D-Kansas City. “You will see some changes to that list if it is going to successfully navigate both chambers.”Eigel and Onder said they agreed with Missouri voters that taxes should not be raised to pay for the upgrades, and did not doubt the concept of issuing bonds to fund bridge repairs, especially because bridges are long-term assets.Eigel, Onder and O’Laughlin made the comments during a press conference organized to launch the Senate Conservative Caucus, a six-member subset of Senate Republicans.They said they would act as a resource for Senate conservatives. Members said the caucus was not formed to challenge the authority of Senate Republican leaders.


