JEFFERSON CITY • Thousands of Missourians expecting a state tax refund this spring could instead receive surprise tax bills because of a tax withholding error — a blunder that drew sharp criticism from members of the House Budget Committee Wednesday.Because of errors in withholding tables drawn up by the Department of Revenue that were corrected in September, taxpayers expecting to receive modest refunds could instead owe the state money. And even those who do receive a refund could have it reduced by as much as 90 percent, the department has said.Making matters worse, the state is depending on those people who will owe money to send in their checks so that revenues match the amount of money the state is seeking to spend this fiscal year.

Lawmakers expressed frustration that issues with state-formulated withholding tables were not widely publicized, which could have mitigated surprise bills.“It’s a lack of communication,” said Rep. Kip Kendrick of Columbia, the ranking Democrat on the budget panel. “I’m going to have very upset constituents — everybody in this room will have very upset constituents — and somehow we’re all crossing our fingers right now hoping they’ll owe us money. That’s terrifying.”As of Wednesday, income tax revenue was down $532 million, or 13 percent, this fiscal year compared with the same point last fiscal year. Department of Revenue Director Joel Walters on Wednesday blamed sluggish figures on the withholding error.Walters said he still expected general revenue collections to grow as tax season intensified. Walters said he still believed the state’s estimate of 1.7 percent general revenue growth over last fiscal year was accurate.“I am confident of that,” he told lawmakers.Next year’s estimate forecasts a 2 percent growth in net general revenue over this year. Gov. Mike Parson’s recommendations for the state’s $30 billion budget are based on that assumption.“I think that number’s appropriate,” House Speaker Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield, said of the predicted revenue growth.Tax refund problems this year are due in part to the December 2017 federal tax overhaul, championed by Republican lawmakers and President Donald Trump.Congress doubled the standard deduction and eliminated the personal exemption. Missouri bases its income taxes on the federal system and allows a personal exemption only if one is available for federal filers.In the past, taxpayers who minimized the number of dependents generally didn’t owe the state money when they filed. The changes in state withholding tables means those people should change their strategy on this year’s return.
“Now you should claim those dependents to not owe money,” state Treasurer Scott Fitzpatrick has said. “For people who didn’t change their elections after the tax changes occurred, having no dependents creates a liability.”Another problem: Walters said the state did not notice until the federal tax changes a 15-year-old defect in its withholding formula that went unnoticed until the federal tax law exacerbated the impact of the error.“None of this impacts the actual amount of tax anybody owes,” Walters said, explaining that even if an employer did not withhold an adequate amount, the amount of taxes owed did not change.Rep. David Wood, R-Versailles, asked whether anyone should be disciplined over the error.“I have no fear of giving consequences to people,” Walters said. “This is a situation where when I look through it, you know, if I see that there’s somebody that deserves consequences, I will do it. I haven’t seen that at this point.”
The surprise tax bills have drawn special scrutiny from Democrats, who are also concerned about the effects on revenue from two tax laws state Republicans have approved in recent years.House Minority Leader Crystal Quade, D-Springfield, has proposed a bill that would extend the deadline for Missourians to pay their 2018 income tax bill.On Wednesday, Quade asked Walters about how widespread the filing issues will be, something the department has been hesitant to estimate.“I would like to know the amount of families, or people, that are going to be affected by this so that we can start to get word out to our constituents,” Quade said before the Wednesday budget hearing.The spotty collections come as lawmakers begin to parse Parson’s budget request for next fiscal year, which starts July 1. Parson, a Republican, spent time Wednesday meeting with individual members of the House and Senate, including legislative leaders and new members on both sides of the aisle.In the short meetings on Tuesday and Wednesday, Parson outlined his plans for boosting workforce development and upgrading infrastructure.“He also spent time answering questions and listening to the concerns of local communities, as well as listening to the priorities of individual members,” said spokesman Steele Shippy.Kurt Erickson of the Post-Dispatch and the Associated Press contributed to this report.


