JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri officials want more time to decide whether to accept the donation of a former rail line that state parks boosters want converted into a biking and hiking trail.Faced with a Feb. 21 federal decision deadline, the Missouri Department of Natural Resources and the Missouri Central Railroad, a subsidiary of Ameren, on Thursday asked the U.S. Surface Transportation Board for a six-month negotiation extension, a DNR spokeswoman said in an email."DNR and Missouri Central Railroad intend to continue working toward the goal of signing an interim trail use agreement in the near future, if mutually agreeable terms can be reached," said Connie Patterson, spokeswoman for DNR.

The 144-mile former rail line, stretching from Beaufort in Franklin County to Windsor in western Missouri, would resemble the Katy Trail, another former rail line that cyclists and hikers use to traverse the state.











Then-Gov. Jay Nixon, a Democrat, announced plans to convert the rail line in 2016. He has continued to promote the project since leaving office.Patterson said Thursday the Surface Transportation Board is not operating due to the partial federal government shutdown."However, it will continue to have jurisdiction to grant the extension even if the shutdown prevents it from doing so until after Feb. 21," she said, citing past board decisions as precedent.Although the state and the railroad have completed the "complicated endeavor" of salvaging the line, the two sides have not struck an Interim Trail Use Agreement.
That said, the two sides have made "substantial progress" in that regard, according to a letter the two sides sent to the federal board on Thursday.In asking for the delay, the DNR and the rail road cited the "extreme complexity" of converting the corridor, which stretches through 10 counties, numerous small cities and various other settlements. "The size and complexity of the corridor adds to the significant undertaking for trail sponsorship, and it is essential that MDNR understand the immediate and long term liabilities, costs, benefits and opportunities involved," the letter states.
The request says that three Missouri governors have been in office since the trail was first proposed, meaning each has "needed to be briefed" on the project.Mike Sutherland, deputy state parks director, said in December that officials were worried about the cost of constructing and maintaining the trail, and whether that would divert finite resources from existing state parks.Project boosters, including Nixon, have urged state parks enthusiasts to contact Republican Gov. Mike Parson's administration to voice support for the project.The Missouri Farm Bureau Federation has opposed the planned trail network, saying it would disrupt nearby farms and lead to increased road and public safety expenses.Meanwhile, the state has not moved forward with development plans for four mothballed state parks acquired during Nixon's tenure.Despite the lack of development, a state parks official told the Post-Dispatch last year there were no plans to sell off the land.


