JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson on Thursday announced that he would move hundreds of state employees from the Department of Economic Development to other agencies across state government.The reorganization, Parson said, will "streamline" the Department of Economic Development, or DED, so that it can focus solely on economic development programs, moving extraneous agencies out from under its umbrella.The size of the office will plummet, from 863 employees currently to 178 after the changes take effect at the end of August, Parson's office said.

Approximately 597 DED employees affected will be divided among the Department of Higher Education, the Department of Natural Resources and the Department of Insurance, Financial Institutions and Professional Registration. Fifteen other employees will work from the lieutenant governor's office, while 73 vacant positions will be eliminated, Parson's office said.The move came the morning after Parson, a Republican, delivered his first State of the State address, during which he said he would focus on workforce development and infrastructure investments this legislative session.In announcing the reorganization, Parson's office cited a study conducted over the summer that concluded the DED had more functions compared to similar state agencies across the country.States that devoted more of their economic development resources to "directly engaging with businesses ... tended to outperform Missouri in terms of job creation and capital investment," his office said."I told you yesterday we were going to take bold steps," Parson said. "I meant that as much more than just a speech I made yesterday."Parson signed three executive orders to trigger the shuffling of state government:• One executive order, and perhaps the most consequential, is Parson's move to shift the Division of Workforce Development and the Missouri Economic Research and Information Center from DED to the Department of Higher Education.The Department of Higher Education would grow by approximately 344 employees, according to Parson's office.Commissioner of Higher Education Zora Mulligan said the Department of Economic Development's mission had become too diluted, whereas the Department of Higher Education had been limited to promoting traditional degree programs.
"In a 21st century economy, we know that we also have to be helping individuals run through apprenticeship programs, get a short-term credential, and so that broadening of perspective is a really, really useful tool for the state of Missouri," Mulligan told reporters.A cornerstone to Parson's workforce development strategy is the proposed creation of a $22 million program called Fast Track to get people into new, high-demand jobs more quickly.Adults over the age of 25, with a household income of less than $80,000, could qualify for 100 percent tuition reimbursement to learn new skills in job fields such as nursing.
• The Division of Energy will be moved from the Department of Economic Development to the Department of Natural Resources. The division promotes energy efficiency and renewable energy use to "drive economic growth, provide for a healthier environment, and achieve greater energy security for future generations," according to its website.The move will result in approximately 37 employees moving to the Department of Natural Resources, which oversees things like environmental inspections and state parks.• The Public Service Commission and the Office of Public Counsel will move to the Department of Insurance, Financial Institutions and Professional Registration.He is renaming the Department of Insurance, Financial Institutions and Professional Registration the Department of Commerce and Insurance.Approximately 216 employees will be affected by the move, Parson said.Ryan Silvey, commissioner of the Public Service Commission, which regulates utilities, said the move will not affect the commission because it operates independently of other state departments."The administration made it clear that they were wanting to refocus DED," Silvey said.He said moving the Public Service Commission and Office of Public Counsel under the umbrella the Department of Insurance, Financial Institutions and Professional Registration was a "better fit" because all three offices have "consumer affairs-driven" missions.The orders will take effect on Aug. 28, unless the Legislature intervenes, but leaders in the GOP-controlled House and Senate signaled their support on Thursday. Parson said the cost of the moves would be "absorbed" by the agencies.


