With a tweet in a snowstorm, former state Rep. Robert Cornejo prosecuted the Republican establishment case against Amendment 1.In November, Missouri voters of all political stripes overwhelmingly approved the anti-corruption constitutional amendment, sponsored by the bipartisan Clean Missouri coalition. It limits lobbyists gifts, sets campaign donation limits, makes state lawmakers subject to the state’s open records law, closes the revolving door between lawmaking and lobbying and reduces gerrymandering in the drawing of legislative boundaries. Amendment 1 passed with 62 percent of the vote.But some Republican establishment interests — including Gov. Mike Parson — nearly immediately announced plans to try to undo the will of the voters.

Enter Cornejo. The former state representative and attorney from St. Peters resigned his seat last year when Parson appointed him to the Labor and Industrial Relations Commission, a plum assignment that pays about $107,000.On Saturday, Cornejo lamented that Amendment 1 might get in the way of his former colleagues’ beer-drinking habits. A Boston-based craft brewer, Harpoon Brewery, had tweeted a picture of two cans of its Harpoon IPA, with a message sent to Republican and Democratic lawmakers, suggesting they get together for a beer summit to work out their differences.The brewery was taking a shot at the federal shutdown, which is limiting the ability of small craft breweries to get new cans approved for their ever-changing beer lineups.Cornejo tried to turn the tweet into a metaphor about what is wrong with Missouri’s Amendment 1, which affects state lawmakers.
This great idea is banned here in Missouri #moleg thanks to the unconstitutional sham of Clean Missouri! People of all political stripes should get together over a drink and work towards common ground. Prost! https://t.co/GjuUUcG2hT— Robert Cornejo (@CornejoForMO) January 12, 2019

“This great idea is banned here in Missouri thanks to the unconstitutional sham of Clean Missouri!” Cornejo wrote. “People of all political stripes should get together over a drink and work towards common ground.”The problem, of course, is that nothing in Cornejo’s tweet was true.In fact, the strength of the Clean Missouri proposal was that it brought together people from both sides of the aisle, including Democrats such as former U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill, and Republicans such as former U.S. Sen. John C. Danforth, and former state senators Rob Schaaf, Jim Lembke and Bob Johnson. There is nothing that stops any of those people, or any state lawmakers, from getting together for a beer to discuss their differences. The main idea of Amendment 1 is to make them use their own money to pay for that beer, rather than take money from lobbyists, as has been the norm in Jefferson City for far too long.It’s easy to understand why Cornejo might be averse to that suggestion. In each of his last two years in the House, he was the fifth-highest lobbyist gift-taker, receiving thousands of dollars in free meals, tickets to concerts, golf outings, and, yes, beer.But to be clear, Amendment 1 doesn’t even ban that which Harpoon Brewery was attempting to accomplish.That beer isn’t available in Missouri, but I found it online retailing for $16.99 a 12-pack. That would mean each can of beer theoretically sent to a lawmaker would cost $1.42. That’s still legal in Missouri under Amendment 1, which sets a “$5 per occurrence” lobbyist gift limit.
As I was responding to Cornejo on Twitter, trying unsuccessfully to get him to admit to the error of his ways, I was sipping on an Incarnation IPA made by 4 Hands Brewery here in St. Louis. The six-pack of cans I bought costs $7.99, or about $1.33 per can.Here’s another truth Cornejo chose not to respond to during our discussion:Unlike lawmakers, in his new job, he’s not allowed to take any gifts from lobbyists at all.That’s because among his first acts as governor, Parson signed an executive order banning members of his administration from taking such gifts. That executive order also includes a ban on members of the governor’s administration from taking lobbyist jobs upon leaving state government work.
So, the very governor who has announced his support for legislative efforts to overturn Amendment 1, signed an executive order containing similar elements to the anti-corruption effort approved by voters.This is the sort of common ground that the folks at Harpoon Brewery intended for lawmakers to find together, as they shared discussion over a hoppy IPA.It’s a good idea. And it’s one that should happen more often in Missouri.It still can.The voters in Cornejo’s home county understand that. Nearly 63 percent of voters in the GOP hotbed of St. Charles County approved Amendment 1.I’ll wager two cans of Cornejo’s favorite IPA that those voters won’t take too kindly to lawmakers attempting to overturn their will.












