JEFFERSON CITY • It wasn’t the kind of start Republicans hinted at when they launched the 100th Missouri General Assembly on Wednesday. Meeting in their first full day of the legislative session Thursday, Republican infighting brought chamber business to an immediate halt as an intra-party power battle broke out between rank-and-file lawmakers and newly installed Senate President Pro Tem Dave Schatz.The seven hour filibuster tested the resolve of Schatz and signaled the next four months could be a rocky affair, despite the GOP holding an iron grip on state government.

And, it came after Republican Gov. Mike Parson has been working to restore calm to a Capitol that was roiled last year by the scandal involving former Gov. Eric Greitens.The issue at the heart of the filibuster were proposed changes in the way the Senate operates.Schatz, a Sullivan businessman, for example, wanted to add two members to the powerful Senate Appropriations Committee, which helps write the state’s $28 billion budget.The expansion had the support of Senate Minority Leader Gina Walsh, D-Bellfontaine Neighbors, who said the additional slots could be filled by newly elected senators, giving them much needed experience in an age of term limits.Opponents, however, said the move — and other changes — would spread senators too thin and force them to miss hearings being held by the other 20 committees.“It’s gotten to where it just taxes everyone,” said Sen. Doug Libla, R-Poplar Bluff.Sen. Gary Romine, R-Farmington, led the pushback, saying there should be fewer committees altogether.“Instead of consolidating, we’re expanding,” said Romine, who laid blame for the filibuster at the feet of Schatz.
“It has to do with a lack of communication,” Romine said.Democrats needled Republicans for being unable to get through even one day without descending into disagreement.“This is our first real day and Republicans are infighting,” said Sen. Jamilah Nasheed, D-St. Louis. “If this is an indicator moving forward, it’s just appalling.”
Nasheed and Sen. Jill Schupp, D-Creve Coeur, said there are other issues the Senate should be spending its time on, such as a problem with the state’s income tax withholding tables that could result in people having to pay an income tax bill, rather than receive a refund.“This was a big mess up,” Schupp said.Sen. Bob Onder, R-Lake Saint Louis, said the changes proposed by Schatz came as a surprise to many members who thought the new leader would keep Senate rules intact.“I think that started us in a bad position,” Onder said.In the end, Schatz blinked first and brought the impasse to an end by removing one of the controversial provisions. The change was approved on a bipartisan 23-4 vote.Schatz said the issue could be revisited in the coming days.The legislation is Senate Resolution 19.


