A St. Louis judge was appointed Wednesday by Gov. Mike Parson to the Eastern District of the Missouri Court of Appeals.













St. Louis Circuit Judge Robin Ransom


Judge Robin Ransom was just selected in October to lead the 22nd Circuit that covers St. Louis and was the first African-American woman to do so. She was first appointed to the 22nd Judicial Circuit in 2008.

Ransom's appointment follows Judge Lisa S. Van Amburg's retirement from the appellate seat in August. She was one of three nominees for the post.
Ransom is a St. Louis native and earned her bachelor's degree in political science and sociology from Douglass Residential College-Rutgers University in 1988. She graduated from the University of Missouri School of Law in 1991.After law school, Ransom worked for the St. Louis County Public Defender's Office and the St. Louis County Prosecuting Attorney's Office, as well as the St. Louis County Family Court-Juvenile Division. She was later appointed to be Family Court commissioner in 2002 and remained there until her appointment to the circuit court in 2008.
Ransom serves as a mentor with nonprofit The Literacy Project and as a member of the Missouri State Foster Care and Adoption Board. She also serves with the Juvenile Officer Performance Standards Work Group.Ransom was selected over Clayton lawyer John P. Torbitzky and Cape Girardeau Circuit Judge Michael E. Gardner. 


