JEFFERSON CITY • A special application that destroys text messages wasn’t the only secretive phone app used by then- Gov. Eric Greitens’ administration.Gov. Mike Parson’s administration confirmed Wednesday that some state phones from the Greitens era had a special security app that allowed users to schedule when their text messages are deleted.No current administration officials use the Silent Phone app, Parson spokesman Steele Shippy said.

Officials say the Silent Phone app was installed as part of the preparation for a trade mission in 2017 to help maintain secure communications while overseas.According to records obtained by the Post-Dispatch through the Sunshine Law, among those who had the Silent Phone app was Chief Operating Officer Drew Erdmann, who downloaded the service on the recommendation of the Missouri Highway Patrol.The app is designed for business and government employees who are concerned about protecting sensitive information from hackers.But Silent Phone also could make it harder for the public to see who is communicating with government officials about the public’s business. Records of such communication are generally public, and laws require such records to be retained and produced upon request.A similar application used by employees of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency became the subject of a federal lawsuit last year when the conservative group Judicial Watch asked a judge to force the agency to provide all employee communications sent using an app called Signal.Like Silent Phone, once texts are deleted from the Signal app, they are no longer available.Georgetown Law professor David Vladeck told Wired that deleting U.S. government records would blatantly violate the Federal Records Act.“It’s no different from taking records home and burning them,” Vladeck said. “They’re not your records, they’re the federal government’s, and you’re not supposed to do that.”The destruction of text messages by state employees also could violate the law. The governor’s office has a system for safeguarding emails, texts and records of phone calls, but it is unclear if any were texts destroyed by the Silent Phone app, because the app is designed to leave no trace that the record existed.In the email exchange obtained by the newspaper, Parson’s executive secretary Michelle Hallford — who also worked in Greitens’ administration — wrote that Erdmann needed to download the application, as well as one called “Content Blocker.”
“Drew needs both apps on his phone,” Hallford wrote.In response, Erdmann, who was hired by Greitens, wrote: “One is for secure comms recommended by HWP. The other enables me to back up my phone.”In a statement issued Wednesday, Erdmann said he stopped using the app more than a year ago. He also said it was not used to hide text messages.
“The app was strictly used as a security measure and pertained only to situations when safety and security necessitated within the Governor’s Office related to overseas travel (e.g. China, Middle East) or during domestic security events (e.g., aftermath of Stockley Verdict). The last time I recall using the app was in November 2017 while traveling for official business to the Middle East,” Erdman said.Capt. John Hotz, spokesman for the Missouri Highway Patrol, said the agency used the app to protect and encrypt sensitive operational information during high-risk situations such as the protests in Ferguson.“The app was also utilized by the Governor’s Security Division during a trip to China and Middle East. The app provided a hardened communication platform that prevented the information from being intercepted or hacked,” Hotz said.Greitens, who resigned June 1 under a cloud of scandal, was notoriously secretive in his 17 months on the job. He spent little time communicating with the Capitol press corps, installed a lock on the door to the press room and hasn’t made any public appearances since his departure.More than two dozen people in Greitens’ administration used or downloaded the Confide application, which destroys text messages between users.Open records advocates say using Confide to discuss public business would violate state records retention laws.The Confide usage remains a matter of litigation.Attorney Mark Pedroli, who sued the Greitens administration in 2017, said in October that Greitens and his team violated a May 31 court order requiring the governor’s attorneys to turn over the names of anyone in the office who at any time downloaded or used the Confide app.












