JEFFERSON CITY • After a tumultuous 2018 filled with talk of impeachment and an expensive and heated election for U.S. Senate, Missouri officials moved closer to bringing some calm to state government Thursday.In a ceremony in the lobby of the Missouri Supreme Court building, Republican Eric Schmitt was sworn in as Missouri’s 43rd attorney general. He was appointed to the post by Gov. Mike Parson.Schmitt, 43, replaces fellow Republican Josh Hawley, who was sworn in as U.S. senator Thursday in Washington after beating two-term incumbent Democrat Claire McCaskill in November.

Now, with one more vacancy to be filled, Parson told the Post-Dispatch that he’s hoping to put a year of upheaval in the rear view mirror.“I think the one thing we’ve really got to get back on track on is making sure we all understand we’re public servants. And, above everything else, we should be working for the people every day,” Parson said.Parson, who ascended to the top post in state government after Republican Eric Greitens resigned amid scandal, said he wasn’t concerned that the remaking of state government has resulted in four statewide offices being held by people who weren’t elected to those posts.“It’s unusual circumstances. We’ve never been down this road before,” Parson said.The final domino will fall on Jan. 14, when Rep. Scott Fitzpatrick, R-Cassville, who also was appointed by Parson, is sworn in to replace Schmitt as treasurer for the final two years of that term.Schmitt, of Glendale, said he will keep politics out of the office after allegations surfaced during Hawley’s tenure that political consultants had embedded themselves in the official workings of the office to help Hawley plot his bid for Senate.“We have a bright line here of making sure the folks in this office focus on doing the work of the attorney general’s office,” Schmitt said.Schmitt, who will oversee an agency with about 300 employees, has already chosen top aides in his office, including Cristian Stevens as deputy attorney general for criminal litigation and Tom Albus as first assistant attorney general, both of whom are former U.S. prosecutors.
“The job of attorney general of the great state of Missouri is a serious responsibility, and as the state’s chief legal officer, I take that responsibility seriously,” he said in a short address after being sworn in by Missouri Supreme Court Chief Justice Zel Fischer.Since being named to the post in mid-November, Schmitt said he’s been on the hunt for attorneys for the office.“All I’m doing is recruiting,” he said.Schmitt offered few specifics on how he’d run the office differently than Hawley but said he wants to focus on addressing opioid abuse and supporting county prosecutors.
“People deserve to feel safe,” Schmitt said.Schmitt also is considering adding the ZIP code of drivers to a report his office produces that tracks racial profiling by police in vehicle stops. That could help determine if a disproportionate number of black motorists are being pulled over in predominantly white municipalities.Schmitt also has suggested he would use his new job to address perceived injustices within the state’s criminal justice system — an issue he took on during his tenure in the Senate where he sponsored legislation after the 2014 Ferguson protests aimed at stopping police departments from aggressively issuing traffic tickets to raise revenue.“My job, my duty is to protect Missourians, and I’ll work hard every single day to do just that,” Schmitt said.












