JEFFERSON CITY • Treasurer Eric Schmitt will be sworn in as Missouri’s next attorney general on Thursday, the same day fellow Republican Josh Hawley becomes the state’s next U.S. senator.But Schmitt’s replacement, even though he’s already been appointed by Gov. Mike Parson, won’t be sworn into office until Jan. 14, leaving a gap of 11 days in which the state will not have an official state treasurer.For Rep. Scott Fitzpatrick, R-Cassville, the delay could be beneficial.

Under state law, if an appointee to be treasurer holds the office for more than two years, he or she cannot run for more than one additional four-year term.The current term ends Jan. 11, 2021. Thus, by waiting until Jan. 14, Fitzpatrick would be able to run for two full terms, giving him the possibility of holding the $107,700-a-year job for a decade.Fitzpatrick said more factors than just term limits went into picking that day.“There were more considerations than just that,” he told the Post-Dispatch Wednesday.“I think part of that was, one, I needed to get some of my personal affairs in order,” Fitzpatrick said. “And, there are some personal financial issues, such as holdings and investments, that have to be reviewed.”In addition, it is the same day Auditor Nicole Galloway, a Democrat, is being sworn in.
The tactic isn’t a new one. Lawmakers elected in special elections have routinely kept a close eye on the calendar to determine if their swearing-in date will be affected by the limits on legislative terms.Such a consideration wasn’t an issue for Schmitt, because the attorney general position is not term-limited.Fitzpatrick, first elected to the House in 2012, was the latest domino to fall in a remake of the top echelon of state government in the wake of former Gov. Eric Greitens’ resignation last year.
Parson, who had been lieutenant governor, took over June 1. He then appointed former Senate Majority Floor Leader Mike Kehoe to his old job.After Hawley beat U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill in November, Parson appointed Schmitt to replace Hawley. Then came Fitzpatrick’s appointment to replace Schmitt.Fitzpatrick, who was chairman of the powerful House Budget Committee, represents Barry County plus parts of Stone and Lawrence counties. He is the founder of MariCorp U.S., a Shell Knob-based marine manufacturing and construction company.Schmitt, a former state senator from Glendale, is scheduled to be sworn in at 11:05 a.m. Thursday in the lobby of the Missouri Supreme Court.Hawley will be sworn in Thursday afternoon in Washington.


