JEFFERSON CITY • After voters overwhelmingly adopted a new redistricting plan this year that could reduce Republican dominance in Missouri, state party leaders are increasingly coalescing around proposals to undo those constitutional provisions and tighten access to the initiative petition process.Although Republicans again won two-thirds majorities in both legislative chambers, voters stung the GOP three times in six months on high-profile ballot items.Aided by an avalanche of spending by liberal groups and unions, campaigners convinced voters to raise the minimum wage, reject a GOP-backed “right to work” law and enact a suite of ethics rules that included the new redistricting plan for state legislative districts.

Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, told the Associated Press last week that he would campaign for a new ballot measure to reverse the redistricting elements of the so-called “Clean Missouri” initiative.“Fundamentally, you think when the people vote you shouldn’t be changing that vote,” Parson said. “But the reality of it is that is somewhat what your job is sometimes, if you know something’s unconstitutional, if you know some of it’s not right.”Parson also indicated he would back efforts to restrict the ability to place any new questions on the ballot.“We’re not at all denying the ability to do it,” Dan Mehan, the president of the Missouri Chamber of Commerce and Industry, said of initiative petition efforts. “But we just want to make sure we’re approaching it in a proper way.”The Clean Missouri ethics push seems to have rankled Republicans the most.Sixty-two percent of voters supported the changes. Besides redistricting changes, changes include limiting lobbyist gifts and subjecting legislators to the Sunshine Law.In response, one Republican state senator filed legislation that would exempt constituent emails and other communications from disclosure. The Missouri Republican State Committee donated $150,000 on Nov. 21 to a group called Fair Missouri, which is seeking to undo the redistricting changes.Sen. Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, the incoming leader of the Missouri Senate, said Republican leaders were still studying the full impact of Clean Missouri.But he suggested legislators would debate raising the threshold necessary to pass a constitutional amendments. In Florida, for example, proposed amendments need 60 percent support to take effect.“Maybe we need to raise the threshold as to what it requires to amend the Constitution,” Schatz said.Mehan agreed, saying: “In Missouri, it’s 50 percent plus one vote to change the constitution. Do we want to make that two-thirds? Sixty (percent)?”He also suggested requiring petitioners to collect signatures in each of Missouri’s eight congressional districts.To put a statutory change on the ballot, petitioners must now gather signatures of 5 percent of registered voters in six of eight congressional districts. To modify the constitution, signatures from 8 percent of voters in six districts is required.
“If we’re going to do some sort of constitutional change, then let’s make sure we get people in all eight districts — not just six — expand it to be a truly statewide effort rather than three-quarters of the state,” Mehan said.Several lawmakers have filed resolutions that would place such questions before voters. It is unclear whether Republicans will attempt to change rules only for constitutional questions, or if statutory changes and voter referendums on state laws could also see tougher standards.One change, Senate Joint Resolution 1, sponsored by Sen. David Sater, R-Cassville, would require constitutional amendments to receive two-thirds of the vote to pass.Under his version, amendments placed on the ballot simply for the purpose of repealing any amendment passed before 2021 would need to be approved by only a simple majority — meaning it would be easier to repeal older amendments and harder to enact new ones.
Jack Cardetti, who ran this year’s winning campaign to legalize medical marijuana in Missouri, said the initiative petition process was an “important mechanism” for groups to bring issues directly before voters.“Missourians have a long tradition of being able to directly petition their government for change,” Cardetti said. “That is an important mechanism in our democracy to bring issues to the forefront that are being ignored in Jefferson City.”As evidenced by vote counts this year, the Legislature is often out of step with voters on big issues. Cardetti’s Amendment 2, known as New Approach Missouri, passed with nearly 66 percent of the vote after years of sputtering in the Legislature — even though medical marijuana efforts did gain bipartisan support.Sixty-two percent of voters chose to raise the minimum wage through a statutory change, which lawmakers had declined to do. Sixty-five percent of voters rejected the right-to-work law, which then-Gov. Eric Greitens, a Republican, touted as his signature achievement.Cardetti said the ballot box backlash was due to the disconnect between voters and the Legislature.Mehan countered that out-of-state, left-leaning groups spent big on many of the successful campaigns last year — casting doubt on the assertion there is grassroots enthusiasm for policies that Democratic voters tend to support.Cardetti said Republicans had used the petition process, too — most notably in 2010 when St. Louis financier and Republican donor Rex Sinquefeld pushed a successful ballot question that banned earnings taxes outside of St. Louis and Kansas City. The measure also forces the two cities to reauthorize their taxes every five years.“That would never have been able to pass the Legislature,” Cardetti said.But, Cardetti said, some proposals to tighten the process are worth a look, such as one backed last year by Secretary of State Jay Ashcroft, a Republican.The legislation would have raised various fees to discourage frivolous petitions, which eat up state resources. Ashcroft also hinted he would support the attempt to raise the threshold needed to change the Constitution.“It is important to improve the initiative petition process, such as finding a method to reject frivolous petitions earlier in the process,” Ashcroft said in a statement, “and ensuring our constitution isn’t changed without broad agreement while still protecting the citizens’ right to petition their government. I look forward to the Legislature’s debate.”


