WASHINGTON • Missouri lost a governor and an incumbent senator in 2018, a tumultuous year in which the state was in the national spotlight on two major story lines with long-term effects on Show Me politics.Some days, Missouri seemed like the Shock Me state. Beneath the daily roller coaster of Donald Trump’s presidency, Missouri had its ups, downs and era-defining twists and turns.Former Gov. Eric Greitens, a rocketing figure in Republican politics who, leading into 2018, was being mentioned as potential contender for higher national office, resigned amid allegations he’d had an extramarital affair and threatened his lover with a compromising photograph.

Like Trump, Greitens had campaigned for office against “career politicians” and political corruption. After his resignation, Greitens virtually disappeared from public life overnight. He was rarely seen or heard from for the rest of the year, and Missouri settled into a period of temporary normality under the new governor, the grandfatherly Mike Parson.In November, Republican Attorney General Josh Hawley, on as rapid of a rise as Greitens before Greitens’ fall, defeated incumbent Sen. Claire McCaskill, a two-term Democrat caught in the crosscurrents of national and state politics.McCaskill was a self-professed aspirant for the political center. Hawley is a conservative Trump ally who agreed with the president on virtually everything. Trump’s lingering popularity in Missouri and McCaskill’s voting record at major junctures, like Trump Supreme Court nominees, proved to be her undoing in a state that has increasingly moved right in the 21st century.The upshot: Missouri enhanced its Republican representation in Congress even as that body is freshly split down the middle. Hawley will join incumbent Sen. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., in a 53-47 Republican majority in the United States Senate.Meanwhile, all eight of Missouri’s U.S. House members were re-elected. But the six Republicans in the delegation will now be part of a minority after the Democrats took control of the House with a gain of 40 seats on Nov. 8.Suddenly, Rep. William Lacy Clay, D-St. Louis, and Rep. Emanuel Cleaver, D-Kansas City, are thrust back into the majority, and their Democratic Party will control committees, investigative work, and the flow of legislation over the next two years, at least.
“Being in the majority in the House means everything,” Clay said.While the collapse of Greitens’ governorship was the result of alleged personal improprieties and political arrogance of his own doing, McCaskill’s electoral loss was primarily viewed as the result of trends that had moved beyond her reach.She had been elected in 2006 and re-elected in 2012 with essentially the same center-left political philosophy and voting record. She had been a survivor in a state that had not voted for a Democrat for president in the last five elections and eight of the last 10.
McCaskill’s defeat ended an era. As long as she was in office, and a recognizable national figure, Missouri Democrats could cling to the idea that Missouri was a state that could oscillate back and forth between parties in its top statewide elections. But since McCaskill was re-elected in 2012, Missouri Republicans have won every statewide race for president, senator and governor.The generational shift is significant. State Auditor Nicole Galloway is now the highest-ranking elected Democrat in Missouri. She is just 36, three years younger than Hawley, who will turn 39 on New Year’s Eve.McCaskill was 45 when she was first elected auditor in 1998. She used that as a springboard to the U.S. Senate eight years later, after losing a run for governor in 2004. Much attention will be on Galloway as the calendar moves toward the state’s 2020 gubernatorial election. Blunt, who turns 69 in January, is not up for re-election until 2022.The long-term impact of a third Missouri story line of 2018 — that of former Democratic Secretary of State Jason Kander — is harder to foresee. He had been considered a rising national star in a Democratic Party desperately seeking new faces, even though he had lost narrowly to Blunt in the 2016 Senate race.As 2018 began, Kander was traveling extensively around the country for a voting-rights political group he started. He got favorable media and activist attention in states that hold early presidential primaries and caucuses. But shortly after declaring he would run for mayor of Kansas City, Kander withdrew and announced he was getting treatment for depression.His service as an Army intelligence officer in Afghanistan had weighed harder on him than he’d admitted. He needed to get help, he said. Suddenly, his political ambitions didn’t seem as important as a quieter, healthier life in the moment. Maybe that’s the biggest takeaway from Missouri’s 2018 political year.


