JEFFERSON CITY • A new state-run nursing home for military veterans could be on the horizon in Missouri.A review of state bidding documents shows the Missouri Veterans Commission is seeking a contractor to determine if the current fleet of seven homes for aging veterans is enough to meet demand in the coming decade.As an option, the contractor also could propose adding bed space to the state’s existing veterans’ homes in Bellefontaine Neighbors, Warrensburg, Mount Vernon, St. James, Cape Girardeau, Mexico and Cameron.

The study comes as Gov. Mike Parson recently cut the ribbon on $13 million in renovations to the Bellefontaine Neighbors home, including the conversion of rooms to all single-occupancy with private restrooms.The governor, a veteran, also made a stop this month at the Warrensburg home.In all, the commission manages a total of 1,350 beds across the state for long term skilled nursing care. In July, the commission reported there was a waiting list of 761 veterans seeking space in the facilities.
Bid documents show the contractor should estimate the number of veterans that will be eligible for nursing home care over the next 10, 20 and 30 years.The analysis also should determine where a new home should be located in order to reach the greatest number of veterans. Additionally, the contractor should propose sites within 90 miles of the facility in Bellefontaine Neighbors, located north of St. Louis.
Among the considerations that should be made are the availability of health care workers and other facilities that might compete with the available workforce, the documents note.The report will also outline projected costs of building a new facility and operational costs for the first five years.Veterans commission spokesman Daniel Bell said proposals are due in January.


