NEW YORK • St. Louis’ bid to win a Major League Soccer team next year hinges as much on the merits of its competitors as on its own success.This contest won’t be decided by goals and teams, but by dollars and stadiums.Last week, club owners and officials praised St. Louis’ bid for an expansion franchise, impressed with the city’s love for soccer and the wealth of the proposed owners.

But history has proved, in sport after sport, team after team, that favorites don’t always stay favorites. Major League Soccer has demoted cities before, after plans changed.“There is significant competition for future Major League Soccer expansion,” cautioned Dan Courtemanche, a league executive vice president, at the owners’ December meeting last week.RELATED: See how St. Louis stacks up against the competitionTwenty-three teams played this year. New franchisees will open in Cincinnati next year, followed by Miami and Nashville in 2020. League Commissioner Don Garber has long targeted 28 teams as a “fully expanded” league. Despite recent discussion to move past 28, there’s little indication that would happen right away.One of those two spots is already gone: Garber said earlier this month that Anthony Precourt, owner of the Columbus Crew, will build the league’s 27th team in the hipster, high-tech mecca of Austin, Texas, and sell the Crew.That leaves room for expansion to just one city — and proposals from at least eight: Charlotte, N.C.; Detroit; Las Vegas; Phoenix; Raleigh, N.C.; Sacramento, Calif.; San Diego; and St. Louis.Owners and league officials have said repeatedly that the St. Louis bid — from World Wide Technology chief executive Jim Kavanaugh and Enterprise Holdings’ Taylor family — is a favorite.Kavanaugh briefly played professional soccer and owns the minor-league St. Louis Football Club. The Taylors bring a multibillion dollar bank account and a deep commitment to St. Louis. Their plans have recently won support from Missouri Gov. Mike Parson and St. Louis aldermen, two entities that dogged last year’s failed St. Louis bid for a team. And the ownership group has promised to pay out-of-pocket for a $250 million stadium on Market Street downtown.“St. Louis is a great market,” said Los Angeles Galaxy President Chris Klein, a St. Louis native and former De Smet soccer star. “And one I think Major League Soccer should be in.”The competitionBut frontrunners don’t always stay that way. Just a few years ago, a group of National Football League owners repeatedly praised the St. Louis effort to build a new football stadium and keep Stan Kroenke’s Rams in the city. The NFL’s expansion committee even recommended the team stay put. Then owners, swayed by the allure of Kroenke’s money and the grandeur of his vision, voted to send the Rams to Los Angeles.The current list of MLS expansion proposals is not fixed. League officials mention some on one day, and others on another. Garber has stopped naming them altogether, so as to avoid the complaints when he forgets one.But some of the eight cities have clearly moved down the list, if only temporarily.Garber, for instance, has publicly suggested that Charlotte and Raleigh aren’t in the running for this round of expansion. In September, he spoke to reporters about the success of clubs in Atlanta and Orlando, Fla., and franchises to come in Miami and Nashville. “I think we’re probably done expanding in the southeast for a little while,” he said.Sacramento, Calif., has a rabid soccer culture, the active support of city politicians, public money for a stadium, and a site picked out. But it doesn’t have a wealthy owner to woo the league.San Diego has a strong owners group and a growing, affluent region full of adults who grew up playing the sport — but voters there just turned down a plan to use city land for a new soccer stadium.Las Vegas, now a darling of professional sports teams, is an easy target. But Vegas Mayor Carolyn Goodman said a year ago that a Major League Soccer proposal was a few years away. And there are no public plans to attract a soccer team next year.
Two serious competitors remain, and they have some key advantages over St. Louis.‘We check a pretty big box’In November last year, the William Clay Ford family, which owns the NFL’s Detroit Lions, joined Detroit Pistons owner Tom Gores and Cleveland Cavaliers owner Dan Gilbert on a Motor City bid, beefing up an already star-studded application. A month later, they pitched their plan to the league expansion committee. The league loves the size of the metropolitan area — at 4.3 million, it’s double that of Austin. And its urban core is rapidly rebounding.But by May of this year, the Detroit group had dumped plans to build a soccer-specific, open-air stadium — a feature the league dearly loves. Instead, they said the new team would play at the Ford Field dome, home of the Lions. That month, Garber publicly said Detroit was no longer a front-runner. And in September this year, the Detroit owners wrote a letter to league brass saying they wouldn’t retrofit Ford Field’s roof with a retractable top, either.Detroit is now working hard to make the dome suitable. They’ve pitched a multimillion dollar renovation to accommodate soccer. And MLS success at the football stadium in Atlanta, which has drawn crowds exceeding 70,000 to some games, has softened the league’s opinion.Detroit bid spokesman Kevin Grigg said “open dialogue” with the league continued regarding Ford Field.
Officials say Phoenix, too, is appealing.The metropolitan area is the 11th-largest in the U.S., with a population of 4.7 million and double-digit growth over the decade. Moreover, the closest Major League Soccer teams are in Los Angeles, 370 miles away. A team in Phoenix would fill a Southwest hole, in a sports-crazy town.“This is arguably one of the most vibrant if not competitive sports markets in the country,” said Ray Artigue, a sports marketing consultant and former director of the sports business program at Arizona State University.The bid has a built-in fan base. The minor league team Phoenix Rising is one of the more popular in the United Soccer League. And the ownership group, headed by Rising owner and restaurant chain chairman Berke Bakay, have added power investors, including international soccer star Didier Drogba, the musician Diplo, and in February, Chinese hotel magnate and billionaire Alex Zheng.“We check a pretty big box,” said Bobby Dulle, Rising’s general manager.There are drawbacks to Phoenix. The group has pitched an open-air stadium, despite the desert heat. They say they’ll have giant fans and misters and water walls to cool the breeze.Indeed, a 112-degree day in July still drew a sold-out 7,500 to a Rising game — but would that work for the tens of thousands needed to fill out an MLS stadium?“Phoenicians are used to it,” Dulle said.Meanwhile, St. Louis’ bid is getting deeper into the details. The group is speaking with architects, hammering out tax incentives, lining up corporate support and getting ready to present to owners, when called upon.But anything could happen, cautioned Patrick Rishe, director of the sports business program at Washington University. Remember last year, when St. Louis thought its chances were dead?“The Taylors changed everything,” Rishe said.Who knows what will surprise us in Sacramento, he said, or San Diego, or Phoenix.


Austin














Conceptual rendering of what a potential Major League Soccer stadium would look like if built at city-owned McKalla Place in Austin, TX. Rendering courtesy of Austin FC


Metropolitan Statistical Area • Austin-Round Rock, 31st-largest in the U.S.2017 population estimate • 2.1 millionGrowth since 2010 • +400,000, or about 23 percentU.S. television market • No. 40 Ownership •  MLS commish Don Garber has given Columbus Crew owner Anthony Precourt the green light to put a team in Austin.Stadium • City officials have  approved a site in North Austin.Strengths • Austin is growing like crazy, and has no professional sports teams.Weaknesses • It’s unclear whether Precourt’s move to Austin will leave Columbus without a team.

Detroit














Artist rendering of how Ford Field might look if Detroit gets a Major League Soccer expansion team. Artist rendering courtesy Rossetti


Metropolitan Statistical Area •  Detroit-Warren-Dearborn, Mich., 14th-largest in the U.S.2017 population estimate •  4.3 millionGrowth since 2010 • +17,000, or less than one-half of 1 percentTelevision market • No. 14 in U.S.Ownership •  Detroit Pistons owner Tom Gores, Cleveland Cavaliers owner Dan Gilbert and the William Clay Ford family, which owns the Detroit Lions.Stadium •  A retrofitted Ford Field, home to the Detroit LionsStrengths •  A three-sport ownership group. Plus, Detroit’s a huge market, and the urban core is rebounding.Weakness • MLS likes soccer-specific stadiums, even post-Atlanta.

Phoenix














Rendering of the field view for the possible MLS stadium of Pheonix Rising FC release on March of 2018. Rendering by Populus


Populus


Metropolitan Statistical Area • Phoenix-Mesa-Scottsdale, 11th-largest in the U.S.2017 population estimate • 4.7 millionGrowth since 2010 • +544,000, or about 13 percentU.S. television market • No. 12 Ownership •  Kona Grill restaurant chain chairman Berke Bakay; Chinese hotel magnate and billionaire Alex Zheng; soccer star Didier Drogba and musician Diplo, among others.Stadium • Open-air stadium proposed east of downtown PhoenixStrengths • MLS has no teams in the Southwest.Weakness • Phoenix has every other major professional sports league, plus Spring Training and golf tournaments galore.

Sacramento














Sacramento Mayor Darrell Steinberg (right) said billionaire Ron Burkle agreed to buy controlling interest in Sacramento Republic FC, with a goal of bringing an MLS team to the city.


Rich Pedroncelli


Metropolitan Statistical Area • Sacramento-Roseville-Arden-Arcade, Calif., 27th-largest in the U.S.2017 population estimate • 2.3 millionGrowth since 2010 • +176,000, or about 8 percentU.S. television market • No. 20 in U.S.Ownership • Pittsburgh Penguins owner, investor and philanthropist Ron Burkle has controlling interest Stadium • Open-air privately-owned MLS stadium next to a 14-acre entertainment district in downtown SacramentoStrengths • Burkle's controlling stake, a large and rapidly growing area, and only the San Francisco Giants as pro sports competition nearby during the season.Weaknesses • Other ownership groups have more money than what Burkle reportedly has; the MLS already has a team less than 100 miles away in San Jose.

St. Louis














Architectural firm HOK's 2017 rendering of a proposed soccer stadium for the west side of downtown St. Louis.


HOK



Metropolitan Statistical Area • Bi-state St. Louis, 21st-largest in the U.S.2017 population estimate •  2.8 millionGrowth since 2010 • +20,000, or less than 1 percentTelevision market • No. 21 in U.S.Ownership • World Wide Technology chief executive Jim Kavanaugh and Enterprise Holdings’ Taylor family.Stadium • Open-air, privately-funded stadium proposed west of Union StationStrengths •  MLS likes the wealth and experience of the ownership group.Weakness • St. Louis isn’t growing as fast as some markets. And some owners may see new teams in Cincinnati and Nashville as fulfilling the league’s Midwest needs.


