JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson could announce his pick for Missouri’s next state treasurer as early as next week.With the clock ticking down to the holidays, an administration official told the Post-Dispatch Tuesday that the Republican governor is likely to act on the vacancy before the Christmas break.The screening process has been underway since mid-November, after Parson announced that Treasurer Eric Schmitt would replace Josh Hawley as attorney general when Hawley is sworn into the U.S. Senate in January.

In naming Schmitt attorney general, Parson said he felt comfortable about the fit because Schmitt had already been vetted by Missouri voters when he was elected treasurer in the 2016 election.Parson also showed an affinity for previous elected experience when he appointed former Senate Majority Floor Leader Mike Kehoe, R-Jefferson City, to Parson's old job as lieutenant governor, following the June 1 resignation of his scandal-plagued predecessor, Eric Greitens.If that same sentiment applies to the treasurer job, Parson is likely looking at someone who has held or is holding elected office. And, given that the current roster of state government leaders is comprised of white men, the governor may be looking at women and minority Republicans to fill the $107,746 per year position.Among those mentioned as possibilities are Republican state Reps. Holly Rehder of Sikeston, Scott Fitzpatrick of Shell Knob, Jean Evans of Manchester and Shamed Dogan of Ballwin, the lone black member of the GOP caucus.
Rehder told The Associated Press last week that she had let Parson's office know she's interested in the job.Rehder, a member of the House since 2012, has led the push to create a statewide prescription drug monitoring program as a way to fight the opioid epidemic. She made an unsuccessful bid for House Speaker earlier this year.Fitzpatrick, a business owner, is chairman of the House Budget Committee, which is one of the most powerful positions in the General Assembly. He has been in the House since 2012.
Dogan told the Post-Dispatch earlier he had been in contact with the governor’s office about the opening.Elected in 2014, Dogan is a former Ballwin alderman who once worked for the National Republican Senatorial Committee and for former U.S. Sen. Jim Talent of Missouri. He chairs the House committee on local government.Evans is a real estate agent who was elected in 2016. During the 2018 legislative session, Evans emerged as the sponsor of legislation that put a question on the ballot to raise the state’s gas tax. Despite vocal support from Parson, voters rejected the referendum.On the Senate side, Sandy Crawford, a Republican from Buffalo who replaced Parson in the Senate in 2017 is a former member of the House and a former banker.


