JEFFERSON CITY • Outgoing Attorney General Josh Hawley, during a conference room meeting on Thursday with his senior staff, heaped praise on his deputies and asked them to detail office accomplishments to incoming Attorney General Eric Schmitt.Schmitt, who like Hawley is a Republican, will take over the roughly 300-person office on Jan. 3 when Hawley is sworn in as a U.S. senator.Though the two officials, and their staffs, exhibited relaxed moods during the open press portion of the meeting, former staffers have described heavy turnover, low morale and tumultuous management during Hawley’s tenure.

Soon after the meeting, the office of Secretary of State Jay Ashcroft, also a Republican, announced it would investigate whether Hawley improperly used taxpayer resources for political purposes.Schmitt, careful not to criticize Hawley, has signaled that he intends to make subtle changes in the way he will run the office. But first, he said in an interview, he wants to ensure continuity .“We want to talk to people, we want to do an evaluation, but by and large a lot of those folks are going to be staying,” Schmitt said of attorney general’s office staffers.“And that’s a positive thing. That’s the kind of continuity I think Missourians should expect.”















            How Josh Hawley shook up the Missouri attorney general's office — and what happened next

Critics say Hawley's administration bled staffers and dedicated limited resources to firing salvos toward the federal government. Hawley said a reorganization was long overdue.




When asked what he would do differently than Hawley, Schmitt said he would emphasize crime prevention and collaboration with local prosecutors. He named three county prosecutors to his transition team, including St. Charles County Prosecutor Timothy Lohmar, a Republican.“One of the things I think is important as the chief law enforcement officer is as it relates to crime, people deserve to feel safe,” Schmitt said. “Their neighborhoods should be safe, and that’s certainly going to be a focus of mine.”Lohmar said it would be difficult for Schmitt to launch some kind of crackdown on crime. The attorney general’s office lacks original jurisdiction in criminal matters.“We bristle when we hear the attorney general, or candidates for attorney general, refer to themselves as the chief law enforcement officer of the state, because they’re absolutely not,” Lohmar said.“They don’t have any authority over us or what we do.”But Lohmar said he expects Schmitt to devote greater resources than Hawley to helping local prosecutors.
“They’ve always been a great resource,” Lohmar said. “I anticipate Eric is going to bolster those efforts.”Lohmar also said he expects more commitment to state issues. Hawley, in his two years as attorney general, devoted unprecedented resources to challenging the federal government. The cases, prepared by a new “Federalism Unit,” raised his profile as he was running for U.S. Senate.Lohmar called the unit “(totally) bogus” and a mechanism for “pandering.”“I think the AG’s focus has always been and should always be on the domestic issues and not so much battling the federal government,” Lohmar said. “I think Eric is in tune with that.”
Schmitt did say he believed addressing federal government overreach is important. He also suggested he would use his platform to push to address perceived injustices within the state’s criminal justice system.In the state Senate, where he served from 2009 to 2017, Schmitt sponsored legislation after the 2014 Ferguson protests aimed at stopping St. Louis County police departments from aggressively issuing traffic tickets to raise revenue. Schmitt called the practice “taxation by citation.”“I believe at the core of my soul that people ought to be treated as individuals, and they ought to be treated fairly under the law, and not as just some revenue-generating mechanism by these cities,” Schmitt said.The Post-Dispatch reported last week that Schmitt’s chief of staff in the treasurer’s office, Andrew Dziedzic, had at one point downloaded the text-message deleting app Confide on his smartphone.The app’s use plagued former Gov. Eric Greitens’ administration, leading to accusations he and his staffers destroyed public records in violation of the law.“We don’t use those apps to communicate,” Schmitt said. “We never have, never will. I don’t use them — never have, never will.”Hawley, in response to a question from a reporter, said he was not aware that his former chief of staff, Evan Rosell, had used Confide when he was working in the attorney general’s office. The Kansas City Star reported last week that Rosell had used the app.Schmitt, in an interview, demurred when asked whether he would investigate A New Missouri, a nonprofit group allied with Greitens. Elad Gross, a St. Louis lawyer who has announced his candidacy for attorney general as a Democrat, has urged the attorney general to investigate under the authority of the state’s consumer fraud statutes.Schmitt said it was too early to comment, and did not even commit in an interview to seeking the office in 2020.“I am focused right now on the transition and the swearing-in and again, having that office be the best law firm in the state,” Schmitt said.


