JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson is launching a tour of the state Tuesday designed to address myriad problems in Missouri’s health care system, including painkiller abuse, rural hospital closings and health insurance costs.Entering his sixth month as Missouri’s chief executive, the Republican’s four-day trek includes stops in St. Louis, Kansas City and his hometown of Bolivar, where he will hold a rural health summit aimed at addressing the future of small-town hospitals.













Gov. Mike Parson gives a brief speech after he was sworn into office as the 57th Governor of Missouri at the Capitol building in Jefferson City on Friday, June 1, 2018. Photo by David Carson, dcarson@post-dispatch.com


David Carson




“We need to be innovative in our approach to strengthen, improve, and support our rural hospitals,” said Dr. Randall Williams, director of the Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services.The focus on health care comes amid calls for Missouri to expand Medicaid. If supporters can collect enough signatures, voters could be asked to support such a move when they go to the polls in 2020.Studies have shown that states like Missouri that did not expand Medicaid under the Affordable Care Act have seen more struggles in rural hospitals. Despite that, Parson is not advocating for an expansion.Rather, administration officials, including Williams and the state’s new Medicaid director, former House Speaker Todd Richardson, are looking at a series of programs to shore up health care in rural areas.Among the ideas is a pilot program with the University of Missouri designed to lure more doctors to practice in smaller communities.Richardson, a Poplar Bluff Republican who took over the $10 billion-per-year MO HealthNet program in October, is focusing on reducing fraud and abuse within the program as a way to rein in costs.The state is in the midst of a $2.7 million contract with McKinsey & Co. to review fraud within the system, which serves nearly 1 million Missourians.In 2013, a private contractor identified more than 220,000 people it said should be dropped from Illinois’ Medicaid program, which is nearly three times larger than Missouri’s.Initial results of the work in Missouri could be released in January.
The tour also will include a stop in St. Joseph to discuss a mental health initiative that would boost treatment services through a telemedicine program.













Mayor Lyda Krewson, Kansas City Mayor Sly James and Missouri Gov. Mike Parson embark on a tour of St. Louis starting at Nathaniel Rivers Place Apartments. They will be looking for ways in which the state and city can work together to improve economic conditions. Photo by Laurie Skrivan, lskrivan@post-dispatch.com


In St. Louis on Wednesday, Parson will meet with Mayor Lyda Krewson and law enforcement officials to discuss the state’s opioid crisis.Frustrated by the inability of lawmakers to approve a statewide drug monitoring program, counties in Missouri have banded together to launch their own programs.
But with the retirement of Sen. Rob Schaaf, R-St. Joseph, who had blocked the creation of a statewide prescription database, lawmakers and Parson are on track to make Missouri the last state to implement such a program when they begin their annual legislative session in January.Along with putting a monitoring program on the books, Parson wants to focus on treatment options for drug users, as well as drug treatment courts, to address an epidemic that is causing more than 1,000 overdose deaths a year.















            Solutions hard to find as opioid epidemic keeps hitting St. Louis hard



At the event, Parson and Krewson “will discuss the importance of state and local partnerships in tackling the challenges in curbing the opioid crisis.”While in the St. Louis area, Parson also will visit the once-troubled St. Louis Veterans Home. During his tenure as lieutenant governor, Parson raised red flags about substandard care at the state-run facility in Bellefontaine Neighbors.Since then, the facility has undergone renovations, as well as a change in leadership.Later Wednesday the governor plans to host a roundtable discussion on health insurance costs for small business owners, highlighting a program that allows employers to band together in insurance pools to lower premium costs.Thursday includes stops in Kansas City and Warrensburg, followed by an event Friday in Jefferson City.


