JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson’s administration has not decided whether thousands of Missouri welfare recipients will lose their benefits if they use medical marijuana.The Department of Social Services, which administers the Temporary Assistance for Needy Families program, or TANF, said the question remains under review.“The Department of Social Services is currently studying the issue and will make a decision on how to proceed at the appropriate time,” spokeswoman Rebecca Woelfel told the Post-Dispatch in response to questions this week.

The agency is not alone in facing a wide array of questions about how to implement a medical marijuana initiative approved by more than 65 percent of voters on Nov. 6.Officials, for example, also have not made decisions on whether to bar medical marijuana users from certain state jobs.Amendment 2 legalizes the cultivation of cannabis, as well as the production of marijuana and marijuana infused products to aid patients suffering from 10 debilitating illnesses, including Parkinson’s, post-traumatic stress disorder, chronic pain, epilepsy, glaucoma and cancer.But, under a 2011 law signed by former Gov. Jay Nixon, the state developed a program to screen TANF applicants for drug use.Under the TANF program, which provides cash benefits to an average of about 25,000 recipients each month, the state requires officials to ask applicants about illegal drug use.Recipients may be then required to take a drug test. If they do not show up for the appointment or do not complete the drug test, they will not receive benefits for themselves for three years.Woelfel did not address the department’s process for adjusting to the new law or how long the review would take.The Department of Corrections had a similar response to questions about rules on medical marijuana use by correctional officers.
“The department has been discussing this issue, of course, but we haven’t proposed any policy changes,” agency spokeswoman Karen Pojmann.Under the new law, consumption of marijuana is prohibited in jails and correctional facilities. Users also are not permitted to operate motor vehicles, boats or aircraft while under the influence.Gary Gross, executive director of the Missouri Correctional Officers Association, said it remains unknown whether someone who has a medical marijuana card would be barred from working at the agency.
“There is just absolutely nothing set in stone,” Gross said.Gross said he doubts whether the union will be able to bargain for the right of officers to use medical marijuana for therapeutic reasons.In Colorado, where recreational marijuana is legal, marijuana use by prospective correctional officers is prohibited.“A pre-employment drug test will be administered at any part of the selection process, and applicants who test positive for any controlled substances, including marijuana, will be disqualified from consideration,” the Colorado prison hiring website notes.In Illinois, a patient seeking a medical marijuana card cannot be an active duty law enforcement officer, correctional officer, correctional probation officer or firefighter, nor can they hold a school bus permit or commercial drivers license.The agency that oversees personnel rules for Missouri’s state government workforce also has not weighed in on how medical marijuana will be viewed during the hiring and employment process.“The Office of Administration is looking into this topic and has not made a determination about policy,” said spokeswoman Brittany Ruess.


