JEFFERSON CITY • Former Gov. Eric Greitens’ top campaign consultant is hoping to become the next chief of the Republican Governors Association.Austin Chambers, who steered the political newcomer into the governor’s office in the 2016 election, told the Post-Dispatch he had thrown his name into the mix to take over for RGA Executive Director Paul Bennecke.“They have an open application process where anyone interested who meets the criteria can apply. I have applied,” Chambers said in a text message.

Chambers, 23, is coming off of a narrow victory as a top campaign aide to Georgia Gov.-elect Brian Kemp, who beat former state Senate Minority Leader Stacey Abrams in a nationally watched race.If Chambers gets the new post, he would continue a tradition of Georgians leading the RGA.Vice President Mike Pence’s chief of staff, Nick Ayers, formerly served as the executive director, along with Bennecke. Ayers also worked on Greitens’ campaign.All are close allies.In addition, the RGA’s chief legal counsel, Michael Adams, serves as an attorney for the controversial nonprofit Chambers established to promote Greitens’ agenda.The organization, known as A New Missouri, accepts dark money contributions and is based in the same office building as Greitens’ former campaign operation.
For Chambers, the new post would take him out of the hands-on campaign work he’s done since he was a teenager.In 2013, Bennecke recruited Chambers to serve as the political director for the Senate campaign of Georgia Republican David Perdue, who won the seat in 2014.Chambers joined forces with Greitens in 2015 at age 20.
In managing Greitens’ bid for governor, Chambers oversaw a campaign in which Greitens cast himself as an outsider in both the primary and the general election.The narrative, fueled by $13 million in contributions from the RGA, worked well in a year when Missouri voters gave Donald Trump a 19-point victory over Hillary Clinton.Despite not winning endorsements from key GOP-leaning groups such as the National Rifle Association and the Missouri Farm Bureau, Greitens beat Democrat Attorney General Chris Koster by a six-point margin, 51 percent to 45 percent.After holding 33 governorships coming out of the 2016 election, the RGA had a challenging election cycle in 2018, losing six seats.It was not immediately clear when the RGA would hire the new director.“The interview process with the panel of governors hasn’t begun yet,” Chambers said.


