For 30 members of the St. Louis Fire Department and one city resident, Tuesday was the time for Missouri Gov. Mike Parson to salute their lifesaving efforts.At a ceremony Tuesday at Harris-Stowe State University, Parson awarded a Medal of Valor to St. Louis Fire Capt. Leon Whitener III and a Civilian Partnership Award to Raymond Rayford for their heroics in April 2017.Whitener was driving home after work on April 22 when he heard a scanner call for a fire that had trapped a person in a building in the 4100 block of McRee Avenue, according to the fire department.

Being close, Whitener drove to the scene and immediately ran into the burning building. Rayford, who had been outside the building with a growing crowd, ran in behind Whitener.The pair found a woman who uses a wheelchair trapped inside and then carried her to safety.
The other 29 members of the St. Louis Fire Department honored Tuesday were lauded for their work on Jan. 24, 2017, when they rescued people from a fire in the 4600 block of Evans Avenue that left 11 injured.
On arrival, firefighters saw heavy smoke pouring from the building. Firefighters forced their way in and found eight people in a back bedroom. They carried the children out, and helped guide the adults down the stairs.At the time, Fire Chief Dennis Jenkerson said the quick first response, in less than four minutes, saved lives. "A minute longer and we'd be having a totally different conversation — and it wouldn't have been a good conversation," he said.Honored for their actions related to Evans were: Battalion Chief Gary Steffens; Capts. Larry Conley, Michael Hostetler, Bryan Radley and Joe Waring; Privates Louis Bollasina, Paul Clark, Marquis Hayes, Joe Johnson, Tim Mahnken, Patrick O'Brien, Patrick Pollihan, James Reynolds, Dave Ray, Jeff Ronshausen, Dale Schultz, Tim Schultz, Galen Taylor, John Vallero, paramedic supervisor Colin McCoy; paramedics Daniel Goldfeld; Dustin Lammert; Cameron Morton and James Wilson; EMTs Andrew Beasley; Antuan Knox; Nicholas Spiess and Norman Walker; and dispatcher Angela Williams. 


