JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri Auditor Nicole Galloway, the last Democratic statewide officeholder in Jefferson City, continued to dominate her Republican opponent in the cash race through October, according to reports filed with the Missouri Ethics Commission on Monday.Galloway spent more than $1 million in October and raised another $210,000 for her campaign coffers. Galloway entered the final stage of the race before the election next Tuesday with $546,000 on hand.Republican Saundra McDowell, who broke through a four-way GOP primary in August, again posted anemic fundraising figures. She raised $41,000 in October and spent $43,000, ending the period with $24,000 on hand.

Besides fundraising problems, McDowell's campaign has been dogged by scrutiny surrounding her family's finances — and whether she is even eligible to be on the ballot given her apparently brief time in Missouri.All three medical marijuana campaigns showed a pulse heading into the final week.That said, the only donations Missourians for Patient Care — a shadowy group backing Proposition C — recorded in October were two in-kind donations totaling $93,000.Missourians for Patient Care again declined to disclose its donors, even though the Missouri Ethics Commission has criticized the concept. The committee faces an ethics complaint alleging it is intentionally concealing donors in violation of the law.The only way the proposed statutory change will go into effect is if it passes and two other proposed constitutional amendments fail.New Approach Missouri, backing Amendment 2, received almost $192,000 in October and spent $132,259. The committee had $99,341 on hand going into the final week of the campaign.Find The Cures, which is backing Amendment 3, reported raising $344,000, $309,000 of that coming in the form of loans from Springfield physician and trial lawyer Dr. Brad Bradshaw.The campaign reported spending almost $300,000 during the reporting period, and had $89,000 on hand.Raise Up Missouri, which is backing Proposition B, an effort to raise the state's minimum wage to $12 per hour by 2023, spent an eye-popping $4 million in October, raised an additional $811,000, and entered the final stage of the campaign with nearly $600,000 on hand.
The Sixteen Thirty Fund, a liberal "dark money" group, donated $4.7 million of the roughly $6.6 million Raise Up Missouri has raised for its campaign.SaferMO, which is backing a gradual 10-cent increase to the state's fuel tax, Proposition D, raised almost $2.5 million in October and spent almost $888,000 during the reporting period. Construction groups and local governments appear to be heavily invested in the effort.Gov. Mike Parson and Lt. Gov. Mike Kehoe, both Republicans, are also backing the ballot initiative.Clean Missouri, which is sponsoring a suite of ethics changes contained in Amendment 1, spent $2.2 million and raised $1.1 million, leaving $341,000 on hand before election day.
Missourians First, leading the anti-Amendment 1 campaign, raised $201,500 in October. St. Louis financier Rex Sinquefield donated $200,000 of that.Missourians First had $144,000 going into election day after spending $57,000.The Democrats' Missouri House Victory Committee raised almost $136,000 in October and spent $220,000. The committee ended the fundraising period  with $113,000 on hand.According to the report, the Democratic committee was working to influence 18 races though direct financial assistance, indicating the party believes its best shots are in select metropolitan districts across the state.2018 Missouri House races
The party infused cash directly into St. Louis County's 70th, 94th, 95th, 96th 99th and 100th districts. It is also playing in St. Charles County's 65th District and Jefferson County's 97th and 113th districts.The committee also aided three Columbia-area campaigns, one Springfield campaign, and five western Missouri districts, including the St. Joseph-based 10th, and the Kansas City-area 14th, 30th, 31st and 35th districts.Of the 18 in the report, the 10th and 97th districts are the only districts that Democrats currently control.


