Four years after Missouri voters rejected a sales tax increase for road improvements, they’ll see on the Nov. 6 election ballot another route to that end — a proposed hike in the tax at the pump on gasoline and diesel fuel.State transportation officials and other supporters say the measure, Proposition D, is an essential first step toward meeting $825 million a year in unmet state road and bridge needs.“It takes constant investment to maintain that system and build for the future,” said Patrick McKenna, director of the Missouri Department of Transportation.

Under the proposition, put on the ballot by the Legislature, the current 17-cents-a-gallon state tax would increase 2.5 cents each year starting next July until it hits 27 cents in mid-2022.That, MoDOT says, would restore the tax’s purchasing power it had when it was last increased back in 1996. Now the tax, the 49th lowest among the 50 states, has the buying power of only 7 cents.















            Save time at the polls: Check our voters guide to today's election

Be in the know before you head to the polls.  




“The gas tax does not grow with the general growth of the economy the way income or sales tax does,” McKenna said.The keep-up-with-inflation message has been a centerpiece of some TV ads for Safermo.com, the gas tax campaign committee which has raised more than $4.3 million.Much of that has come from companies and unions that stand to benefit if road and bridge work increases.Leading the way have been the Laborers Union’s Eastern Missouri District Council based in Bridgeton, which has kicked in $1 million, and the Heavy Constructors Association of Greater Kansas City, which has contributed $650,000.No organized opposition effort has emerged. But some state lawmakers who opposed the plan in the Legislature complain that the ballot wording and the proposition are misleading.The measure assigns a projected $123 million a year from the tax hike when fully implemented directly to cities and counties for local road and bridge improvements and $288 million to the Missouri Highway Patrol.However, there is no mention of more gas tax money for MoDOT in the ballot listing or the proposition.But supporters say assigning all of the state share of the tax hike to the patrol would allow the Legislature to then redirect from the patrol to MoDOT a like amount in projected revenue from the current gas tax proceeds.How much more money, if any, the patrol would receive than it would otherwise get from revenue from the existing gas tax rate is hard to project, campaign officials say.That’s because the Legislature has been steadily increasing the patrol’s percentage share in recent years and could be expected to do so anyway even if Proposition D fails, campaign supporters say.But the proposition would stabilize the patrol’s future funding, they say.The critics say the ballot listing as passed by the Legislature overstates the benefit to the patrol because of polling showing strong public support for law enforcement.“I voted against it (in the House) because it’s an intentional shell game,” said Rep. Kurt Bahr, R-O’Fallon. He also says he doesn’t like tax increases in general.He added, however, that he doesn’t doubt that MoDOT would in the end get much of the extra revenue that campaign supporters say it would.Sen. Dave Schatz, R-Sullivan, who helped craft the language, acknowledged that supporters made sure the patrol is in the ballot listing because of polling results and proven voter support for raising taxes for police.But he said the wording is fair. He said also that legislators were limited by a law restricting the length of the ballot listing.
He noted that they also needed to include references to an unrelated bill that the gas tax measure was tacked onto in the final day of the legislative session.That bill — which is now also part of Proposition D — would exempt from state taxes prizes and medals won in the Olympics and similar events.While the Legislature would have the final say each year on the exact amounts from the gas tax going to MoDOT and the patrol, Schatz pointed out that the state Constitution doesn’t allow the state’s share of the gas tax to be used for any other purpose.Proposition D also includes a provision authorizing the Legislature to set up a fund in future years for major road projects aimed at alleviating truck traffic bottlenecks. But the measure doesn’t assign any money or revenue source for that.Unlike in some past tax hike campaigns to aid MoDOT, an itemized highway project list to be funded hasn’t been released.Instead, MoDOT officials have been holding public meetings with local officials around the state to get input on what types of improvements they want the most.“It’s very important that regional planning commissions and transportation advisory committees have the opportunity to weigh in on this,” McKenna said.Schatz added that not issuing an itemized list avoids any internal fighting among advocates for their favored priorities.
However, McKenna and others have pointed out some big-ticket items already in MoDOT’s plans likely would be accelerated if voters approve the tax hike.In the St. Louis area, for example, reconstruction of a big stretch of Interstate 270 in north St. Louis County and reconfiguration of overpasses, ramps and access roads, has been cited.With existing revenue, MoDOT has been able to commit over the next four years only $250 million of the estimated $700 million cost.McKenna said advancing the 270 project “is critical to the economic vitality of the region” and the entire state, partly because of its integral part of freight trucking operations. Doing the work in one unified project is the best way to accomplish that, he said.“We are hundreds of millions of dollars away from that reality right now,” he said.In addition to steering $288 million in new state money to MoDOT, supporters say the gas tax increase would potentially qualify the state to receive hundreds of millions more a year in federal aid should Congress expand its highway programs.The pro-gas tax effort has gotten campaign help from a bipartisan list of elected officials.That includes Republicans such as Gov. Mike Parson and Lt. Gov. Mike Kehoe and leading Democrats such as St. Louis County Executive Steve Stenger and St. Louis Mayor Lyda Krewson. The top elected officials in St. Charles, Jefferson and Franklin counties, all Republicans, also are on board.The campaign estimates that local governments in the St. Louis area would get an estimated $34 million more a year in gas tax money when the increase is fully implemented. St. Louis County and its municipalities get the biggest cut, about $16 million.Supporters have taken pains to call the gas tax plan a user fee, since individuals and companies using roads and bridges are the ones that would pay the tax hike.That removed a key argument made in 2014 by opponents of the proposed sales tax for roads that year — that it would have shifted the burden for highways from the trucking industry and others that use it to the general public.In addition to gas and diesel, this year’s proposition also would increase the tax on some other motor fuels such as compressed natural gas beginning in 2025.Moreover, the measure requires state agencies by 2023 to come up with a way to tax electric-powered vehicles “at substantially the equivalent rate” and to implement it by 2026. That provision also applies to alternative fuels.















            Save time at the polls: Check our voters guide to today's election

Be in the know before you head to the polls.  







