Five-year-old Taylor Duncan's goal this year has been to have ice cream with as many Missouri mayors as she can. On Thursday night at the Municipal League of Metro St. Louis meeting in Florissant, she boosted her tally wholesale.Taylor, who has also shared a frozen treat with Gov. Mike Parson in her half-year campaign, added 22 St. Louis County mayors, who partook in ice cream as part of their attendance. She toured the room, asking brief questions of each, and posed for a group picture.Before Thursday, Taylor had met with 118 mayors this year. Now she has a running total of 140, plus one governor.

"This will run through the end of the year," said her mother, Therese Duncan, who home schools Taylor. "That's mostly because my husband is military."He has been stationed at Fort Leonard Wood, about 10 miles from the family's home in Waynesville.The Duncan family has set up a gofundme account to help cover the gas for their trips around the state to continue Taylor's quest.In addition to eating ice cream on Thursday, league members approved by resolution their annual priority list, urging Missouri lawmakers to:
• Restore the right of municipal courts to impose penalties on those who fail to appear in court.
• Enforce the collection of internet sales tax, as allowed by a U.S. Supreme Court ruling.• Have a local expenditure database, provided that it applies to all governments and not just municipalities.• Work to establish a high-speed internet overlay district as has been done with local participation in the Columbia and Kansas City areas.• Create a statewide prescription drug-monitoring program.• Oppose statewide votes on strictly local issues.


