JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri school officials are set to launch interviews with four finalists seeking to be the state’s next education commissioner.In a meeting Tuesday, state Board of Education President Charlie Shields said the month-long application period drew five resumes and seven nominations before it closed last Friday.The board met behind closed doors Monday to review the 12 potential commissioners, winnowing them to four with an eye on conducting final interviews by Nov. 19.

“I think we’re excited about the opportunities that are before us. We intend to move forward with all due speed,” Shields told members gathered for a regular meeting of the board at the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education headquarters.The current salary for the post is $191,544, and candidates must have a doctorate to be considered.The board hopes the new commissioner can start in January.
Roger Dorson, interim commissioner, has led the department since December, when the board fired former Education Commissioner Margie Vandeven.The board became powerless in January when the Senate refused confirm former Gov. Eric Greitens' nominees to the panel. A search for Vandeven's replacement then ended because the panel could not form a quorum.
Greitens' replacement, Gov. Mike Parson, has re-stocked the board, allowing members to launch the search process again.Shields has praised Dorson for his leadership and said the board could opt to remove the "interim" tag from Dorson's title by the end of any selection process.On Tuesday, Shields did not announce the names of the four finalists. Among possible contenders is Rockwood School District Superintendent Eric Knost, who announced earlier this month he will retire after 31 years in public education at the end of this school year.During the scuttled search process in January, 10 people applied to replace Vandeven.


