JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri Gov. Mike Parson has chosen the outgoing speaker of the Missouri House to run one of the biggest programs in state government.Rep. Todd Richardson, 41, a Republican from Poplar Bluff, was named director of the state’s Medicaid operation Monday, marking the first time in nearly two years that the program has had a permanent director.Richardson, an attorney, replaces Joe Parks, who served as the director of the program, known formally as MO HealthNet, from 2013 to 2016.

Richardson’s salary will be $225,000, up from the $210,000 Parks was earning when he left. As speaker, Richardson was paid $38,400 per year.Parson and Department of Social Services Director Steve Corsi defended the high salary, which is more than the governor and other agency heads earn.“This is a $10 billion department in this state. It’s huge,” Corsi said.“This isn’t an easy role, and it comes with many challenges,” Parson said.MO HealthNet provides health insurance services to nearly 1 million residents at a total cost of nearly $10 billion, making up about one-third of the state budget.The federal government pays for a significant portion of the program, which provides prescription drugs, nursing home services and managed care to low-income seniors, children and disabled Missourians.Richardson, a member of the House since 2010, was elevated to the speaker’s post in 2015, following the forced resignation of John Diehl after Diehl had an inappropriate relationship with a college-age intern. Richardson is term-limited.Corsi acknowledged that the previous two permanent directors of MO HealthNet were physicians, but said Parson had taken a “bold step” by choosing Richardson.
As director of MO HealthNet, Richardson will oversee one of the fastest growing programs in state government.In the state’s most recent budget, lawmakers approved an additional $700 million of spending, primarily to fund higher-than-expected health care costs.Total Medicaid spending in Missouri grew by 6.2 percent last year, with managed care premiums and mental health services driving most of the increase.
During his last session as speaker, which ended in May, the GOP-controlled House expanded MO HealthNet benefits for pregnant women to provide substance abuse treatment for up to year after giving birth.But the Republican-controlled Legislature has repeatedly rejected requests to expand Medicaid eligibility to more recipients as part of the Affordable Care Act. Missouri is among 14 states that haven’t done that, which has limited the state’s ability to provide coverage to low-income adults without children.That has created a coverage gap among the working poor, who earn too much to qualify for Medicaid coverage but too little to afford subsidized coverage under Obamacare.It also has hurt rural hospitals that take care of a large number of uninsured patients.Although the federal government would pick up a majority of the funding for the expansion, state lawmakers have declined, citing concern about long-term funding.Richardson and Parson signaled the GOP position on expansion is unlikely to change.“My focus is not going to be on expanding Medicaid eligibility,” Richardson said.Richardson was already set to be replaced as speaker in January by Rep. Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield.


