JEFFERSON CITY • Linda Hickam is resigning her post as state veterinarian, a Missouri Department of Agriculture spokeswoman told the Post-Dispatch on Monday.Hickam, who oversees the state's animal welfare laws and health programs, submitted her resignation last week. It is effective Oct. 31, said Sami Jo Freeman, spokeswoman for the department. Hickam held the post since September 2011."We accepted her resignation," Freeman said. Freeman said she wasn't aware of any "force out" by department leaders. "We know that she was was a great state vet and did many things for the department of ag."

Hickam said in a statement the agency "has accepted by resignation, effective Wednesday, Oct. 31, to enable me to pursue other career opportunities that will contribute back to Missouri agriculture."She said the animal health team made "great strides" in improving the state's "animal health laboratory equipment, testing capabilities and ability to respond quickly during a disease incident. We have also worked hard to implement animal health and care programs in a way that improves and protects the health and well-being of Missouri’s livestock."She added a new program "will enable producers to market meat and poultry interstate from State Inspected Plants.
"The future of Missouri agriculture is bright, especially with a Governor and Director of Agriculture who are both farmers themselves," Hickam said. "I wish the team at the Department of Agriculture well in all of their future endeavors."Hickam, a Columbia, Mo., native and graduate of the University of Missouri College of Veterinary Medicine, joined the department in 2007.
In 2011, Missouri lawmakers approved the Canine Cruelty Prevention Act, which Hickam helped enforce. The law increased standards for kennel owners and led to many breeders leaving the business.The Post-Dispatch reported in August that the Department of Agriculture had dramatically reduced referrals of bad breeders to the attorney general's office in recent years. The attorney general's office has since sued one kennel owner in Phelps County; the agriculture department referred a second breeder, in Douglas County, to the attorney general's office in September.Dr. Taylor Woods, who preceded Hickam, will take over on an interim basis, Freeman said, "to just kind of provide a steady hand" while the department, under Gov. Mike Parson's administration, searches for a new state vet.


