BERKELEY • Gov. Mike Parson and a bipartisan group of St. Louis area governmental leaders came together Tuesday to push for passage of Proposition D, the proposed state gasoline tax increase on the Nov. 6 ballot.“It’s probably not the most politically popular thing to do,” Parson, a Republican, said of the idea of endorsing a tax hike. “But at some point you have to take a real reality look at where we are in the state of Missouri and how are we going to move forward.”Parson spoke at a news conference at the Renaissance Airport St. Louis Hotel about the measure, which would phase in a 10-cent-a-gallon increase over four years.

The event kicked off a weeklong statewide tour by the governor on the proposed boost in the fuel tax, which funds state and local road and bridge projects and the Missouri Highway Patrol.Also endorsing the measure were St. Louis Mayor Lyda Krewson and St. Louis County Executive Steve Stenger, both Democrats, and the top elected leaders of St. Charles, Jefferson and Franklin counties, all Republicans.Earlier, Parson talked up Prop D before about 300 people at a Missouri Chamber of Commerce and Industry conference, also at the hotel. He pointed out that the current 17-cent gas tax hasn’t been increased since 1996 and now has the buying power of just 7 cents.He said passage is a key to updating the state’s infrastructure. That’s one of his main priorities, along with workforce development — the subject of the chamber conference. At the news conference, Krewson said: “It’s not often that all of us are together on one issue.”Stenger said: “Unless we make long-overdue investments in our roads and bridges,” the county will lose economic development momentum he says it has picked up in recent years.
Among the projects likely to be funded by the state’s share of the extra money, Stenger said, is reconstruction of Interstate 270 and its overpasses. He said that’s the Missouri Department of Transportation’s top priority in St. Louis County.Scott Charton, a spokesman for the Safermo.com committee funding the gas tax campaign, said local governments in the St. Louis region would get about $34 million more a year once the increase is fully phased in.
That includes more than $16 million for the county and its municipalities and $6 million for St. Louis.St. Charles County Executive Steve Ehlmann called the measure “a user fee” because it would hit only those people who use the roads. “If you don’t drive, if you’re not on the highways, you don’t pay,” he said. “The more you drive, the more you pay.”No formal opposition group has emerged to argue against the tax hike, but supporters have raised more than $2.5 million so far for their pro-Prop D campaign.Under the measure, the tax on gas and diesel would go up 2.5 cents each year starting next year, topping out at 27 cents in 2022. The measure also would increase taxes on alternative fuels such as natural gas and propane.Analysts say the tax hike would generate at least $123 million more a year for local road work and at least $288 million more for state road work. The proposition would earmark $288 million to the state patrol, allowing the Legislature to redirect from the patrol a like amount in revenue from the current gas tax.Transportation officials say the added money will help the state begin catching up on $825 million in unfunded road and bridge needs.


