JEFFERSON CITY • Armed with a robust campaign fund and no known organized opposition, supporters of raising Missouri's gasoline tax launched a 30-second television ad Thursday designed to fuel support for the 10-cent hike.The ad by SaferMo.com focuses on how the added cash will be used to make the Show-Me State's roads safer.

"Proposition D is a bargain to keep my family, and yours, safer," the narrator says.The ad comes as Republican Gov. Mike Parson is set to campaign for the increase next week in a series of stops throughout the state. He is tentatively scheduled to be in St. Louis on Tuesday to highlight the need for more spending on roads and bridges.Lt. Gov. Mike Kehoe, also a Republican, has been traversing the state to promote the hike for the past several weeks.
If voters approve, a 10-cent increase in Missouri's 17-cents-per-gallon motor fuel tax would be phased in over the next four years.The tax on gas and diesel would go up 2.5 cents each year starting next year, topping out at 27 cents in 2022.  The measure also would increase taxes on alternative fuels such as natural gas and propane.
Analysts say the tax hike could generate $293 million more for the state road fund when fully implemented.Transportation officials say the added money will help the state begin catching up on $825 million in unfunded road and bridge needs. The gas tax, among the lowest in the nation, has not been raised since 1996.Among projects that could be in line for funding are a revamping of traffic-choked Interstate 270 in north St. Louis County.SaferMo.com has received dozens of large political contributions since it was formed after the Legislature placed the question on the Nov. 6 ballot.Contributions of $100,000 apiece have come from the Site Advancement Foundation, the St. Louis Construction Training and Advancement Foundation and the Missouri Construction Industry Advancement Fund in Jefferson City.The biggest single donation so far has been $250,000 from the Missouri Realtors Association. Engineering firms that could see an uptick in business also have contributed.Loading...
