JEFFERSON CITY • A Virginia-based law firm is suing Missouri Gov. Mike Parson over an executive order banning employees in the governor’s office from accepting gifts from lobbyists.In a lawsuit filed in federal court last week, the Institute for Justice said the ban on gift-giving violates the organization’s First Amendment rights to free speech because it prohibits them from giving workers in Parson’s office two books.“IJ cannot freely distribute its publications to communicate with state employees of the executive branch because those employees must reject the publications, purchase the publications, or be subject to disciplinary action, up to termination of employment, for knowingly accepting IJ’s publications from lobbyists,” the complaint states.

For years, state lawmakers have been unable to agree on regulations that could end or put limits on freebies handed out by lobbyists.In 2017, in one of his first acts, former Gov. Eric Greitens issued Executive Order 17-02 barring gifts to his employees. After Parson took over in June, he kept the order in place, despite previously being the lone statewide officer who accepted gifts.
His spokeswoman signaled Tuesday the governor isn’t planning to change the policy.
“The Governor’s Office does not comment on pending litigation, but pursuant to Executive Order 17-02, the governor and his staff will not accept lobbyist gifts,” Kelli Jones said.The institute advocates for libertarian causes, including school choice, civil forfeiture reform and loosening regulations on hair braiders.The suit comes as Missouri voters will get a chance to vote on a referendum Nov. 6 that would bar lawmakers from accepting gifts worth more than $5.Supporters of the change said lobbyists distributed more than $1 million worth of gifts in 2017, the highest reported total since 2006.


