JEFFERSON CITY • A Warrensburg Republican who finished a distant second in his bid to take on Democratic U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill is now considering a run for governor.Paperwork filed with the Missouri Ethics Commission shows Tony Monetti formed an exploratory committee to run in the August 2020 gubernatorial race.Monetti has not filed a financial report showing whether he has raised  money for the run.

Gov. Mike Parson, who took over as Missouri’s chief executive in June following the departure of scandal-plagued Gov. Eric Greitens, has not said he is seeking election to a full term.In a September interview on his farm in Bolivar, Parson told the Post-Dispatch he would be happy if he successfully serves out the remainder of his current term.But, he didn’t rule out seeking another four years at the helm of state government.“I’ve got at least two-and-a-half years to get some things done. Whenever it’s over, I’m going to sit out here and look at cows,” Parson said.In the GOP primary for U.S. Senate, Monetti received 9.75 percent of the vote in an 11-way race won easily by Attorney General Josh Hawley.
Monetti is a graduate of the U.S. Air Force Academy and served in the Air Force, where he flew the B-2 stealth bomber.Monetti also was an assistant dean of aviation at the University of Central Missouri. He resigned from that job to make his run for the Senate.
The political newcomer raised nearly $450,000 during the race, Federal Elections Commission records show.Although vastly outspent by Hawley, Monetti did wrangle a high profile endorsement when former vice presidential nominee and Alaska Gov. Sarah Palin campaigned for him during an appearance in Kansas City.Monetti did not immediately respond to a request for comment Monday.Others who are listed in Missouri Ethics Commission records as running for governor in 2020 include Greitens and Republican state Rep. T.J. Berry of Kearney.Berry said Monday he is not seriously considering a run for governor.












