JEFFERSON CITY • Advocates for survivors of Catholic clergy sex abuse gathered outside the state Capitol on Wednesday urging Gov. Mike Parson to give Attorney General Josh Hawley subpoena power in his ongoing investigation of possible sex crimes within the Catholic Church.The attorney general's office told the Post-Dispatch last week that it can gain special prosecutor status — and thus, subpoena power — with the help of either the governor or a local prosecutor who requests aid.“Yes, there are procedures through which a local prosecutor and/or the governor can initiate a process that would result in our office being appointed special prosecutor,” Daniel Hartman, Hawley's chief of staff, said in a statement. “However, our office has no legal authority to initiate those procedures and thus it would require action by a local prosecutor or the governor on their own initiative.”

But on Wednesday afternoon, Parson's office cast doubt on his ability to name Hawley special prosecutor, saying the governor first needed a request from a local prosecutor seeking assistance."Until then, our office lacks the Constitutional and statutory authority to compel any further actions," Kelli Jones, Parson's spokeswoman, said in a statement. "The Governor fully supports the Attorney General's independent review on this extremely important matter."State law says: "When directed by the governor, the attorney general, or one of his assistants, shall aid any prosecuting or circuit attorney in the discharge of their respective duties in the trial courts and in examinations before grand juries, and when so directed by the trial court, he may sign indictments in lieu of the prosecuting attorney."Hawley announced an investigation into the state’s dioceses last month. The announcement followed the release of a Pennsylvania grand jury report that uncovered widespread abuse of more than 1,000 children by more than 300 priests over a period of 70 years.
But Hawley has said he lacks criminal jurisdiction, and is relying on the state's four dioceses to cooperate voluntarily with his investigation. The St. Louis-based Survivors Network of those Abused by Priests, or SNAP, also delivered a letter to Parson's office on Wednesday. The administration had no immediate comment.
Tim Lennon, president of SNAP, has gone so far as to call Hawley's investigation of possible abuse a "sham" because he does not have the subpoena power to compel testimony and the production of documents.Hawley's office said that it is searching of a mechanism in state law that would allow it to subpoena the church, if the office decided that was the right course.At the moment, any action Hawley takes is amplified by his ongoing bid to unseat U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., this November. Advocates have urged Hawley to avoid politicizing the probe in the heat of campaign season.Hawley's office has cautioned that its probe will take time because of the volume of records attorneys must examine. Officials said last week they had identified at least 100 boxes of records that can each hold about 2,000 documents across the state's four dioceses.SNAP also wants Hawley to expand his investigation to include priests that have "quietly" been sent to Missouri to live at church facilities after allegations of child molestation surfaced.


