JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson on Monday named two men to the Missouri Housing Development Commission, which oversees controversial low-income development tax credits.Allies of former Gov. Eric Greitens, a Republican, stopped the state's participation in the program last December, keeping Missouri from matching some $140 million in federal low-income housing tax credits.Parson, also a Republican, was a backer of the credits and opposed Greitens' move, which sent waves through the state's development community. Greitens resigned in June, and Parson was elevated to the state's top job.

The program has long been criticized for inefficiencies, but Parson has praised the credits' role in spurring development in poor areas.
Parson named Mark Elliff, of Carthage, and Rick McDowell, of Parkville, to the commission on Monday. Elliff is the president, CEO and director of Economic Development at Carthage Chamber of Commerce, according to a news release. McDowell is president and CEO of Lee’s Summit Economic Development Council.Parson, in a statement, repeated his promise that the state would not again issue tax credits until the program is reformed.
“We are confident in the legislature’s ability to develop tax credit reforms that address housing needs, while ensuring greater accountability and an increased return on the investment of taxpayer dollars,” Parson said. “As a member of the Commission, I am committed to considering current federal tax credit applications, but until substantial reforms are enacted, state tax credits will not be issued.” Parson was able to make the appointments after the state Senate rejected three of Greitens' nominees to the panel earlier this year.


