All 10 cases of West Nile virus diagnosed this year in Missouri have been in the St. Louis area, including one death.That geographic detail is no longer available on the Missouri health department website, where cases of the mosquito-borne virus were provided by county from 2002 to 2017 but are now the state’s latest example of withholding information by citing privacy concerns.The department will decide what information to release on a case-by-case basis, according to state health officials.

Department spokeswoman Megan Hopkins confirmed U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention data showing that all West Nile virus cases in 2018 have been in St. Louis County or St. Louis. A records request from the state for county-level West Nile virus data is pending.A hypothetical case of West Nile virus in Worth County, population 2,200, might not be revealed because of federal privacy laws, said department director Dr. Randall Williams, who was appointed to the position in 2017 by former Gov. Eric Greitens.“We think that we have to approach each case, each decision about releasing data on its own merits,” Williams said. “To the degree that we can without violating HIPAA (federal privacy law), we will report West Nile virus by county.”According to the Missouri health department’s HIPAA brochure, communicable disease information “can be released only in aggregate form that prevents the identification of a patient or physician.”Missouri reports other communicable diseases by county, including HIV, tuberculosis and lead poisoning. For example, there is one person living with HIV in Worth County, according to the state.It is important for people to know which communicable diseases are circulating in their area to try to prevent infection. The need is especially great in smaller counties such as Worth that don’t have health departments or prevention efforts such as mosquito surveillance and spraying, public health experts said.
The CDC reports West Nile cases by county except for Maryland, South Carolina and Virginia, which provide that information on state websites. At least 34 other states where the disease circulates, including Kansas and Illinois, also provide county-by-county counts of the disease on their websites.Montana reports three cases of West Nile virus in McCone County, population 1,700. In North Dakota’s LaMoure County, there are two cases in a population of 4,100.In Delaware, the health department has released information in the last month about West Nile virus cases in a 73-year-old New Castle County man, a 60-year-old Sussex County man and a 68-year-old New Castle County man, a whooping cough outbreak in 97 people in an Amish community in Kent County, the death from rabies of a Kent County woman and flu illnesses in a 50-year-old woman from Sussex County and a 70-year-old woman from New Castle County.
“The more local you can make it, the more likely people are to pay attention,” said Andrea Wojcik, the state health department’s chief of community relations. “It’s a tricky balance sometimes to provide people with prevention tips (while) respecting that personal privacy requirement.”Wojcik said she could not imagine a scenario where Delaware would not release the county numbers for any reportable infectious disease, including Ebola or anthrax.Williams’ secrecy with Missouri health data has previously stirred up concerns in the state Legislature. Earlier this year, the Legislature cut eight positions in Williams’ office after he refused to release information about testing for the tick-borne Bourbon virus in Meramec State Park, where a state worker caught the disease and died in 2017.Former state Rep. Justin Alferman, who now works in Gov. Mike Parson’s administration, previously said Williams used a “weird interpretation of HIPAA” to deny the release of aggregate test results.St. Louis County last month sent a news release announcing the county’s first West Nile virus case of the season. County health director Faisal Khan, who is departing the job, said it is not unheard of for a state to hold back the same information but in Missouri’s case he “(hasn’t) seen an adequate explanation for the rationale behind it.”


