JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri lawmakers returned to the Capitol on Tuesday to consider legislation dealing with drug treatment courts and education in science, technology and math.The Missouri House Judiciary Committee on Tuesday unanimously advanced legislation that would bolster Missouri’s drug treatment courts. The House Workforce Development Committee approved legislation allowing computer science courses to count toward math, science or practical art credits needed for high school graduation.The moves came after Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, vetoed two bills addressing the topics over the summer. Rather than override the new governor, lawmakers are attempting to rework the proposals after Parson called for a special session last month.

The legislation dealing with drug treatment courts, House Bill 2, would place all of the state’s treatment courts under one regulatory umbrella. It also adds two more members — one representing prosecutors and one representing the criminal defense bar — to the state commission that oversees drug courts. The term “drug courts” would be replaced with “treatment courts” in state statute.Under the bill, the state commission would be authorized to establish best practice standards for the state’s treatment courts. The legislation would make it easier to authorize venue changes for offenders.Jackson County launched the first so-called treatment court in Missouri in 1993, according to the state Drug Courts Coordinating Commission. The commission says that Missouri has more treatment courts per capita than any state in the nation.According to the commission, the courts have diverted drug users from incarceration. Participants have lower recidivism rates compared to offenders who are put on probation or who enter prison. The courts have also reduced “crime and the need for foster care,” according to the commission.Treatment court participants gave birth to 925 babies between 1993 and 2017; 846 of those babies were born “drug-free,” according to the commission. More recent state figures put the number of drug-free babies born at 871.According to the commission, the state has saved “millions of dollars in lifetime costs in care for children” because of the proliferation of drug courts in Missouri.
At the end of last year, there were 147 treatment court programs in Missouri, including various adult treatment courts, juvenile treatment courts, family treatment courts, DWI treatment courts and veterans courts.The House was also moving to fix on Tuesday legislation that attempts to boost the number of students pursuing careers in computer science.Under legislation approved unanimously by the House Workforce Development Committee, the Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education will establish an online-based program to increase awareness of computer careers among middle school students.
St. Louis School Guide: Get test scores and moreDESE would also develop a high school graduation policy that allows students to take a computer science course for one unit of math, science or practical arts credit.Business groups praised the proposal, which is a focal point of Parson’s agenda.“This was the No. 1 issue that our members cared about,” said Ryan Stauffer of the Missouri Chamber of Commerce and Industry.“We believe in a strong workforce and employ a lot of these computer programmers, so we support this,” added Kyna Iman, who represents Boeing Co.But, there also are concerns that it could mean fewer math classes for students. Scott Penman of the Missouri Association of School Counselors said students will have to pay extra to take make-up math courses in college.


