JEFFERSON CITY • There were few fireworks when Missouri lawmakers convened a special legislative session on Monday.Facing a call by Gov. Mike Parson to fix two proposed laws that he vetoed this year, the Republican-controlled House and Senate spent the day positioning legislation for a vote later in the week.Parson, a Republican, ordered the session late last month to run concurrently with the Legislature’s annual veto session, which is set for Wednesday.

Rather than override the new governor, who marked his 100th day in office on Sunday, lawmakers will attempt to rework the two bills.One would allow high school computer science courses to count toward math, science or practical art credits needed for graduation. Parson vetoed the measure, saying it unfairly appeared to be tailored to apply to one contractor.Rep. Travis Fitzwater, R-Holts Summit, told KCUR in July that Learning Blade, which works with Arkansas, Kentucky and Tennessee public schools on STEM curriculum, helped write the language of the legislation.At the time, however, Fitzwater added the Chattanooga, Tenn.-based company wouldn’t be the only software firm that could meet the criteria.“I don’t believe that there was any sort of malfeasance or anything with this bill,” said Sen. John Rizzo, D-Independence. “This is just an honest mistake.”Sen. Jamilah Nasheed, D-St. Louis, wondered why lawmakers couldn’t reconsider the legislation when they came back for their regular session in January.“Why are we in special session when we could have dealt with this in January?” she asked the bill sponsor, Sen. Doug Libla, R-Poplar Bluff, wondering how much money the special session would cost.If all the state’s legislators collected their daily expense checks, the special session could cost an estimated $20,000 per day, not including staffing and mileage reimbursement costs.“We need to get this moving,” Libla said, adding that the state is losing out on investment opportunities. The senator said changes he is proposing in the legislation will eliminate concerns that it was drafted to benefit one vendor.
The other proposal dealt with treatment courts. Parson said the bill appeared to violate constitutional prohibitions on including multiple subjects under one bill.“These two issues were a part of the General Assembly’s historic session as they passed a number of their priorities,” Parson said in a statement. “By working together to come up with a more narrowly defined focus, we will have better served the people of Missouri.”The sponsor of the drug treatment legislation, Rep. Kevin Austin, R-Springfield, said he expects the measure to move quickly out of the House.“You never take anything for granted, but this should be an easy walk for me,” Austin said.
Also on tap are votes later in the week on appointments he’s made to various boards and commissions, including the state Board of Education, which has only begun meeting again after the Legislature rejected appointments made by former Gov. Eric Greitens.Although a special session is designed to fix legislation without having to override the governor, he could face backlash over his line-item veto of about $12 million out of the state’s $28 billion budget.Among the items that could be overridden is a $153,000 cut that Parson made from the Department of Health and Senior Services. The program designates hospitals as stroke, heart attack and trauma centers.Parson also received bipartisan scorn for cutting $50,000 to supply local law enforcement officers with tourniquets designed to stop bleeding if police or the public are injured.In an interview Saturday, Parson told the Post-Dispatch he believes supplying the tourniquets should be a local decision.“At what point do we say, how much are we going to supply. I think if the people of the towns and the counties felt like that need was there, they would do it,” Parson said.Senate President Pro Tem Ron Richard, R-Joplin, said “no” when asked if the upper chamber would attempt to override any of Parson’s budget decisions.


