ST. LOUIS • As Missouri Gov. Mike Parson, Kansas City Mayor Sly James and Mayor Lyda Krewson toured St. Louis on Friday, the discussions at each stop often returned to one common goal: strengthening relationships between state officials and the leaders of Missouri’s two largest cities.Parson, a conservative Republican from Bolivar, and Krewson and James, who lead Missouri’s largely Democratic urban centers, don’t often see eye to eye on public policy matters, by their own admission.Touring one another’s cities — together with a third trip in the works for the two mayors to spend time in rural Missouri — reflects a renewed effort to find some common ground, and a change in approach from the more strained relationships forged by Parson’s predecessor, Eric Greitens.

Both Krewson and James made clear the purpose of hosting the new governor in both St. Louis and Kansas City this summer wasn’t to present Parson with a list of demands, but to get to know one another and share information about challenges and successes in their respective municipalities.“Before we can actually start making requests and demands of each other, we have to have built some trust between each other to know that we’re not playing games here,” James said.But, Krewson added, “we showed him some things” that might suggest “things we want.”The first stop on Friday morning was Nathaniel Rivers Place Apartments, a low-income housing community in north St. Louis that city officials said would have been impossible to build without low-income housing tax credits.
First stop on @GovParsonMO’s tour of St. Louis is Nathaniel Rivers Place apartments, a low income housing community that couldn’t have been built without Low Income Housing Tax Credits. @LydaKrewson showing the governor and @MayorSlyJames around town today. pic.twitter.com/ZJeRvW7Wec— Celeste Bott (@celestebott) September 7, 2018


Last year, the Missouri Housing Development Commission voted against using state money to match $140 million in federal low-income housing tax credits through a program that has long been a political flashpoint. Then-Lt. Gov. Parson bucked Greitens in criticizing the move, but Parson maintained Friday that reforms to the program should come through the Legislature.Krewson and James also broached the subject of stronger local control on gun policy, arguing that St. Louis and Kansas City should be able to more tightly regulate guns in their respective regions for the sake of public safety. They had shared their views on the earlier Kansas City trip.
Parson still doesn’t take a firm stance on the matter, but he said he’d keep an open mind should a bill be introduced in the Legislature to address it.“I’ve always been a believer in the Second Amendment. ... Do I think there are ways we maybe can do a better job? I’m open,” Parson said during a meeting with Post-Dispatch editorial writers and editors after the tour.“Everybody wants me to answer that question. I don’t know what that legislation would look like. I don’t know how it would affect the cities,” he said. “We don’t want to have high crime rates. Whatever I can do to help these two mayors, I want to try to assist.”Krewson led Parson and James through a packed itinerary that included visits to Roosevelt High School, Ranken Technical College, and MADE, a working space for artists. They were joined by Linda McMahon, administrator of the U.S. Small Business Administration, for stops at the downtown T-Rex Incubator and GeoData IT LLC, a small veteran-owned business on Washington Avenue.Parson also addressed the St. Louis Board of Aldermen during its first meeting following a summer break.“We’re not going to agree on some things. I’m not going to agree on some of the things you do here, you’re not going to agree on some of the things I do,” Parson told the chamber. “But I will tell you this: If we will be open-minded with one another, there will be many, many things we will agree on, that will be the best thing in the world for the state of Missouri. And we should all focus on that.”


