JEFFERSON CITY • Gov. Mike Parson announced Thursday that he is calling legislators back to the capital city for a special session on education and expansion of drug treatment courts.Parson said in a release the special session would run concurrently with the GOP-controlled Legislature's annual veto session, during the week of Sept. 10. He vetoed two bills dealing with the topics over the summer.A special session means lawmakers can try to start from scratch to assuage Parson's concerns instead of forcing a potentially contentious vote to override the new governor's vetoes. Parson, a Republican, took over as governor on June 1 when former Gov. Eric Greitens resigned.


















            Post-Dispatch coverage of Greitens' affair scandal

From Greitens' initial statement to calls for his resignation, read the Post-Dispatch coverage of the governor's affair scandal. 




"These two issues were a part of the General Assembly’s historic session as they passed a number of their priorities," Parson said in a statement. "By working together to come up with a more narrowly defined focus, we will have better served the people of Missouri.” Parson vetoed House Bill 2562, which dealt with drug treatment courts, on July 13. Parson also vetoed Senate Bill 894, which dealt with science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) programs in the state.
The Senate bill would have allowed high school computer sciences courses to count toward credits needed for graduation. But Parson said bidding criteria for an online program that was spelled out in the bill appeared tailored for one company.Parson said the bill that in part dealt with treatment courts appeared unconstitutional because it included multiple subjects. He also said the legislation appeared to allow a judge who was seated in 2011 to receive state retirement benefits for which only employees who started working for the state before 2011 are eligible.
The benefits for employees who started before 2011 are considered more generous than the newer plan.Another portion of the House bill allowed certain individuals to enter abandoned property to secure it and clean it. But Parson said this could lead to unsafe situations, especially if the property owner did not know the person was improving the property.This Associated Press contributed to this report.


