JEFFERSON CITY • An overhaul of the state’s hiring system championed by former Gov. Eric Greitens went into effect Tuesday amid concern that it could trigger political retaliation.Natashia Pickens, the president of the Communications Workers of America Local 6355, told the Post-Dispatch that the new law was making some social service workers nervous.“We do work for the government,” Pickens said. “If I choose to support a candidate, and that candidate is of the opposite party, am I going to be at risk of losing my job? These are a lot of questions that we’ve had, and we’ve not been able to get any responses.”

Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican who took over after Greitens quit on June 1, hailed the new law, which he said would give the state greater flexibility in how it manages its workforce.“The new merit reform law will help us improve how state government operates for the benefit of both our citizens and our committed public servants by investing in new ways of working like never before,” Parson said.Under the state’s merit system, most employees are hired based on their performance on standardized tests, rather than their allegiance to a particular politician or political party.The new law removes the requirement that employees must rank in the top 15 percent of applicants — or in the top 15 applicants — to be selected for a state job. Now, workers need only meet the minimum requirements of the particular job class.The law also will streamline a hiring process that has sometimes led to 90-day wait times to hire job candidates.“Enabling managers to place the right employees in the right jobs, based on their skills and performance, will make their units more productive and allow managers to better recognize and reward employees for superior performance,” said Lt. Gov. Mike Kehoe, who sponsored the legislation in the Senate.
The changes are part of a deal the scandal-plagued Greitens laid out in his budget proposal in February, in which he said he’d sign off on small raises for the nation’s lowest-paid state workforce if lawmakers send him legislation that could make it easier for the governor’s administration to hire, fire and reward government workers.Lawmakers included $700-per-year raises in the budget, but the increase won’t go into effect until Jan. 1.The hiring changes also won’t immediately go into effect. State officials must first update the state’s personnel code and identify which pools of employees will lose their merit classification.
Opponents of the changes are concerned that the changes run counter to the reason the civil service system was developed when patronage and not skill or brainpower was a key factor in hiring.Pickens said many if not most of the employees the union represents at the Department of Social Services and the Department of Health and Senior Services still did not know how they would be affected by the new law. She said about 6,700 state workers were eligible to join the communications workers union, and she estimated the CWA had 1,100 members that were state employees.“We’ve asked which job classes are going to be covered and which job classes are going to be excluded,” Pickens said. “We’ve been told that they’re working on it and we’ll be updated. We’ve not gotten any word. We’ve talked to multiple members, and many of them don’t know if they’re covered or not.”She worries that the new law guts established processes that protected merit employees from frivolous complaints.“That goes away under the new merit system, because those protections are taken way,” Pickens said. “You can be fired for any reason and they don’t have to tell you what the reason is.”


