JEFFERSON CITY • With a severe drought clobbering Missouri farm country, officials outlined plans Monday aimed at addressing water and feed shortages for livestock operations across the state.Among them is an initiative that will allow ranchers to pump water out of nearly 28 state-owned lakes to supplement drying farm ponds that were never fully replenished during the winter months.Calling the conditions in 86 of the state’s 114 counties “very serious,” Gov. Mike Parson said the state also will open an estimated 900 acres of public land to a lottery so ranchers can cut hay to feed their cattle.

Parson, who runs a cattle farm in Bolivar, is among those who have had to feed hay to his herd because his pastures haven’t been able to support normal summer grazing. He said he’s never had to do that in August in his life.“This is a long way from being over,” Parson, who is 62, said. “Some people are not going to make it.”The drought in Missouri has been brought on by below-average rainfall affecting about 98 percent of the state. Twenty-five Missouri counties have been declared disaster areas by the U.S. Department of Agriculture, triggering emergency loan assistance.













Images courtesy of the U.S. Drought Monitor.


Missouri Department of Agriculture Director Chris Chin said ranchers are culling their herds and importing hay from out of state to keep their operations afloat.The state has eased permitting regulations and waived fees on hay hauling to assist farmers trying to get feed to their herds. But, she said, the cost of hay has risen quickly as demand has grown, putting some farmers at a financial disadvantage.“When our farmers hurt, our communities hurt too,” Chin said.Sean Cornelius, a dairy farmer from Hamilton in the hard-hit northwest region of the state, said he’s seen just 3.2 inches of rain since May. He said opening access to water in state parks and conservation areas will be a “super help.”
“We’ll do the best with what we have,” Cornelius said.Most of the pumping locations are north of Interstate 70 at places like Crowder and Wakonda state parks and Bonanza Conservation Area. In order to pump water out of the impoundments, farmers must contact the Department of Natural Resources at 573-751-4115, ext. 3209.Farmers are limited to 5,000 gallons of water per farm per day. Farmers can apply for the hay lottery through Saturday. One farmer from each location will be issued a permit that will allow haying on state grasslands from Aug. 27 through Nov. 27.
Its not just farmers facing hardship.In Cameron, near St. Joseph, officials declared a water emergency last week. The designation bars residents and businesses from watering their lawns and flowers. Other restrictions include prohibiting restaurants from serving water unless it is specifically requested by a customer. People violating the order face fines of $100 per day.To help shore up supplies for its 10,000 customers, the city has received permission to draw water from Pony Express Lake.In Hamilton, city administrator Jean Van Aperen said officials are searching for a nearby water district to help augment their supplies. The northwest Missouri town of 1,800 residents has been under restrictions similar to those in Cameron since May.Thus far, she said no fines have been issued.“If we see someone violating the rules, we try to educate them on why they are in place. So far it has worked,” Van Aperen said.Parson said he hopes the state assistance will ease the pressure on the state’s agriculture industry.“We can’t fix the rain. It’s a little bit above our pay grades,” he said.


