JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri Gov. Mike Parson's team is still processing an open-records request dating to a more chaotic era in state politics.Attorney General Josh Hawley's office filed the Sunshine request with former Gov. Eric Greitens' office on May 11. Hawley, a Republican, was investigating whether Greitens, a Republican, and his team broke a Missouri law that forbids taxpayer-paid employees from working on political projects.When Greitens resigned on June 1, Greitens' legal team told the attorney general's office the governor's office was closing the request. But it also said the office could "resubmit" its request to the Parson administration.

Parson's office told the Post-Dispatch in June and on Tuesday that the office was not processing that particular request.When told this on Tuesday, the Post-Dispatch contacted the attorney general's office to ask about the apparent inaction.Later that day, a Parson spokesman called to say the governor's office was mistaken. The administration was pulling the files, after all."I apologize for any confusion," said Steele Shippy, communications director for Parson, a Republican. It remains unclear to what extent anyone was working to fulfill this request over the summer.When pressed for an explanation, Shippy said in an email: "Today is not the first day this Sunshine request has been talked about or worked on. Our office reviewed this Sunshine request shortly after taking office and we are working to fully comply with the request."Mary Compton, spokeswoman for the attorney general's office, said in an email Wednesday morning: "The Governor’s Office has confirmed to us that they are still processing our Sunshine request."In the request, Hawley’s general counsel Michael Martinich-Sauter asked for any emails between the governor’s office and Austin Chambers, a top Greitens political adviser, and any emails to C5 Consulting, a now-defunct political shop owned by Vice President Mike Pence’s chief of staff, Nick Ayers.
The office also wanted any emails to Greitens’ personal confidants, Mark and Chris Bobak, as well as any emails to the Greitens Group, Greitens’ campaign treasurer Jeff Stuerman and other campaign-related entities. They also wanted the office to pull emails between two staffers that contained any of 17 search terms (including "Chalupas").The investigation followed reporting from the Kansas City Star raising questions about the legality of Greitens’ taxpayer-funded staff working on Greitens’ personal Facebook page.Greitens' general counsel, Lucinda Luetkemeyer, wrote to Martinich-Sauter on June 1 that the office was "closing the pending records request" because that was the last day of the Greitens administration.Luetkemeyer said in the same letter, however, that the outgoing administration was forwarding the request to the Parson administration for "review and processing," suggesting the request was not closed. Later in the letter, though, she said that Hawley's office could "resubmit" the request if it desired, suggesting the request was closed.
The Post-Dispatch obtained copies of the governor's office Sunshine request log on June 21. It shows the status of Martinich-Sauter's request was marked "closed" as of June 1.Compton would not say in June whether the office intended to resubmit its request.She said only in an email that “our office intends to pursue and conclude its investigations in an orderly fashion.”At a campaign stop in St. Charles last week, the newspaper asked Hawley, who is running for U.S. Senate this year, for an update on his investigation. Hawley was also investigating Greitens' potentially illegal use of charity resources.Hawley said that both investigations were ongoing.“We want to make sure that we get the facts, and that we are very thorough,” Hawley said last Wednesday. “And we are going to continue to do that. But they (the investigations) are open.”


