JEFFERSON CITY • An Osage County judge dismissed a lawsuit Tuesday that sought to block Missouri voters from deciding whether to raise the state’s gasoline tax in November.Associate Circuit Judge Robert Schollmeyer ruled against the lawsuit filed by Rep. Mike Moon, R-Ash Grove, and activist Ron Calzone, who had argued that the Legislature took parliamentary shortcuts in approving a referendum that would phase in a 10-cent increase in the state’s motor fuel tax over four years.Moon had said the referendum violated the Missouri Constitution because the measure’s wording deals with two topics, which is not allowed.

The ballot question, known as Proposition D, was approved in the often-frantic, closing hours of the legislative session in May. With time expiring, lawmakers tacked the gas tax issue onto a bill authorizing a tax deduction for Olympic medals.Schollmeyer, in his 14-page decision, said separate pieces of the legislation fit together under a common title.“(T)he provisions undoubtedly have a natural connection to regulating Missouri’s state revenue stream,” the judge wrote.Attorneys for the state and a coalition of organizations backing the referendum had called on Schollmeyer to be cautious in deciding whether to allow cases such as this to move forward, saying it would be better to decide after voters weigh in.At 17-cents per gallon, Missouri’s motor fuel tax is among the lowest in the nation. Increasing the tax by a dime would place the state’s gas tax above the national average, according to the U.S. Energy Information Administration.
Analysts say the tax could bring in an additional $293 million annually for the state road fund once the full amount has been implemented. The measure also creates a dedicated revenue stream for the Missouri Highway Patrol.Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, has signaled his support for the increase, saying the state cannot continue delaying a major infrastructure plan.
Construction companies already have contributed more than $300,000 in campaign contributions to a group known as SaferMO.com, which was established to get the measure approved.“SaferMO.com appreciates the court’s clear decision dismissing this baseless attempt to keep Missouri voters from having a say on Proposition D. Our statewide coalition is growing and moving full speed," spokesman Scott Charton said.“Businesses across Missouri agree — transportation funding is one of the most important issues facing our state. We need to invest in our infrastructure and use our natural connections to our advantage as we seek to grow our economy,” said Dan Mehan, president and CEO of the Missouri Chamber of Commerce and Industry.Moon and Calzone say they are planning to appeal.“In a time when Missourians are clamoring for checks and balances between the different branches of government, it appears that the legislature is being handed an open checkbook… whatever the legislature wants, the courts will ‘have their backs,'" Moon said.The legislation is House Bill 1460.


