JEFFERSON CITY • When Attorney General Josh Hawley and U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill face each other this November, as many as six high-profile questions will appear on the same ballot as the Senate race.Three groups gathered enough signatures to place three different medical marijuana measures on the ballot. Another group seeks to raise Missouri’s minimum wage to $12 per hour by 2023. Two other questions — one raising the state’s fuel tax and another reforming state ethics laws — will appear if they survive court challenges.
















            A study in contrast: Josh Hawley and Claire McCaskill

From his days as a law clerk to his private practice, Josh Hawley has focused on cases where religion and the law intersect. Claire McCaskill …






In response to Post-Dispatch questions last week, McCaskill made her positions on the topics known, while Hawley said he was still formulating his opinions.At a campaign stop at a soybean farm in Tebbetts, Mo., on Friday, McCaskill said she would back at least one medical marijuana initiative and support the ethics-reform push backed by the group CLEAN Missouri. She also endorsed the minimum wage hike and the boost to the state’s fuel tax.McCaskill, a Democrat, said she was still studying the three medical marijuana initiatives, and said she was “a little uncomfortable” with the language backed by Springfield attorney and physician, Dr. Brad Bradshaw.“I do think medical marijuana should be passed,” she said.“I think it is time that we make additional investments in our infrastructure,” she said. “And I join our Republican governor and our Republican lieutenant governor in supporting the gas tax.“I certainly think an increase in minimum wage is appropriate,” McCaskill said, “and I couldn’t be more enthusiastic about CLEAN Missouri.”Hawley, a Republican, said he was still studying the proposals when asked about them at a St. Charles campaign stop on Wednesday.“I’m glad they’re on the ballot,” Hawley said when asked about medical marijuana, the gasoline tax and the minimum wage increase. “I think the people should have their say on all of them. I think it’s up to the voters.
“I’m still studying the language on each one of those,” he said, when pressed on his positions. The campaign did not respond to a follow-up question about Hawley’s position on CLEAN Missouri.McCaskill has barbed Hawley for his support of the state’s “right to work” law, which two-thirds of voters rejected last week. By opposing either medical marijuana or a hike to Missouri’s minimum wage, Hawley risks being on the wrong side of public opinion.A Quinnipiac University poll last year found 94 percent of U.S. adults support legalizing marijuana for medicinal purposes. Voters in conservative states such as Florida and Arkansas approved their own programs in 2016.
















            Medical marijuana backers confident Missourians will get to weigh in this year

Backers of medical marijuana have failed for years to get a question on the ballot.




Missouri voters last approved a minimum wage hike in 2006. Like the right-to-work vote, the state’s conservative electorate has shown support for traditionally Democratic-backed economic policies.McCaskill, on the other hand, could face exposure for her support of increased taxes to pay for road improvements. Missouri voters in 2014 shot down an increase to the state’s sales tax to pay for road improvements.But Republicans — including Gov. Mike Parson and Lt. Gov. Mike Kehoe — have signaled support for this year’s gasoline tax question, saying that Missouri can’t delay a major infrastructure push any longer.Proponents of the gas tax also argue such an increase amounts to a more equitable way to pay for road improvements than the 2014 proposal, saying that those who drive more will inevitably pay more for road upkeep.Though CLEAN Missouri has drawn bipartisan support, a number of Republicans in recent weeks have said that they will oppose the ballot initiative.They argue a provision reforming Missouri’s redistricting process will unfairly leave Missouri with too many Democratic legislative districts following the 2020 U.S. Census. Proponents dispute this.


