Thirty-five percent of health care firms and 38 percent of financial firms said they were experiencing a shortage of skilled applicants. That jumped to 61 percent in tech services, where jobs often require industry certifications.Tech firms also stood out when employers were asked what they’re doing about the skill shortage. The top responses in finance and health care included training inexperienced workers and offering higher wages.In technology, firms’ No. 1 answer was that they were hiring from outside the United States. That may become difficult if the government continues to make H-1B visas harder to obtain.The No. 2 answer was more shocking: 42 percent of tech employers selected “none of the above.” In an industry that complains of a severe skill shortage, nearly half of firms aren’t doing anything specific about it.
“This may reflect a reticence by technology-intensive services employers to invest in employee development in a very talent-competitive industry,” the report says.For Hart Nelson, the community college’s associate vice chancellor for workforce solutions, that non-response poses a particular challenge to places such as St. Louis. “It really means these jobs may get created overseas or somewhere else,” he said. “The jobs will go somewhere.”
If tech firms can’t or won’t invest in talent development, the responsibility falls to regional colleges, universities and programs like LaunchCode and Claim Academy. The quality and quantity of their graduates will determine whether St. Louis becomes a leader or an also-ran in the industries of the future.In fact, the report contains a call to action for institutions such as St. Louis Community College. Across the three targeted industries, firms listed “shortage of available training programs” as their third most important barrier to growth, after the skill shortage and “government policies or regulations.”Nelson says his institution is listening. The community college works with employers in various industries to meet their skill needs. It’s building a new health sciences building on the Forest Park campus so it can train more nurses and other medical professionals.The employer partnerships aren’t all at high skill levels. Nelson says conversations with financial services firms led to the creation of a 12-week training program that prepares workers for data-entry or call-center jobs.While St. Louis Community College has been studying workforce issues for a decade — and has highlighted the skill shortage as a top issue for the last four years — others have joined the conversation recently. The Missouri Chamber of Commerce issued a report this spring on the looming shortage of young, skilled workers, and new Missouri Gov. Mike Parson has listed workforce training as a top priority.Talk and action are two different things, however. Missouri’s higher-education budget for this year cuts community college funding by $3.7 million, or 2.6 percent. It’s going to be hard to train the workforce of the future with resources that don’t even keep pace with the past.


