JEFFERSON CITY • As a light rain fell on Missouri’s capital city Thursday, a task force assembled to assess the state’s drought met for the first time.“It’s a little ironic that we convened this meeting in the middle of a rainstorm. But don’t let it deceive you,” Missouri Department of Natural Resources Director Carol Comer told more than three dozen in attendance.Fifty-two of Missouri’s 114 counties are now affected by the lingering lack of precipitation, up from 47 last week when Gov. Mike Parson activated the panel to monitor the drought. Eleven counties have slipped into a more extreme category of drought since July 19.

In all, nearly 2.6 million people live in drought-affected areas.The most updated drought map, released Thursday, places St. Charles County and a swath of southwestern St. Louis County within the abnormally dry category.Other warning signs are in Franklin County, where groundwater well levels have fallen off, said National Weather Service hydrologist Mark Fuchs.“In just a week we’ve had quite an expansion of extreme drought,” said Jennifer Hoggatt, of the Department of Natural Resources’ Missouri Water Resources Center.Although it’s early in the assessment, Rob Kallenbach of the University of Missouri Extension service said the drought has already cost the state’s agriculture industry an estimated $2 billion.And, Kallenbach said, that number is growing.For farmers, especially those in the hard-hit northwest part of the state, the drought has raised red flags about having adequate feed for cattle.“Our hay yield’s about half of where we usually are,” Kallenbach said.The state has already granted a statewide variance that allows grazing on land that would normally not provide grazing.Missouri also has earmarked $2 million to help farmers plant cover crops to improve feed and forage and other natural resources.
Kallenbach said more farmers are turning to harvesting drought-damaged corn to feed to their herds.Colleen Meredith, soil and water conservation director for DNR, said the state is considering a plan to ease regulations on farmers in order to streamline the process for digging wells.The drought has affected public water systems near Kansas City and northwestern Missouri, said David Lamb of DNR’s public drinking water division.
In Hamilton, low water levels in the reservoir that supplies nearly 2,500 customers has triggered conservation measures and forced officials to begin seeking options to acquire more water.Officials in Cameron, near St. Joseph, have gotten permission to temporarily draw from Pony Express Lake in order to shore up their supplies for 10,000 customers.Fuchs said there is some rain in the forecast in the next week, but it won’t be enough to keep the entire state from being under a drought by October.“There’s some hope there for the state, but not necessarily where we need it the most,” Fuchs said.State officials have been watching the situation since winter, when warning signs about problems in the northwest part of the state began to surface.By mid-July, the committee felt the parched conditions warranted governmental involvement, sparking the governor’s executive order.The committee includes members from the Department of Natural Resources, the U.S. Forest Service, University of Missouri, the Department of Agriculture and other state, federal and local agencies.State climatologist Pat Guinan said this drought rivals the 2012 drought, with rainfall totals 12 to 15 inches below normal in some counties, representing a 56 percent decrease in precipitation.“They are approaching records, when we have records going back 150 years,” Guinan said.


