JEFFERSON CITY • Backers of Gov. Mike Parson have launched a political action committee in support of the Republican chief executive — but, unlike a similar group tied to his predecessor, the names of donors and the amounts they contribute will be disclosed to the public.“We’re going to support, obviously, his policies, and, Lord willing, his re-election bid (in 2020),” John Hancock, chairman of Uniting Missouri PAC, told the Post-Dispatch.Parson, who had been lieutenant governor, took over for former Republican Gov. Eric Greitens on June 1 when Greitens resigned amid months of scandal.

During his 17 months in office, Greitens used the nonprofit group A New Missouri to promote his agenda.In contrast to Uniting Missouri, A New Missouri did not have to reveal its donors because of its nonprofit status. This led to charges that Greitens violated Missouri campaign finance law by intentionally concealing donors and worries that his backers gained unfair influence within state government.“All of our donations will be disclosed,” said Hancock, who is the former chairman of the Missouri Republican Party. “And all of our expenditures will be disclosed. ... That was done expressly at Gov. Parson’s desire not to have any dark money involved in his political world.”Unlike a traditional candidate campaign committee, Uniting Missouri is able to accept unlimited donations. Since Missouri voters enacted limits on campaign contributions in 2016, a growing number of candidates have set up political action committees that do not have to abide by those rules.“Really this is an outgrowth of the way the campaign finance laws are drafted,” Hancock said. “There really would not be a need for a PAC in the old days when there were no contribution limits.”
The Post-Dispatch reported last year on a surge in political action committees following the passage of Amendment 2, which capped individual contributions to campaign committees at $2,600 per election.In contrast to Uniting Missouri’s large donations from a limited number of backers, Parson’s campaign committee raised $106,000 in small donations last quarter from more than 200 contributors.
Uniting Missouri has accepted just more than $155,000 in contributions since its inception on June 29, according to its disclosure forms. Almost all of that money was raised on July 18.Sterling Bancshares Inc., of Poplar Bluff, donated $20,000 to Uniting Missouri. The company, involved in low-income housing tax credit projects, did not respond to inquiries throughout the spring about a role some speculated it played in mysterious cash payments to opponents of Greitens’.Mark Gardner, of Springfield-based Gardner Capital Inc., donated $25,000. MACO Development Inc. in Clarkton donated $25,000. Gardner and MACO are also tied to low-income housing tax credit projects.Greitens led an effort to end low-income housing tax credits last year, which have earned low marks for inefficiencies. Parson supports the incentives, saying they spur necessary investment in underdeveloped areas.Parson has said that he would not try to reinstate low-income housing tax credits this year, and said that any effort to restore them would have to be tied to reforms.Other donations to Uniting Missouri include: $10,000 from Republic Services Inc., a waste-collection company whose properties include West Lake Landfill; $25,000 from St. Louis County-based Express Scripts; $20,000 from St. Louis-based Spire Missouri Inc.; $20,000 from Phoenix Home Care; and $10,000 from Wildwood-based Torch Electronics.


