JEFFERSON CITY • A coalition of labor unions fighting to stop Missouri from becoming a right-to-work state ended the most recent fundraising quarter with $3.7 million in its campaign account.On a day in which candidates and political action committees reported their quarterly contributions and expenditures ahead of the Aug. 7  primaries, the numbers from the We are Missouri PAC show the pro-labor group far ahead in fundraising over its opponents.The trio of political action committees working in support of right to work reported having a total of $985,118 after the April, May and June reporting period.

• Research your ballot with the Post-Dispatch voters guideThe money-check came as Gov. Mike Parson, a Republican, said Monday he would hit the campaign trail trying to convince voters to vote “yes” on the proposition.“We support right to work and I’m sure we’ll be out there on the campaign (trail),” Parson told reporters at the Capitol. “We’re not sure scheduling wise how much that will be, but yeah, we’ll be supporting that issue.”Under the proposal, workers could not be compelled, as a condition of employment, to join or to pay dues to a labor union.We Are Missouri has raised a total of $12.3 million in its effort to overturn the law approved last year. Between April and July 1, the coalition raised $5.4 million and spent $6.8 million.The group Freedom to Work has $441,289 after raising $562,000 in the quarter. The account spent $1.3 million during the past three months, including $900,000 to a company owned by one of former Gov. Eric Greitens’ consultants, Jeff Roe. The money was supposed to pay for the collection of signatures to put a pro-right to work referendum on the ballot, but backers failed to turn in any of the signatures needed.A second group, Missourians for Freedom to Work, has $539,960 in its account after raising $592,000 in the quarter. Among the donors was $100,000 from Joplin mega donor David Humphreys, a roofing material company. Among its biggest expenditures was $42,000 for a Virginia-based polling firm to do focus groups.The third PAC, Missourians for Worker Freedom, has $3,869 in its account after receiving one $5,000 contribution from Liberty Alliance.In the Republican race for auditor, attorney David Wasinger of Huntleigh had $760,968 in the bank, fueled largely from an early $500,000 loan he gave himself.Rep. Paul Curtman, R-Pacific, reported $20,939, after raising $9,399 in the quarter.Businessman Kevin Roach of Ballwin had $2,877 in his campaign account, while Saundra McDowell, a Jefferson City attorney, ended the quarter with $1,522 in her account. She raised $3,501 and spent more than $5,400.The winner will take on Democratic Auditor Nicole Galloway in November. She reported having $1.1 million in her account.Contested primaries also are on tap for a number of seats in the Missouri House and Senate. Among them:• 73rd House District: Three Democrats are vying for the seat currently held by Rep. Courtney Curtis, D-Ferguson. The district encompasses St. Louis Lambert International Airport and includes all or parts of Berkeley, Ferguson, Bridgeton and St. Ann.Lee Smith of Ferguson has $3,436 in his account. The former president and business manager for the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 2352 received just one $150 contribution in the most recent quarter.
Raychel Proudie, who had considered a run for the Ferguson-Florissant school district last year, has $7,421 in her account after raising $6,245 in the prior three months.Floyd Blackwell, the former mayor of Cool Valley, did not file a quarterly report by Monday's 5 p.m. deadline.• 86th House District: Four Democrats are vying to represent this district, which takes in part of University City north of Delmar Boulevard and smaller municipalities around Page Avenue. State Sen. Maria Chappelle-Nadal, D-University City, is term-limited in the Senate but can serve one more term in the lower chamber.She had the most cash on hand as of July 1 among the slate of candidates, which includes Farrakhan Shegog, 26, of University City; retired engineer Gloria Nickerson, 64, of University City; and educator Bobby Shields, 56, of University City.• 14th Senate District: Three Democrats are running in this heavily-Democratic district, which stretches from Clayton to the Missouri River and takes in all or parts of municipalities such as Ferguson, Berkeley, University City and Normandy.Rep. Joe Adams, D-University City, was leading the cash race as of July 1, recording more than $62,000 on hand and a nearly $17,000 fundraising haul last quarter. Former Rep. Sharon Pace, D-Northwoods, raised $2,800 and had $27,900 on hand.
A third candidate, Brian Williams of University City, is a former staffer of U.S. Rep. William "Lacy" Clay. Williams had $41,460 on hand and raised $22,510 last quarter. One $100 check came from former U.S. Rep. William  Clay, Sr., who told the Post-Dispatch Monday that "I know him and I think he's a well-qualified individual."Chappelle-Nadal has a historically icy relationship with Adams, who ran against her for state Senate in 2010. She said Monday she is leaning toward voting for Pace. She said the two men in the race have focused their campaigns on University City, offering Pace an opening to snag votes in other parts of the district.• 95th House District: Republicans Joe Patterson and Michael O'Donnell are running in the Republican-leaning 95th District, which takes in Oakville in south St. Louis County. Republican Rep. Marsha Haefner is term-limited.Patterson, 32, a police detective for St. Louis County, raised $18,000 last quarter, spent $17,000 and had $23,300 cash on hand as of July 1. He describes himself as pro-labor and said he would vote "no" on the Aug. 7 right-to-work referendum.O'Donnell, 50, a Navy reservist, raised $600 last quarter and had $3,270 in his campaign coffers as of July 1. "They money side's probably the most difficult," he said. O'Donnell supports the right-to-work initiative.• 97th House District: Three Republicans are running for the chance to unseat Rep. Mike Revis, a Fenton Democrat who won a special election to the Republican-leaning Jefferson County seat in February.David Linton, an attorney whom Revis beat in February, had $1,600 on hand after spending $2,100 last quarter. Mary Elizabeth Coleman, 36, a lawyer and former Arnold City Council member, raised $8,014 and had $10,352 on hand. A third candidate, Phil Amato, 64, a former Arnold City Council member, raised $6,300 last quarter, spent $6,800 and had $4,400 on hand.Amato said he's endorsed by LIUNA Local 110, which donated the maximum $2,600 to his campaign in June. Amato, who ran for Jefferson County Council as a Democrat in 2010, said he is pro-labor but his values align with the Republican Party because of the Democrats' leftward drift."I didn't leave the party (the Democrats)," he said. "The party left me."Coleman said she is voting "yes" on Prop A, but said she is from a union family and expects to see voters shoot down the pending law on Aug. 7."Unions are a vital part of our community," Coleman said, adding that she is in the "middle" between Amato and Linton when it comes to union issues. Linton did not return a request for comment.


