JEFFERSON CITY • Even though much of it is gone or crumbling, one of the most well-known stretches of pavement in the world will be under the microscope in Missouri and Illinois as state officials begin planning for the 100th anniversary of Route 66.Under legislation signed by then-Gov. Eric Greitens, Missouri is set to form an 18-member commission to plan and sponsor a centennial observance in 2026 for the Mother Road, which stretches 2,400 miles from Chicago to Los Angeles.In Missouri, the now-decommissioned two lane highway generally follows the path of Interstate 44 across the state. In St. Louis, Route 66 wound its way through a number of alignments, including the Chain of Rocks and McKinley bridges, Chouteau Avenue, Tucker Boulevard, Gravois Avenue, Chippewa Street and Manchester Road.














Jason Apple and Pam Martin clean up after a day of burgers and root beer at Carl's Drive-In on Manchester Road in Brentwood on Thursday, Aug. 18, 2016. The mainstay along old Route 66, built as a 1920s gas station, was renamed in 1959 by Carl Meyer. Meyer sold it to Frank Cunetto in 1986, who carried on the tradition of burgers and root beer almost 30 years until last year when it was sold to Mike Franklin. Photo by Robert Cohen, rcohen@post-dispatch.com


Robert Cohen


Heading west, it went through Wildwood, Eureka and Pacific.During its time in service, the road was a key route for Americans migrating during the Great Depression and a popular vacation travel route after World War II. It was phased out in 1985 as it was replaced by the interstate highway system.
















            Experience the best of Route 66

10 ways to jump-start your Route 66 experience in Missouri, Illinois and Kansas. 




Throughout the eight states it crosses, many of the roadside businesses built to serve travelers closed as traffic dwindled to a trickle.Under terms of the law sponsored by Missouri Rep. Lyndall Fraker, R-Marshfield, the commission will plan and sponsor official Route 66 centennial events and activities, encourage the development of programs to involve residents in activities that commemorate Route 66 centennial events and make information available to the public about Route 66 events.New Gov. Mike Parson has not selected members for the panel.













A bison herd grazes in Lone Elk Park in St. Louis County, just off Interstate 44 near Valley Park as snow falls on Wednesday, Feb. 10, 2015. The park, featuring its namesake elk, bison, wild turkey and other waterfowl, opened to the public in 1971 after serving as a storage and testing facility for ammunition during World War II. Photo by Robert Cohen, rcohen@post-dispatch.com


Robert Cohen


Fraker said he hoped to be appointed to serve on the panel.As a youngster in the 1960s, he recalls piling into the family station wagon to head on Route 66 to St. Louis Cardinals baseball games. While some of the roadway had already been transformed into what would become I-44, he said some of the old diners and motels were still along the route.Now, he lives next to the old highway.
In his hometown of Marshfield, Fraker envisions erecting signs directing motorists to the downtown business district as a way to boost tourism. He also said grant money could pay to paint water towers along the route promoting local connections with the old road.













Bodybuilding competitors answer the judges' call for 'reverse double bicep' at the Caveman Classic at Meramec Caverns in Stanton, Mo. on Saturday, May 5, 2001. Lester Dill first opened the popular Route 66 cave in 1935. Photo by Robert Cohen, rcohen@post-dispatch.com


Robert Cohen


“We see motorcycle clubs, Corvette clubs and old vehicles traveling the highway. We just feel like we’re not really taking advantage of it,” Fraker said.Kate Renfrow, spokeswoman for the Missouri Division of Tourism, said a recent survey showed that 5 percent of the state’s visitors report that they do some type of Route 66 activity when they are visiting the Show-Me State. Of those, nearly half said the old road was a motivator for their visit.
In Illinois, Rep. Tim Butler, R-Springfield, sponsored a similar proposal that now awaits the signature of Gov. Bruce Rauner. There, Route 66 roughly followed the route that is now Interstate 55.Butler said he was in Atlanta, Ill., recently and counted six out-of-state license plates on the main street in town.













Crowds gather at Ted Drewes Frozen Custard on Chippewa Street, a part of old Route 66, on Thursday, Aug. 11, 2016. Photo by Robert Cohen, rcohen@post-dispatch.com


Robert Cohen


“When you drive on 66 in Illinois, you go through small towns like Atlanta. They’ve done a wonderful job of rehabbing their downtown,” Butler said.He said the centennial commission could help other communities tap into the market.“I think you’re going to see communities leverage it for economic development purposes. It’s a huge draw for people around the world,” Butler said.In Washington, U.S. Rep. Rodney Davis, R-Taylorville, Ill., is sponsoring legislation to establish a national commission that will plan for the centennial and create a plan to ensure the iconic road is preserved for future generations. The proposal, which is pending in the House, is known as “House Resolution 66.”“We’re just trying to get the ball rolling for the centennial,” Fraker said.













A young St. Louis visitor to the Wigwam Village Motel in Holbrook, Ariz. has a look through a window during a family visit in 2008. The motel, built in 1950 and known for its Western Americana feel and is located on Old Route 66 and is still serving guests. Photo by Robert Cohen, rcohen@post-dispatch.com


Robert Cohen




