JEFFERSON CITY • A paperwork mix-up in Missouri has scuttled plans to place a statue of Harry S Truman in the U.S. Capitol.In action Friday, Missouri Gov. Mike Parson vetoed legislation that would remove a statue of former U.S. Sen. Thomas Hart Benton in the Capitol’s Statuary Hall in order to make room for one of the nation’s 33rd president.Parson said the legislation approving the statue switch, approved on the final, frenzied day of the Legislature’s spring session, wrongly described which Benton would be replaced.

Benton, the great-great uncle of the famed mural painter by the same name, served five terms in the Senate. Benton’s abolitionist views cost him the Senate seat in 1850. He later served in the House.But, Parson said the legislation he received from lawmakers suggested the statue being replaced was the painter, not the politician.It was not clear Friday how the language of the bill had gotten the two confused, but it appeared in May that the version being voted on by members of the House and Senate had been corrected.Sen. Dan Hegeman, R-Cosby, who sponsored the legislation, could not immediately be reached for comment.In a statement, Parson’s office said, “The governor will be reaching out and meeting with House and Senate leadership next week to explore options and discuss efforts to address veto concerns.”In any case, the push to get a Truman statue into the Capitol will be on hold until at least next year while the situation is clarified.
Each state gets two statues in the Capitol's Statuary Hall, located just footsteps from where Congress does its business.The state’s other statue is of Francis Preston Blair, who served most of a nearly two-decade congressional career in the House of Representatives during and after the Civil War, culminating in two years in the Senate.In 2002, the Legislature approved replacing Blair with Truman. Last year, the state’s two senators, Democrat Claire McCaskill and Republican Roy Blunt, said they want to proceed with the plan to replace Blair.
But Republican members of Missouri’s delegation in the House said they favored replacing Benton, the former senator.During debate on the matter, Hegeman said he favors keeping Blair over Benton because of Blair’s role in keeping Missouri from becoming a Confederate state during the Civil War.And, he said he is following the wishes of the members of Congress.“Many of the delegation would like to see Benton be the one removed. Blair did help keep the State of Missouri in the Union,” Hegeman said at the time.The legislation notes that Truman “was the most important statesman Missouri ever gave the nation, an outstanding county official, United States Senator, Vice President and President of the United States who brought the Second World War to completion, led the free world at the beginning of the Cold War, and stood for fairness and opportunity for all Americans.”The legislation is Senate Concurrent Resolution 50.


