JEFFERSON CITY • Income tax rates in Missouri will drop next year as part of a tax cut being signed by Gov. Mike Parson on Thursday.Under the election-year plan approved by lawmakers in May, the individual income tax rate will decrease to 5.5 percent on Jan. 1, down from 5.9 percent.The rate would gradually drop to 5.1 percent if the state meets revenue targets. To offset the expected loss in revenue, the proposal would phase out a federal income tax deduction.

When fully implemented in 2023, analysts say it will result in an estimated $5.8 million less in revenue.Parson signaled his intent to sign the legislation on Monday when he released his schedule for the remainder of the week. Along with job creation announcements in Sedalia on Tuesday and Warrensburg on Wednesday, the new governor will travel to Springfield on Thursday for the tax bill signing.The measure was sponsored in the House by Rep. Elijah Haahr, R-Springfield, who will take over as speaker of the House next year.“Obviously, I am very excited,” Haahr said Monday. “I think this is one of the capstones of the session.”Despite causing massive financial headaches in neighboring Kansas, efforts to reduce tax rates in Missouri were pushed hard by GOP members of the House and Senate during their spring session.
Former Gov. Eric Greitens, who quit under the cloud of scandal on June 1, hit the road for a tour this year calling on lawmakers to approve a larger package of cuts worth more than $800 million.Haahr contended that his plan is much smaller than what went into effect in Kansas. Lawmakers there were later forced to raise taxes in order to adequately fund education and other services.
Initially, Haahr had wanted to take the top rate down to 5 percent in order to make Missouri one of the 10 lowest states for income tax rates. But, he said the 5.1 percent mark will still move Missouri into the lowest 15.The signing of the individual income tax cut comes after Greitens signed a separate reduction in the corporate tax rate before he left office.Under that plan, the corporate rate will drop to 4 percent, down from 6.25 percent, beginning in 2020.Amid the moves by lawmakers to reduce taxes, lawmakers also voted to put a question to voters in November to raise taxes on motor fuel.Under the ballot question, Missourians will be asked whether to boost the state’s gas tax from 17 cents per gallon to 27 cents over the next five years to pay for road and bridge repairs.


