ST. LOUIS • On the eve of the nation’s birthday, hundreds gathered at the Gateway Arch to celebrate the reopening of a museum commemorating the country’s massive westward expansion.The Gateway Arch Museum and Visitor Center officially reopened Tuesday, drawing federal and state officials along with scores of area residents who highlighted the Arch’s status as a federal monument, and also a local landmark.“This icon represents us and it defines us,” said Cardinals Hall of Famer Ozzie Smith, who emceed the ceremony.




            'This is something so special.' Years in the making, Gateway Arch museum and entry reopensMissouri Gov. Mike Parson applauded the combined national, state and local efforts that carried out the $380 million project.


__tnt.youtube.players.register('youtube-player-620e04de-a81a-5dc7-9041-ae44caa74869');


            {
                "@context": "https://schema.org",
                "@type": "VideoObject",
                "name": "The Gateway Arch museum opens its doors to the public after $380 million renovation",
                "description": "The Gateway Arch museum and entry opened to the public after a $380 million renovation on Tuesday, July 3, 2018. Visitors lined the entrance to experience the redone museum. Video by Cristina M. Fletes, cfletes@post-dispatch.com",
                "thumbnailUrl": "https://bloximages.newyork1.vip.townnews.com/stltoday.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/6/20/620e04de-a81a-5dc7-9041-ae44caa74869/5b3c08a041a46.preview.jpg?resize=1200%2C533",
