        “Together, we have made something very special for the state of Missouri,” Parson said.The National Park Service, Jefferson National Parks Association, the city of St. Louis, Great Rivers Greenway, Bi-State Development, Gateway Arch Park Foundation and the Missouri Department of Transportation were all active in the project.The museum and visitor center features a 46,000-square-foot multilevel addition, marking the next-to-last renovation project at Gateway Arch National Park.The Old Courthouse renovations will be the final project. Included in the new museum are six themed exhibits, one of which is a gallery on the design and construction of the Arch.















            Your guide to Fair St. Louis and July Fourth

Here's where to find music, fireworks and more fun.  




Renovations began in 2013 and were expected to be completed much sooner. But there were delays before and after the groundbreaking, including disagreements over financing obligations among the local and federal public agencies involved.Voters in St. Louis and St. Louis County played a pivotal role in the renovations when they approved Proposition P in 2013, which secured $90 million in sales taxes for the work.Tuesday’s fanfare featured a ribbon-cutting and speeches by U.S. Interior Secretary Ryan Zinke; Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Mo.; Sen. Roy Blunt, R-Mo.; St. Louis Mayor Lyda Krewson; and St. Louis County Executive Steve Stenger.McCaskill applauded St. Louisans who decided to tax themselves “to make sure we take care of our crown jewel, the Arch.”Krewson acknowledged the unity behind the project. “I think this is an example of what we can do when we come together and we make the big decisions at the city and county level.”
















            Interactive: What's New At The Arch?

Here's a guide to what's been accomplished in five years. Hover over one of the images to description of the area. 




Stenger summed up the sentiment of area residents:“This may be a national park, but on a personal level, it feels like ours,” he said.Cindy Steinbruegge, 63, has lived in St. Louis since she was in second grade. She remembers visiting the Arch when it was being constructed, and later, bringing her own kids to see it.
Mike Fuoss, 71, and his wife, Lori, 62, brought their son to the Arch several times when he was young. Their son turned out to be one of the lead architects for the renovation project.The Fuosses traveled from their home in Peoria, Ill., to share this moment with their son, Joel Fuoss, of Trivers Associates architects in St. Louis.Mike Fuoss said he was most excited about seeing how the Arch evolved.“It makes it very special to us and to the city of St. Louis,” he said.















            Watch: Overnight time-lapse of the Gateway Arch

A timelapse of the Gateway Arch and redesigned museum entrance photographed on Wednesday, June 6, 2018, from 6 p.m. until 9 a.m. the next morn…




Steinbruegge said the Arch was worthy of the renovations.“It’s very historically significant,” Steinbruegge said. “It is the Gateway to the West.”Krewson encouraged everyone to turn around and look at the view from the museum — the city skyline with the Old Courthouse front and center.“This will become the postcard from St. Louis,” she predicted.


