JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri Gov. Mike Parson says his first meeting with President Donald Trump was a productive one.The state’s new governor, a Republican like Trump, was in Washington Thursday for a lunch with the president and discussions with Cabinet-level officials.In a statement released afterward, Parson said he and a group of eight other governors discussed issues including infrastructure improvement and workforce development.

“It’s important that we discuss best practices to tackle shared challenges and priorities. In order to continue our strong economic growth, we must address our infrastructure needs, ensure our workforce is ready, and remove job-killing regulations,” Parson said.Parson also met with the heads of the U.S. Department of Labor, the Department of Transportation and with senior officials from the U.S. Department of Commerce and the Small Business Administration.Parson took over as Missouri governor on June 1 after the abrupt resignation of scandal-plagued then-Gov. Eric Greitens.
Parson, who had served as lieutenant governor since January 2017, has said fixing the state’s roads and bridges would be a key part of his role as chief executive.And, like his predecessor, he has said bringing more jobs to the state is important.
The visit to Washington comes after Parson has met with federal, state and local officials in Missouri as he ramps up his fledgling administration. On Wednesday, Parson met with representatives from top area employers, including from Mercy Hospital, Schnuck Markets, Boeing and Washington University.He also met for the second time with St. Louis County Executive Steve Stenger.Parson was scheduled to return to Missouri later Thursday.


