It was the second meeting between Stenger and Parson since the governor was sworn in on June 1; Stenger and St. Louis Mayor Lyda Krewson met with Parson in Jefferson City on June 6.Parson said he wanted to “continue the meeting we had in Jeff City.” He said it was “good to hear the chief talk about some of the initiatives that they started, some of the things they are putting in place with crime rates here.”He said they also talked about workforce development and jobs. “We want to be part of this region of the state, and it’s important for me to get out and be here to see what their concerns are and how we can work together.”Asked if there were specific projects that he discussed with Stenger, Parson said that, with regard to workforce development, he was “trying to learn some of the things they are doing good here in this county that we may be able to transfer some of the positive things that are happening maybe to the state level” and vice versa.“There’s a lot of programs out there across the state and I think one of the goals we have is how do we unite these programs, or how do we consolidate them, to where everybody gets use of them. So that’s some of the things we are talking about today.”
Stenger said it was a “very productive meeting” and that he was grateful for Parson’s visit.“One of the things we talked about was Proposition P and all of the various things we’ve done with Proposition P, adding two officers to a vehicle, what we’ve been able to do from a retention standpoint and an attraction standpoint for officers. And we talked about the state of public safety in St. Louis County.”
Parson said the leaders discussed the appointment process for the Bi-State Development Agency board. Stenger and Krewson have previously said they would urge Parson to quickly appoint new Missouri members for the 10-member Bi-State board. Parson said that he would take action on that “in the near future.”Asked for a reaction to the lawsuit by the state Democratic party over his appointment of Mike Kehoe to lieutenant governor, Parson said, “Well, I think they’re wrong. … I think it was important to make that appointment, and I think I had every ability to do that under the constitution and the laws of … Missouri.”Parson is heading to Washington on Thursday to have lunch with a group of governors and President Donald Trump. A reporter asked whether he would consider pulling back the Missouri National Guard from the Mexican border because of the Trump administration’s policy of separating migrant children from their families in detention.“I want to support the security of the border, that’s something I’ve done my entire career … but none of us want to see families split up,” Parson said.He said “more importantly with that meeting tomorrow, I want to talk about some things that are occurring in Missouri. We just met earlier with Boeing, for example. I want to talk about things like that, how do we get these contracts and how do we get jobs here in the states? We’re interested in what we can do, and what he might be doing, infrastructure-wise, in the near future if he can give us a heads-up on that.”


