JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri Gov. Mike Parson says he believes there was no wrongdoing involving a $2.7 million bid being awarded to a company that formerly employed the state’s chief operating officer.In comments Wednesday during a stop in St. Louis, Parson acknowledged the contract for a review of state Medicaid services was being protested, but said he believes it was handled correctly.“I'm not aware of anything that was rigged or anything like that,” Parson said.

At issue is a six-month contract that was awarded earlier this month to McKinsey & Co.  Former Gov. Eric Greitens’ handpicked COO, Drew Erdmann, worked for the global consulting firm before taking on his state duties.But, according to Parson and the Office of Administration, which oversees the purchasing of products and services for the state, Erdmann has no direct role in the state bidding process.“There was no ties between Drew Erdmann and that company still that we're aware of,” Parson said.The contract, first reported by Post-Dispatch columnist Tony Messenger, became fodder for Democrats, who said the bidding process had been “rigged” in order to steer the contract to McKinsey.House Minority Leader Gail McCann Beatty, D-Kansas City, called on Parson to end the contract and fire Erdmann.“To protect the interests of Missouri taxpayers, I respectfully request that you immediately place this contract on hold pending a full and open review into whether standard bidding rules were followed,” McCann Beatty wrote in a letter to Parson Tuesday.The dust-up is one of the first Parson has had to face since taking over for Greitens on June 1 after the former governor resigned amid multiple scandals. McCann Beatty said it would be best for Parson to cut ties with Erdmann.
“Confidence in state government has been shaken by the many misdeeds and missteps of your predecessor, and you are charged with the unenviable yet vital task of restoring Missourians’ trust in their government. That task will be significantly more difficult if they believe the current administration is turning a blind eye to potential malfeasance,” McCann Beatty wrote.In all, five companies bid for the contract, including Accenture, Deloitte Consulting, KPMG and Navigant. McKinsey received perfect scores for its proposed methodology and its team's qualifications, while the other bidders fared poorly in those areas.
McKinsey received a low score when it came to cost. Only one bidder, Accenture, was slightly higher. The other three were less than half of what McKinsey will receive.Navigant is appealing the contract, saying it should be rescinded and rebid. A timeline for the appeal was not available Wednesday, but Karen Boeger, director of the division of purchasing for the Office of Administration said that the percentage of contracts that are successfully overturned is relatively small.In an interview with reporters Wednesday, Office of Administration Commissioner Sarah Steelman was adamant that Erdmann played no role in the contracting process.“There was no outside influences on this bid  or any bid,” Steelman said.She also defended Erdmann for his role in trying to streamline state government.“He’s a huge asset to the state,” she said.Jeremy Kohler of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this report.


