JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri Gov. Mike Parson is making his first trek as the state’s new chief executive to the nation’s capital Thursday.Gov. Mike Parson, who stepped into the vacancy created by the June 1 resignation of fellow Republican Eric Greitens, is scheduled to have lunch with a group of governors and President Donald Trump on Tuesday, as well as discuss transportation and other issues with Cabinet officials, aides told the Post-Dispatch Tuesday.Parson is scheduled to meet with Secretary of Labor R. Alexander Acosta as well as Secretary of Transportation Elaine Chao on Thursday. He also is meeting with top officials in the Department of Commerce and the Small Business Administration, Parson's office said.

Parson, who had served as lieutenant governor since January 2017, has made infrastructure improvement a key talking point in his first two weeks in the governor's office. He has said the state needs to find a solution to help fix its roads and bridges, which could include an increase in the gasoline tax.In addition, he appointed former Sen. Mike Kehoe as lieutenant governor. Kehoe previously served as chairman of the Missouri Highways and Transportation Commission.Members of Missouri's congressional delegation also raised concerns about the impact of growing trade tensions on the state's agricultural exports with Parson during a 30-minute meeting in Jefferson City last week.The visit to Washington comes as at least three governors have vowed to not deploy any National Guard resources to the border until the Trump administration stops separating migrant children from their parents as part of border patrol efforts.
Along with Republican Govs. Larry Hogan of Maryland and Charlie Baker of Massachusetts, Democratic Gov. Gina Raimondo of Rhode Island also has said she would not send troops.In May, acting on a request from the Trump administration, Greitens deployed four Missouri Army National Guard troops and a helicopter to Arizona to help with border protection.Parson's office did not respond to an inquiry about the status of that deployment Tuesday.
The soldiers are expected to return to Missouri mid-summer.The governor's Washington visit will come after a Wednesday trip to St. Louis, where Parson is meeting with representatives from top area employers, including from Mercy Hospital, Schnuck Markets, Boeing and Washington University.He is also scheduled to meet with St. Louis County Executive Steve Stenger and the Regional Business Council.During his 17 months as governor, Greitens traveled to Washington at least five times for meetings with Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and events organized by the Republican Governors Association.


