New Missouri Gov. Mike Parson is keeping department heads and other appointees from his resigned predecessor, Eric Greitens, in place.One department where that continuity in leadership could hold significance is at the Missouri Department of Natural Resources — an agency where Greitens’ tenure heralded some key changes in policy.In its year and a half under Greitens, the DNR emphasized aggressive reduction of backlogged permits, proposed amending or altogether rescinding dozens of environmental regulations, and initiated talks to take over additional enforcement and oversight responsibilities from regional Environmental Protection Agency officials — all while experiencing cuts to the department’s overall size and budget.

Parson intends to meet with DNR officials in the next week or two for his first detailed discussion of agency policy since he was sworn in, according to a DNR spokeswoman. But Director Carol Comer has already been asked to stay at the helm of the department, and no personnel changes are anticipated.Perhaps the defining Greitens-era policy shift at the DNR has been the implementation of “red tape reduction” efforts that have reversed hundreds of stalled permit applications — some years or even decades old — and accelerated the process of granting new ones.“If you haven’t heard the term ‘red tape reduction’ from the state of Missouri, you haven’t been paying attention,” said Kyra Moore, deputy director of the DNR’s Department of Environmental Quality, in remarks at the Midwest Environmental Compliance Conference in Kansas City this April.Regulatory reduction efforts are also reflected by proposed changes — and rescissions — of existing guidelines for air and water quality and for solid waste management. The rationale behind some of the moves is that the policies are obsolete because there are no sources of given pollutants, or that those sources have gone out of business. It was not immediately clear what might happen if certain activities in question were to resume.But the DNR has also reached beyond its own walls and stacks of backlogs to seek change. Last year, new DNR officials reached out to EPA Region 7 officials to “revisit and clarify (their) respective roles” and, in a “significantly different direction from the past,” asked that “Region 7 step back from its routine practice of conducting individual inspections and taking enforcement actions in Missouri.” The agency said it would review all areas where EPA involvement seemed to exceed “a normal audit function.”“We didn’t say, ‘Get the hell out of our state,’ but it was, ‘Hey, we think we can handle this,’” said Ed Galbraith, the DNR’s Division of Environmental Quality director, in April. “All states have these conversations, some are more direct than others. I’m not aware of another state that sent a letter that’s as broad as ours.”Indeed, Missouri is the only one of the four states within EPA Region 7 to have initiated such a conversation, regional EPA administrator Jim Gulliford recently told the Post-Dispatch.Officials from both the DNR and Region 7 met in February to discuss transferring areas of regulatory oversight, with a plan to assess any switches after six months or so. When asked, neither agency could provide details about what specific responsibilities have switched — or will switch — hands.
Both agencies insist that the change will not coincide with reduced environmental protection.“The idea that there’s somehow going to be a race to the bottom doesn’t exist at all,” said Gulliford. “All the federal statutes — Clean Air Act, Clean Water Act, Safe Drinking Water Act — all those things remain the same.... So we have the same requirement in terms of providing assurance to the public that we’re meeting those.”Mixed response 
"It is a thing to be applauded," said Todd Houts, director of Environmental Health and Safety at the University of Missouri, speaking about DNR's red tape reduction efforts at the MECC. "It's been a very different year to be in Missouri."Others, though, have regarded the changes with a sense of caution.“I’m very leery of this process under the Greitens administration. I’m going to be curious to see how Parson handles this going forward,” said Steve Mahfood, a former director of the DNR. “There’s so much going on at any time, that’s it hard to make sense of it.... Is it trying to get rid of outdated regulation or reduce overall regulation? It’s hard to tell.”Of course, all the Greitens-era changes coincided with a reduction of DNR staff and resources. Shrinking through attrition and an eye for “efficiencies,” the size of the agency went from 1,403 full-time employees in early 2017 to a current headcount of 1,329 people. But technical positions have held steady and actually increased slightly, by about one percent.And while environmental policy in the Parson era has yet to take shape, many expect the farmer-turned-governor to be a reliable advocate for agricultural interests. In other areas, some wonder if he may distinguish himself from Greitens’ environmental agenda, particularly if he overrides efforts to divert funding for state parks.But even those critical of some recent changes at the DNR point out that bigger shifts in environmental policy have stemmed from the state Legislature.“2018 will likely go down as one of the most consequential sessions on environmental issues in a long time,” said the Missouri Coalition for the Environment in their legislative summary, listing a half dozen specific bills that will “that will negatively impact our shared environment for years to come.”


