Updated at 6 p.m., after governor’s stop in St. Louis.COLUMBIA, Mo. • Gov. Mike Parson has already signaled a less combative tone than his predecessor, and on Wednesday, he announced another break from ex-Gov. Eric Greitens: that he will use a taxpayer-funded state plane instead of shunning it.“We’ll be using the state plane when we feel like it’s appropriate to use it,” Parson said during a question-and-answer session with reporters at the University of Missouri-Columbia. “We’ll be driving when we can. I think right now there’s nothing more important than traveling the state and trying to find out what are the issues facing all of the communities, all of the people of Missouri.”

On Wednesday, Parson was on the second day of a two-day tour around the state, stopping in Columbia in the morning. He also planned stops at an agricultural research center in Gordonville, Three Rivers College in Sikeston, and the Cortex research hub in St. Louis.It was initially unclear Wednesday how much a state plane was being used for this tour. Parson took over for the embattled Greitens on June 1 after Greitens left office.Greitens, who like Parson is a Republican, largely shunned the state plane during his 17 months as chief executive, instead opting to travel privately. He even directed the state to sell four of its planes.Greitens argued that the move was to save taxpayer money, but questions circulated throughout his tenure about who exactly was paying for his travel. In personal financial disclosure forms filed in May, Greitens wrote that GOP donor Stanley Herzog’s company provided almost $90,000 worth of personal travel and lodging to Greitens last year.Parson said one reason he was willing to use the state plane more often than Greitens was to boost transparency. “We want you to know where I’m going,” Parson said.Parson, after touring Mizzou’s immersive visualization lab on Wednesday, told reporters that two of his priorities as governor would be improving infrastructure and focusing on workforce development.He again signaled his support for a gradual 10-cent increase in the state’s gasoline tax — which is to go before voters this November — and praised legislators for reversing Greitens’ planned $68 million cut to higher education this year.On education, Parson said, “We’re well aware of what we’re going to have to do for the future, because one thing is for sure: We can’t go out here and say we’re going to cut the education arena and all of sudden say we want skilled workers out there.”
It is unclear if Parson’s signaled support for higher education would translate into more dollars for public higher education in the future.Mun Choi, president of the University of Missouri System, said that though the state reversed planned cuts to public universities this year, nationwide, state support for public higher education was trending down.Last week, the Columbia campus announced it was shedding 185 positions — the majority of which were already vacant — and shaving $45 million in costs in preparation for the upcoming fiscal year.
Choi said that in lieu of increased state support, the university system would have to consider ways to increase revenue itself, including through research breakthroughs and expansion of digital learning programs.“We have to be in control of our own destiny,” Choi said. “We have to prepare for a future with less state support — which means, we have to be more entrepreneurial.”Later, Parson met privately with executives of the Cortex innovation and technology hub near the Central West End.Speaking briefly afterward with reporters, he didn’t give any details about what was said in the meeting, but stressed in general terms the need to improve infrastructure in Missouri.“We can’t keep kicking the can down the road,” he said.Kevin McDermott of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this report.@JackSuntrup on Twitterjsuntrup@post-dispatch.com


