JEFFERSON CITY • Missouri’s new Gov. Mike Parson made his debut to state lawmakers on Monday, delivering a brief address light on policy prescriptions. He used the opportunity, however, to set a tone of collegiality in a Capitol consumed by controversy for five months.“In this chamber, we have the opportunity for a fresh start — to elevate the tone of our political discourse, to recommit ourselves to the values that made our system of government the envy of the world,” Parson told lawmakers and other dignitaries. “This does not mean disregarding our beliefs or moderating our positions. It means debating with respect.”Parson, 62, a Republican, entered his second full week on the job amid a cascade of activity after taking over for ex-Gov. Eric Greitens, also a Republican, on June 1. Lawmakers greeted Parson on Monday with cheers and a standing ovation as he approached the House dais.

They also voted to end the special session that lawmakers launched in May to continue their investigation of Greitens. It was still unclear Monday to what extent the House would investigate the former governor’s “dark money,” or the mysterious payments to Greitens’ opponents.“We must be careful not to erode the public’s trust in our system of government for short-term personal gain,” Parson said. “We should expect criticism and understand that some of it is unfair — but we must always take (responsibility) for our own actions. Most of all, we must always remember that we serve the people and the state of Missouri, not the other way around.“Sadly, much of the political turmoil that has engulfed our state is a result of these truths’ being forgotten,” Parson said, referring to Greitens. Many argued that Greitens put personal interests ahead of the state’s when he refused to resign as scandals around him grew.















            Who is Mike Parson? Meet Missouri's lieutenant governor, who steps up to replace Greitens

Mike Parson, 62, a veteran and former rural county sheriff began his career at the Capitol in 2005. 




State agency leaders, the public, the media and others crammed into the House chamber to hear Parson’s address, which lasted about 15 minutes. The speech capped a busy day for Parson’s fledgling administration, and the tone he has so far set drew praise from Republicans and Democrats.Missouri’s congressional delegation filled Parson’s office Monday morning with the kind of hand-shaking, back-slapping bipartisanship that was largely absent during the 17-month tenure of his predecessor.Parson summoned the 10-member congressional delegation to the Capitol for a meeting Monday morning. After the meeting, U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill, one of only three Democrats in the delegation, said that Monday was “not a day to talk about disagreements” she had with Parson, and noted the change in tenor between him and Greitens.“I don’t think that Gov. Greitens saw this as a team effort,” McCaskill said after the meeting. “I think he saw it as that he could always go it alone and that he was wanting to fight everybody. This governor appears that he wants to work with everybody instead of fight everybody.”Eight members of the delegation — everyone except U.S. Reps. William Lacy Clay of St. Louis and Sam Graves of Tarkio — showed up for the rare gathering.When asked if he’d had much contact with Greitens, U.S. Rep. Blaine Luetkemeyer, R-St. Elizabeth, said “no.”
“I’m very hopeful” the relationship with the governor’s office will improve, Luetkemeyer said. “We are already one meeting ahead of both of the previous two governors.”Rep. Vicky Hartzler, R-Harrisonville, said she had Parson’s personal cellphone number when asked how her relationship with Parson would differ from her relationship with Greitens.“I’ve known him for several years,” she said. “I can text him and he will text back quickly. I can call him on his personal cellphone and he calls me back.”
Hartzler said she advocated expanding rural broadband and addressing opioid addiction to the new governor. McCaskill said the group also talked about workforce development and infrastructure.McCaskill also said she was concerned about tariffs being slapped onto Missouri agricultural products amid escalating trade tension between President Donald Trump’s administration and foreign countries.“I certainly expressed concerns for the ag community,” she said, “on this looming trade war and what a devastating impact that could have on Missouri’s economy.”“I’m concerned about the tariffs, especially for our agricultural community here,” U.S. Rep. Ann Wagner, R-Ballwin, said before the meeting.Parson is embarking on a statewide “listening tour” Tuesday and Wednesday, and he is expected to appoint this week members to the state’s Board of Education, which has been unable to meet since January.Rep. Peter Merideth, D-St. Louis, said Parson’s “honeymoon” period would last as long as the state did not “return to politics as usual.”“If he’s willing to work with us on things like health care and infrastructure and education, then I think there’s a possibility this lasts,” Merideth said. “It’s easy to talk about bipartisanship and being willing to work together. But we’re going to have to see it in action.”Merideth also said reforming how the state treated untraceable political donations, or dark money, would be a top election issue in 2018.


