John Nations, who as president and CEO of the Bi-State Development Agency has overseen the Metro transit system for eight years, is quitting this fall.Nations, the longest-serving chief executive in Bi-State history, said Tuesday he’s leaving because he wants more quality time with his family and to pursue his many interests in legal and civic affairs.Nations, 55, insisted that his resignation has nothing to do with Bi-State’s clashes in recent years with St. Louis County government — the agency’s prime funding source — over how to improve security on MetroLink amid a spate of violent crimes on the light-rail system.

However, the squabbling over MetroLink was cited by a longtime member of Bi-State’s board and strong Nations supporter, former St. Louis Mayor Vincent C. Schoemehl Jr.“It is a testament to his leadership that after all of these years, the only thing people complain about relating to Bi-State operations is something Bi-State Development does not control, which is the policing of MetroLink in Missouri,” Schoemehl said.Schoemehl added that he believed Nations was “just worn out” by the “incessant sniping” and “the refusal of St. Louis County to fix the security” issue.County Executive Steve Stenger, who has criticized Nations in the past, took a diplomatic approach Tuesday, saying he wanted to focus now on the agency’s future.“I really don’t know that my opinion on how he handled his job really adds anything at this point,” Stenger said. He said he wished Nations well but also said “it’s going to be good to have a fresh perspective.”He added that when he and St. Louis Mayor Lyda Krewson meet jointly Wednesday with the new Missouri governor, Mike Parson, in Jefferson City, they will urge him to quickly appoint new Missouri members for the 10-member Bi-State board.“MetroLink security is going to be the top item on the agenda” for the meeting, Stenger said, referring to the request for new board members.Stenger and Krewson last summer sent Parson’s predecessor, Eric Greitens, lists of nominees to fill a board vacancy and to replace Missouri members whose terms technically expired. But Greitens never acted on them. Schoemehl would be among those replaced.Krewson could not be reached for comment Tuesday.Stenger’s opponent in the Aug. 7 Democratic primary, Mark Mantovani, said Nations’ resignation is “regrettable and a predictable reaction to the lack of cooperation” from Stenger on MetroLink matters. Schoemehl is a supporter of Mantovani’s candidacy.In response, Stenger said Mantovani’s comment amounted to “petty politics” and pointed out that it was he, Krewson and St. Clair County Board Chairman Mark Kern who took the initiative last year to form a joint task force to improve policing on MetroLink. Stenger added that Metro itself is ultimately responsible for light-rail security.
Metro officials have criticized St. Louis County police, who oversee the task force, for not presenting a more visible presence on MetroLink trains. County officials point out that they have more than doubled the number of police officers assigned to MetroLink and say that security has improved.There also have been other flashpoints, including the county prosecutor’s refusal to prosecute fare violation tickets written up by Metro security officers.Nations, a lawyer by training and occupation, took over as Bi-State’s CEO in 2010, resigning as Chesterfield’s mayor to do so.He was hired after running a successful campaign for a county sales tax increase for Metro earlier that year, producing the first infusion of new transit revenue in 15 years. Board members cited that as indicative of his ability to build partnerships in the community.
As CEO, Nations runs a $400 million-a-year operation with about 2,500 employees, 400 buses, a light-rail system with 37 stations, a paratransit van service, a general-aviation airport and various other endeavors.Among other things, the agency under his watch opened several new transit centers which act as regional hubs for bus and MetroLink service.Nations also noted that Bi-State at the request of area leaders has formed the St. Louis Regional Freightway, an organization pushing to build on the metro area’s importance in the freight industry.He also cited what he called “clean financial audits” and management performance audits in recent years with no criticisms. He also cited the agency’s getting private entities to kick in part of the cost of a new MetroLink station planned for the city’s Cortex area.Former U.S. Rep. Jerry Costello, D-Belleville, said Nations “by far” has been Bi-State’s best chief executive during Costello’s 30 years of working with the agency. Costello’s lobbying firm currently does work for the agency.But as at various other transit systems around the country, ridership has declined in recent years.To deal with that, Metro under Nations began a study of its bus operation expected to result in a major revamping, including the use of vans and ride-hailing services to replace low-ridership fixed bus routes in some suburban areas.Schoemehl said Tuesday that he and some other board members in an unsuccessful effort to convince Nations to stay offered to support boosting his pay above the current $325,000, which already makes him one of the area’s highest-salaried governmental officials.Schoemehl also said they were ready “to start the clock on a new five-year contract.” Nations’ current contract doesn’t expire until the end of 2020.Christine Byers of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this report.


