Eric Greitens launched his campaign for governor in 2015, vowing to root out public corruption in Jefferson City.He took aim at his predecessor Jay Nixon for his handling of the Ferguson unrest, saying he could have ended the violence in two days.He criticized efforts to get state funding for a soccer stadium in St. Louis, calling it "corporate welfare."

















            St. Louis, state leaders react to governor's resignation



And he took aim at the powerful low-income tax credit industry, saying it was time to end "politics as usual."Combative to the end, the former Navy SEAL insisted Tuesday he had committed no crimes — and said "history and God" would "bring justice."Here is Eric Greitens, in his own words:• “I want to say now, to the corrupt insiders who have been working Jefferson City for decades to maximize their personal profit rather than to serve the people, your days are numbered! I will defeat you, I will expose your lies, I will root out your corruption, and I will see you out of the people’s Capitol, even if in sight of the statue of Thomas Jefferson I have to throw you down the steps of the Capitol myself!” — Greitens jumps into Missouri gov race with money advantage; Brunner on deck  [Sept. 27, 2015]• “Oh, John Brunner, oh my God, you are such a weasel! Are you going to meet tomorrow or not?” [from a recorded conversation with John Brunner, who also was running for the GOP gubernatorial nomination] — 'Oh my God, you are such a weasel!' and other things pols say to each other behind the scenes  [Nov. 25, 2015]• "The great tragedy of Ferguson is if we'd had a leader who'd shown up with any kind of command presence and courage and calm and clarity, we could have had peace by the second night." — Missouri governor put to the test by St. Louis protests [July 2016 debate]















            Post-Dispatch coverage of the Greitens affair scandal

From Greitens' initial statement to the legal battle, read the Post-Dispatch coverage of the governor's scandal. 




• “To be very clear, I have completely ruled out state funding for stadiums. … We are not going to use money from the people of the state of Missouri for what I believe is corporate welfare. We’ve got far too many core priorities of government that have to be invested in.” — Greitens: 'I have completely ruled out state funding for stadiums' [Jan. 2, 2017]• “We are fighting to bring more jobs to the people of Missouri. Some career politicians failed to do their jobs and then went home. That’s wrong. We’re canceling their summer vacations and calling a special session to get this done.” — Missouri governor calling lawmakers back for special session [May 18, 2017]• “We promised that we were going to clean up the culture of corruption in Jefferson City. As governor, I will always hold myself and my team to the highest possible standard.” — Greitens pledges end to 'politics as usual,' and shows it with his first official act [Jan. 10, 2017]
• “The organization that you're referring to [A New Missouri] is one that I have no day-to-day responsibilities with. It's an organization that's separate from the governor's office. It does represent the interests of thousands of people around the state of Missouri who care about seeing our priorities get passed.” — Greitens: 'I have no day-to-day responsibilities' with nonprofit attacking Republican senator [April 24, 2017]• "We zeroed out this failing program, and saved tens of millions of dollars. No. More. Giveaways. … We're here to work with people across Missouri, on both sides of the aisle, to do what works. But let's be clear: Politics as usual is over." — Greitens, appointees move to withhold controversial low income development tax credits  [Nov. 17, 2017]• “This was a consensual relationship. There was no blackmail, there was no violence, there was no threat of violence, there was no threat of blackmail, there was no threat of using a photograph for blackmail. All of those things are false.” — Greitens: 'No blackmail,' 'no violence' in affair  [Jan. 22, 2018]















            Post-Dispatch coverage of Greitens, campaign issues and The Mission Continues

Greitens, a former Navy Seal, founded The Mission Continues in 2007. His alleged use of a fundraising list from the charity is under investigation. 





• “Today prosecutors dropped the false charges against me. This is a great victory, and it has been a long time coming. This experience has been humbling, and I have emerged from it a changed man.” — Invasion of privacy charge against Greitens dropped; governor calls it 'great victory'  [May 15, 2018]• "I know I am not perfect, but I have not broken any laws nor committed offenses worthy of this treatment. For those who would be moved to vengeance, let us allow history and God to bring justice." — Embattled Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens resigns; 'resolution' reached in St. Louis [May 29, 2018]More• Embattled Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens resigns; 'resolution' reached in St. Louis• Trouble lurked between the lines of Greitens' perfect story• Meet Missouri's next governor: Mike Parson• Messenger: Greitens goes out the way he came in, haunted by specter of dark money• Sultan: It should have been enough• Political leaders react to the resignation


