WASHINGTON • A Washington-based Democratic political action committee began running ads in Missouri just before Memorial Day that try to link a Republican candidate for U.S. Senate — state Attorney General Josh Hawley — with troubled Gov. Eric Greitens.Greitens’ sudden resignation announcement Tuesday hasn’t prompted the PAC to pull the ads. Democrats argue that the governor’s decision doesn’t wipe away their claim that Hawley is part of a corrupt and distant Republican leadership in Jefferson City.Republicans believe that any guilt-by-association attacks will go away with Greitens, whose resignation is effective Friday. They assert that Hawley, the leading contender to face U.S. Sen. Claire McCaskill in November, will now be able to more aggressively shift his efforts to the Democratic incumbent and her voting record in the Senate behind a more unified Republican Party.

Regardless of either side’s spin, the post-Greitens landscape will re-focus on the Senate race as the pre-eminent political story in Missouri.

