Since January, Greitens’ survival has dominated headlines and framed most political talk in the state, even though McCaskill, Hawley and outside groups have begun a campaign in which tens — even hundreds — of millions of dollars likely will be spent between now and Nov. 6.“I don’t think the governor staying in office spelled doom for Hawley, but it didn’t help either,” said Andy Blunt, who ran his father, Roy Blunt’s, successful 2016 Senate race in the state. “November is a long way off politically, and now there is plenty of time for the party to come together and for Eric Greitens to be a thing of the past. Everyone is in the same boat now and rowing in the same direction.”But Chris Hayden, a top consultant to Roy Blunt’s 2016 opponent, then-Missouri Secretary of State Jason Kander, said Greitens’ resignation made Hawley the leading face of a Republican Party that has been rocked by corruption. He said Democrats would continue to argue that Hawley did not act in his official capacity to legally investigate Greitens until it became politically safe to do so.“Jeff City is just as corrupt — it is really worse because now you have had a governor resign because of how he has acted,” Hayden, communications director for the Senate Majority PAC, which is running the ads attacking Hawley and Greitens. “Josh Hawley is caught in the middle of this. There is a cloud over him, and that cloud is corruption in Jefferson City.”Dave Robertson, head of the Department of Political Science at the University of Missouri-St.-Louis, said that “Greitens supporters will not view Hawley as the second coming of Greitens, but Democratic ads against Hawley will portray him as the second coming of Greitens to everyone else.“So to the extent that Greitens matters in November, he doesn’t do much to energize Hawley’s base, but does a lot to mobilize McCaskill’s base,” Robertson said in a tweeted response to Post-Dispatch questions. “That’s depending on how much Greitens matters at all – an open question.”Republicans say they hope Democrats continue to attack Hawley through Greitens because it indicates they have nothing else on the first-term Republican attorney general, who is favored by the state’s GOP establishment. Hawley faces a multiple-candidate August primary field that includes ex-libertarian Austin Petersen and ex-Air Force pilot Tony Monetti, who have raised the most money among a field of lesser-known candidates.
“This focuses the race back on Claire McCaskill,” said Bob Salera, a spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial Campaign Committee, which is expected to weigh in with its own heavy advertising campaign to support Hawley. “Her allies have been desperate to change the subject to anything. They tried to latch onto the Greitens thing to replicate the luck they had in 2012 with Todd Akin.”That was a reference to McCaskill’s 2012 Republican opponent, whose comments on rape overturned a race in which polls showed Akin had a good chance of unseating the state’s senior senator.The incumbent McCaskill was uncharacteristically quiet in her reaction to Greitens’ resignation, saying only that she was looking forward to working with Lt. Gov. Mike Parson, who will replace Greitens on Friday.But other state Democrats, arguing that Hawley did not begin his own investigation of Greitens’ campaign committees until months after acknowledging wrongdoing, said Hawley’s own lack of commitment to the job — and his ambition to move up — would remain an attack line long after Greitens is gone.
“Hawley is still a typical politician and a weak candidate, with a record of failing in the job he currently holds,” former state Democratic Chairman Roy Temple said. “I’m not sure renewed scrutiny of his candidacy will prove helpful over the long term.”Though Republican legislative leaders in Jefferson City were among Greitens’ harshest critics, state Democrats were stressing on Wednesday policy issues on which Greitens and Republican leaders generally agreed, in an apparent effort to keep Greitens on the board as an overall campaign issue.In a statement Tuesday after Greitens’ announcement, Missouri Democratic Party Chairman Stephen Webber said legislative Republicans “were wrong to follow Greitens’ lead” on issues such as the minimum wage and health care.But Missouri Republican political operative Gregg Keller said that “Claire McCaskill was a real and substantive loser” with Greitens’ resignation.Keller, a strong Greitens critic, recently warned fellow Republicans that Greitens’ ongoing drama was “making it more difficult for us to maintain control of the U.S. Senate.” But now that Greitens is leaving, Keller predicted Wednesday, attempts by the Democrats to continue using him against Hawley will backfire.“I think that’s a tactical mistake by the Democrats. They can talk all they want about this former elected official who is no longer on the scene, but I expect Josh to go out there and talk about tax reform” and the strong economy, he said.For his part, Hawley received on Wednesday a key endorsement in Springfield from Missouri Right to Life, an anti-abortion group.Kevin McDermott of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this story from St. Louis.


