Parson did not take questions from the reporters gathered outside his second-floor office. But in a statement released Wednesday afternoon, Parson said:“We are taking every step and working around the clock to ensure Missouri state government does not miss a beat throughout this transition. My commitment to all Missourians is to listen to them and work together to advance the interests of our great state.”Among those meeting with Parson were House Speaker Todd Richardson, R-Poplar Bluff; Senate President Pro Tem Ron Richard, R-Joplin; and Senate Majority Floor Leader Mike Kehoe, R-Jefferson City.Richardson said Parson, a 62-year-old former sheriff and state lawmaker from Bolivar, was invited to address a joint session of the House and Senate on June 11.“We’re pleased that there is an open line of communication,” Richardson said.Richard said the legislative leaders were sharing staff with Parson to help him navigate the transition.“It’s not a happy time. It’s a time where we just need to move on,” Richard said. “We’re going to try and help make that as easy as we can.”In addition to meeting with the leaders, Parson reached out to all cabinet members. Parson plans to hold a meeting with the cabinet early next week.On Thursday, Parson will receive a briefing from the Missouri Department of Public Safety’s State Emergency Management Agency and finalize the details of the swearing-in ceremony.Amid the talk of the transition from Greitens to Parson were discussions of whether to continue pursuing an investigation by the House into Greitens’ 2015 extramarital affair and his use of a fundraising list from his former charity, The Mission Continues.Greitens’ spokesman, Parker Briden, said the governor was working in the Capitol on Wednesday and would move out of the governor’s mansion by Friday.Greitens, 44, had been scheduled to testify Monday before a special House committee that was charged with recommending whether to impeach the governor. A Cole County judge also had ruled that his legal staff had to release fundraising information from a dark money nonprofit used to promote Greitens’ agenda.Missouri Attorney General Josh Hawley also is investigating Greitens for his fundraising practices.“Our office intends to pursue and conclude its investigations in an orderly fashion,” Hawley spokeswoman Mary Compton said.With the governor’s 16-month tenure nearly finished, the woman who accused Greitens of taking a picture of her while she was nude or semi-nude issued a statement through her attorney.“My client and I are thankful to all of the individuals involved that honored my client’s privacy by not publishing her name and other identifying information. Our gratitude goes out to the media, the House committee, the St. Louis circuit attorney and the special prosecutor among others. Now that the Governor has resigned, I hope my client can go back to being a private citizen and put this matter behind her,” attorney Scott Simpson of St. Charles wrote.In a memo issued Tuesday to members of the House Republican caucus, GOP leaders said the special session scheduled to determine impeachment would be shut down.
“The decision of Gov. Greitens to step down means we will no longer need to proceed with the special session, and the investigative committee will wrap up its work in short order,” the memo notes. “We know there are still many other questions to be answered, and we will devote as much time as necessary to ensure you are fully aware of where we are, and what happens next.”Richardson told reporters he was unsure about the status of the subpoenas ordering Greitens’ attorneys to release documents. “I don’t have an answer for you,” Richardson said.He added there were no negotiations between House leaders and the governor’s office to close down the House investigation in exchange for Greitens’ resignation.Although Richard was among the voices calling for Greitens to step down when word of his extramarital affair surfaced in January, Richard said he was focused on getting state government back on track.“There is no happy time on a resignation,” Richard said.Among those shuttling in and out of the lieutenant governor’s office was former state Treasurer Sarah Steelman, who was Greitens’ pick to serve as commissioner of the Office of Administration.Steelman would not comment on whether she was planning to stay on board after Greitens leaves to help with the transition. “I just don’t feel like it’s appropriate,” Steelman told the Post-Dispatch.
After their meeting with Parson, Richard and Richardson put their signatures on legislation approved by lawmakers during the spring session. More than 140 bills now go to the governor’s office for his consideration.Greitens will have two days to take action on the legislation before he leaves office.Richardson said he was not concerned about any last-minute vetoes being issued by the outgoing governor.“I have not had a direct conversation, but I am not worried about it,” Richardson said.Jack Suntrup of the Post-Dispatch contributed to this report.• Embattled Missouri Gov. Eric Greitens resigns; 'resolution' reached in St. Louis• St. Louis prosecutor drops computer tampering charge against Greitens• Trouble lurked between the lines of Greitens' perfect story• Meet Missouri's next governor: Mike Parson• Messenger: Greitens goes out the way he came in, haunted by specter of dark money• Sultan: It should have been enough• Greitens said it: Memorable quotes that marked his candidacy, governorship• Political leaders react to the resignation


