On Wednesday, Judge Jon Beetem ordered pizza.It was the morning after.After the sudden resignation of Gov. Eric Greitens.

After the Cole County Circuit Court judge had ordered the soon-to-be former governor’s campaign and dark-money committee to produce documents sought by the Missouri House committee investigating Greitens’ various misdeeds.After the Missouri political world was turned upside down.On Tuesday, many in the Capitol were pointing to Beetem’s ruling as the whiff of air that collapsed Greitens’ house of cards.“Time is of the essence,” Beetem wrote in ordering that documents for both the Greitens for Missouri campaign and A New Missouri nonprofit be produced by June 1. Those documents could well have showed further ethics violations. They could have unmasked private donors. They most certainly would have helped the House make its case for impeachment.Instead, Greitens walked away.Beetem, meanwhile, walked right back into the fray, about 8:35 in the morning, pulling out his credit card to order pizza for a lunch later that day with family law attorneys. They were having a meeting to talk about ways to improve the dispensation of justice in cases that are generally fraught with emotion, the sort of cases that occupy much more of Beetem’s time than those that garner political headlines.“The intersection of the law and family is never pretty,” Beetem said.Before lunch, though, Beetem was pulled right back into the Greitens saga, asked to make a ruling on the case that started it all.Before the governor was charged with two felonies, before he admitted an affair and the House found evidence of behavior that was nonconsensual, before all the impeachment talk, there was a simple Sunshine Law complaint.It was filed by Clayton attorney Mark Pedroli in December, on behalf of fellow attorney Ben Sansone and The Sunshine Project. It alleges that Greitens and his staffers violated open records law by using a phone app that destroys text messages before a government official can determine whether they need to be retained.
On Wednesday, as St. Louis Circuit Attorney Kim Gardner was dropping a felony charge of computer tampering against the governor, Pedroli pressed his case.“We want to go forward,” Pedroli said in a telephone conference call on the case. Beetem let two reporters into his chambers to listen to the call. “There is no reason to delay,” Pedroli said.Except for one.As of Friday night or first thing Saturday morning, Bob Thompson, the Bryan Cave attorney representing the governor’s office in the case, will have a new client. Lt. Gov. Mike Parson will be sworn in as governor, and Thompson might receive new marching orders.That shouldn’t stop the fact-finding that is part of the discovery process, Pedroli argued, appealing to a judge who just the day before had run out of patience with delay tactics.
“It’s been my theory all along that Confide was used to do public business,” Pedroli said. He referenced the Greitens’ campaign and A New Missouri. Like the House investigators, he wants to see documents from those organizations that could help him prove his case.In the end, that case might be made or broken based on what is on the phones of the governor and his staff members. To that end, he asked Beetem Wednesday to take steps to preserve those phones.Thompson protested. That has been the governor’s position pretty much anytime he is asked a question, from reporters, lawmakers or attorneys.“They have refused to answer anything and everything, particularly about the phones,” Pedroli said.Beetem drew a line in the sand.He asked Pedroli to draft orders requiring the governor’s office to confirm the names and phone numbers of everybody in his office who used Confide, and another order requiring a forensic expert or “special master” to take mirror images of those phones to preserve any evidence.Pedroli said he would have them drafted within hours.It was the day after, and time was of the essence.


