ST. LOUIS • Embattled Gov. Eric Greitens' surprise decision to resign the office he's held for less than two years prompted swift reaction from officials throughout Missouri on Tuesday night. But one response from St. Louis Mayor Lyda Krewson, in her own words, "missed the mark."I thank the governor for his service. I know this was a hard decision. My hope is that we get back to working for the people and doing the business of the state.— Mayor Lyda Krewson (@LydaKrewson) May 29, 2018

A tweet Krewson sent shortly after the governor's announcement thanking him for his service sparked backlash from St. Louisans and other Democratic officials who called her statement tone-deaf and unnecessarily tepid, citing the many scandals surrounding Greitens, including accusations of sexual and physical assault.

With all due respect, why are you thanking him? This is a governor who is under investigation for sexual assualt and blackmail, and who has never missed a chance to insult and trample on the City of St. Louis since his term began.— Jonah Klein-Barton (@Klein_Barton) May 29, 2018

It was a St. Louis hairdresser with whom Greitens admitted to having a consensual affair in January. But her testimony both in court and before an investigative committee in the Missouri Legislature told a different story about a far more disturbing relationship. Among her statements – deemed credible by the GOP-led committee of legislators – was an allegation that before running for office as a squeaky clean family man, Greitens took a nude picture of the woman without her consent and blackmailed her with it, before coercing her to perform oral sex.That accusation was at the center of a now scuttled felony invasion of privacy case, though a special prosecutor continues to investigate the matter. Greitens also faced a second St. Louis charge for felony data-tampering, involving his alleged use of a charity donor list for political fundraising, that was dropped on Wednesday.Taking away our hard fought min wage, signing SB 43, vetoing HCB 3, trying to dismantle historic and all tax credits. I haven’t even got to the new shit! Smh https://t.co/NrcHMhgcbP— Bruce Franks Jr (@brucefranksjr) May 29, 2018

Krewson's critics pointed to both charges, as well as Greitens' policy record as as conservative governor and his often inflammatory rhetoric about St. Louis, which he has deemed "the most dangerous city in the United States of America" and an "abortion sanctuary city."Many questioned why she would praise the service of someone who took action to reverse the city's long-sought minimum wage increase for St. Louis workers, something Krewson supported.
I look forward to working with Governor @mikeparson for the betterment of our city and state— Mayor Lyda Krewson (@LydaKrewson) May 29, 2018

Roughly two hours after sending her first tweet, the mayor tried again, saying she looked forward to working with incoming Gov. Mike Parson.It wasn't until the wee hours of Wednesday morning that the mayor offered a condemnation of Missouri's scandalized chief executive on both Facebook and Twitter. Her initial comment was well-intended to "begin the healing needed from the inexcusable, embarrassing and disgusting actions of Governor Eric Greitens," she said, but admitted she probably "should have left civility at the door."
It is said that the road to hell is paved with good intention. Yesterday, I posted a tweet intended to begin the healing needed from inexcusable, embarrassing, and disgusting actions of Governor Eric Greitens. It was well intended but missed the mark!  (1/4)— Mayor Lyda Krewson (@LydaKrewson) May 30, 2018

I probably should have left civility at the door and said, thank goodness Governor Greitens got the message that violating the trust of his family, his supporters, his staff and the voters is inexcusable.  I should have said, it’s about time and overdue. (2/4)— Mayor Lyda Krewson (@LydaKrewson) May 30, 2018

But I considered the victims—the woman whom he assaulted - is wife and children - his many supporters who believed in him - and the people of the State of Missouri, who rightly expected that their Governor would comport himself honorably. (3/4)— Mayor Lyda Krewson (@LydaKrewson) May 30, 2018

Let there be no doubt, I condemn Eric Greitens behavior.  I do not celebrate his downfall, but I am hopeful that we can begin  a new chapter with Governor Mike Parson. (4/4)— Mayor Lyda Krewson (@LydaKrewson) May 30, 2018

She also clarified that she had considered the victims involved in the unfolding scandals, including the woman who said Greitens hit and sexually assaulted her, as well as Greitens' wife and two children."Let there be no doubt, I condemn Eric Greitens' behavior. I do not celebrate his downfall, but I am hopeful that we can begin a new chapter with Governor Mike Parson," she said.


