WASHINGTON • Reaction to Gov. Eric Greitens' resignation from other Missouri politicians was immediate, with fellow Republican and United States Sen. Roy Blunt saying "the governor made the best decision for his family and the state.""I look forward to Gov. (Michael) Parson's leadership and will do everything I can to be helpful," Blunt said in a statement issued by his office just minutes after Greitens' stunning announcement. He was referring to Lt. Gov. Mike Parson, who will take over the governorship after Greitens resigns, effective on Friday. Rep. Blaine Luetkemeyer, R-St. Elizabeth, said that he had been "disturbed by allegations surrounding Gov. Greitens over the past few months.

"This has been a distraction for our entire state and undermined his ability to lead," Luetkemeyer said. "I am hopeful we can quickly put this behind us and Missouri can move forward under new leadership."Rep. Ann Wagner, R-Ballwin, echoed her colleagues, saying that Greitens made the right decision for Missouri and for his family, and that "now is the time for us to move forward." Blunt had not called for Greitens' resignation, but his Senate colleague, Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., had. But McCaskill reacted more cautiously in the immediate aftermath of Greitens' resignation, not referring to Greitens at all in a statement issued by her office."I wish Lt. Gov. Parson the best," McCaskill said. "I look forward to working with him."Rep. William Lacy Clay, D-St. Louis, would have no immediate comment, his spokesman, Steve Engelhardt, told the Post-Dispatch. Greitens' announcement sparked immediate, and harsh, comment from outside groups attempting to influence Missouri's Senate race.McCaskill is up for re-election in November, and Attorney General Josh Hawley, a Republican who had also called for Greitens to resign, is the leading GOP contender to face her.Chris Hayden, a spokesman for the Democrats' Senate Majority PAC, again called on Hawley to refund $50,000 in donations from Greitens' political committees that Hawley received for his successful 2016 attorney general's race. He said Greitens' resignation won't stop his group from arguing that Hawley was late in investigating allegations against the governor.
But Bob Salera, a spokesman for the National Republican Senatorial Committee, a GOP group expected to also spend heavily in Missouri's Senate campaign, said Greitens' resignation will remove a distraction from voters being able to focus on McCaskill's "abysmal voting record.""McCaskill has been desperate to change the subject, but no distractions from her or anyone else is going to change that," he said.More
