JEFFERSON CITY • While a strong majority of the House and Senate agreed to a special session to consider impeaching the governor, a smattering of Republicans and Democrats did not add their names to the effort.In the Senate, three Republicans and one Democrat did not sign the petition for the special session, which is scheduled to start May 18 and last 30 days.In the House, 16 Republicans and seven Democrats, including several from the St. Louis area, were holdouts.

The four senators who didn’t sign the petition are:Sen. Dan Brown, R-RollaSen. Brian Munzlinger, R-WilliamstownSen. Wayne Wallingford, R-Cape GirardeauSen. Maria Chappelle-Nadal, D-University CityNone — including Chappelle-Nadal, who said Lt. Gov. Mike Parson would be worse than Gov. Eric Greitens — has called on the governor to resign, according to the Columbia Missourian.The House members are:Rep. Rick Brattin, R-HarrisonvilleRep. Wanda Brown, R-LincolnRep. Gary Cross, R-Lee’s SummitRep. Paul Curtman, R-WashingtonRep. Chris Dinkins, R-AnnapolisRep. Lyndall Fraker, R-MarshfieldRep. Keith Frederick, R-RollaRep. Mike Kelley, R-LamarRep. Andrew McDaniel, R-DeeringRep. Mike Moon, R-Ash GroveRep. Jim Neely, R-CameronRep. Randy Pietzman, R-TroyRep. Jeff Pogue, R-SalemRep. Holly Rehder, R-SikestonRep. Bryan Spencer, R-WentzvilleRep. Bill White, R-JoplinRep. Michael Butler, D-St. LouisRep. Pat Conway, D-St. JosephRep. Brandon Ellington, D-Kansas CityRep. Jay Mosley, D-FlorissantRep. Stacey Newman, D-St. LouisRep. Joshua Peters, D-St. LouisRep. Clem Smith, D-Velda Village HillsAll of the Republicans who didn’t sign have either not commented on the governor’s situation or have advocated waiting until Greitens’ trial in St. Louis Circuit Court on felony invasion of privacy charges has finished. Of the Democrats, only Butler, Ellington and Newman have publicly said Greitens should resign.Chappelle-Nadal said that, although she had been critical of Greitens, she believed his trial should play out before any decisions should be made.“You still have a right to due process,” she said, adding that, in her view, the situation mirrored that in Washington at the moment. “I don’t want to see a governor like Parson. People at home say, ‘We can’t stand (President Donald) Trump, but (Vice President Mike) Pence would be worse.’ ”She said that, on a “human level,” she could relate to what the governor might be going through: After she said on Facebook that Trump should be “assassinated” and the Senate censured her, she felt isolated.
“I know what it means to have everyone out to get you,” she said.Ellington said the process to impeach the governor should have already begun, based on Greitens’ being charged with two felonies.“If the body really felt that the charges were as serious as their political posturing,” he wrote in a statement posted to Twitter, “then why are we not dealing with the issue during regular session?”
Others approached the situation from a different angle.Spencersaid the people he represented were telling him the efforts to possibly impeach Greitens were a “railroad job.”“My constituents in my area told me the special session was a waste of taxpayer dollars,” he said. “They’re not happy elected officials are taking away their vote.”Rehder said she needed to hear Greitens’ side before considering next steps.“We must not lose sight of our American judicial system,” she said in a statement. “Both parties will be heard in court starting next week.”Newman said she would have signed the petition but was out of town for medical reasons.Butler said he would have signed but was indisposed.


