First, he blamed Democrats.When news broke in January that Gov. Eric Greitens had hidden an extramarital affair from voters for more than two years and may have broken the law by taking a seminude photo of the woman, the Republican lashed out at the former chairman of the Democratic Party in Missouri, Roy Temple.Within days, the former Navy SEAL set his sights on some new targets.

Greitens and his dwindling band of supporters blamed Republicans, including Lt. Gov. Mike Parson. They blamed developers. Lobbyists. Political consultants. A “reckless” prosecutor. The liberal media. George Soros.This week, it’s Satan’s turn.How convenient.The embattled governor is facing a criminal investigation in the city of St. Louis, a fact-finding inquiry by a State House committee that could lead to impeachment, an investigation by Attorney General Josh Hawley into the governor’s relationship with his former nonprofit, The Mission Continues, and an ongoing lawsuit over his potential violation of open records laws by using a phone app that destroys text messages.As pressure builds for him to resign, Greitens’ campaign bought about $50,000 worth of radio ads in Missouri to defend his name by blaming a new demon for his downfall.Like the Church Lady from “Saturday Night Live” fame, the governor has found his foil.“Even Satan’s own lawyers from The Satanic Temple are suing Greitens,” the ad’s narrator says.From what I remember from the 1997 movie “The Devil’s Advocate” starring Al Pacino, Satan’s lawyers were pretty good.But in real life, Lucifer doesn’t have his own law firm.In fact, those who belong to The Satanic Temple don’t actually worship the Christian version of Beelzebub. They are nontheistic secularists mostly, says Lucien Greaves, the Salem, Mass.-based co-founder and spokesman for The Satanic Temple.
“We don’t believe in a personal Satan,” Greaves told me Thursday. “We do believe that everybody should take responsibility for their own actions.”That last statement was a not-so-veiled shot at Missouri’s governor.Greaves said it’s ridiculous that Greitens is trying to take advantage of the fact that The Satanic Temple has sued Missouri over an anti-abortion law, alleging that the law’s requirement that women read a pamphlet stating that life begins at conception violates their religious beliefs.
“Our lawsuit isn’t about attacking the character of the governor,” Greaves says. “It’s about asserting our religious liberty in the face of a policy dispute.”But about that character.Now that his organization is being used by Greitens to somehow rally support for the governor, Greaves has a few things he’d like to get off his chest.“He can’t blame anybody but himself (for his problems),” Greaves says. “This is some pretty low-level pandering. He’s trying to position his current troubles as part of an over-arching conspiracy against him. He’s lost the moral high ground to anybody who actually looks at the facts, and he tries to regain it by asserting moral superiority against The Satanic Temple.”For the record, Greaves doesn’t necessarily have a problem with Greitens having multiple sexual partners while he was married. His organization’s commitment to individual liberty means that “poly-amorous relationships” are not necessarily out of bounds.But that respect for individual liberty goes both ways, Greaves says. The crime with which Greitens is charged — invasion of privacy for taking a photo without consent — well, that wouldn’t be accepted in The Satanic Temple.“That’s well outside of any activity we would condone,” Greaves said. “The people of Missouri deserve better.”So there you have it. The co-founder of a religion named after a fallen angel says his organization has staked out higher moral ground than the governor of Missouri.Isn’t that special.


